<BODY>
<HEADLINE> IMF Team Starts Discussion With Pak Officials </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ISLAMABAD, April 3 (Xinhua) -- An International Monetary Fund (
IMF) delegation has started discussions with senior officials of
Pakistan's Ministry of Finance, official sources said Monday.
</P>
<P>
The five-member delegation, led by the Fund's Assistant
Director for Middle East Sena Eken, arrived here on Monday to hold
talks with the Pakistani government on replacing the Enhanced
Structural Adjustment Facility (ESAF) loans with Poverty Reduction
and Growth Program (PRGP).
</P>
<P>
The IMF announced the PRGP on the eve of the new millenium and
had withdrawn its various existing programs, specially for the
developing and underdeveloped countries.
</P>
<P>
The existing ESAF program in Pakistan will be replaced with the
PRGP, Pakistan's Finance Minister Shaukat Aziz told media on
Sunday.
</P>
<P>
Under the ESAF, the IMF pledged assistance of 1.56 billion U.S.
dollars to Pakistan and the third tranche of 280 million dollars
was suspended after Pakistan went for unclear tests in May 1998.
</P>
<P>
Representatives of the World Bank and the Asian Development
Bank will also take part in the talks between the IMF and the
Pakistani government, the sources said.
</P>
<P>
During its 10-day stay in Pakistan, the IMF delegation will
also review the performance of various governmental departments of
the country including the Revenue Division, they said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
