<HEADLINE> U.N. Court Prepares Trial of Rwandan Genocide Suspect </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
DAR ES SALAAM, April 3 (Xinhua) -- The Prosecutor of the
International Criminal Tribunal for Rwanda (ICTR) has said the
preparation for trial of genocide suspect Jean-Bosco Barayagwiza
is underway.
</P>
<P>
According to Monday sources from Arusha where ICTR locates,
Carla Del Ponte said in a statement from the Hague that the ICTR
welcomed the Appeals Court decision allowing the case to continue.
</P>
<P>
"No date has yet been fixed for the start of trial," she said,
however, discussions will resume between the prosecution and
defense on issues of evidence and procedure in order to start the
trial as soon as possible.
</P>
<P>
The Appeals Court last Friday reversed its decision to release
Barayagwiza, former Rwandan director of Political Affairs in the
Ministry of Foreign Affairs.
</P>
<P>
Barayagwiza will remain in the ICTR detention facilities in
northern Tanzanian town of Arusha.
</P>
<P>
It was the first time that the ICTR Appeals Court has agreed to
revise a decision, normally considered to be final.
</P>
<P>
On November 3 last year, the Appeal Court ordered Barayagwiza's
 immediate release on the grounds that his rights had been
repeatedly violated during his initial detention in Cameroon and
after his transfer to the U.N. prison in Arusha.
</P>
<P>
The initial decision was based on the fact that Barayagwiza was
held for 19 months in Cameroon without being informed of the
charges against him, while the ICTR provisional detention is not
supposed to exceed 90 days.
</P>
<P>
That decision led the Rwandan government to suspend its
cooperation with the ICTR till February when the ICTR Prosecutor
applied for a review of the decision on the ground that she had
new facts.
</P>
<P>
The new decision confirmed that the rights of the appellant had
been infringed during his prolonged detention but on a
considerably smaller scale than it had deemed in last decision.
</P>
<P>
The judges of the Appeal Court said that Barayagwiza should be
tried by the ICTR, but that the violation of his rights would be
taken into account at the time of his judgement by the Trial
Chamber.
</P>
<P>
They said that if the Court found Barayagwiza innocent, he
would be entitled to financial compensation for the violations; if
guilty, his eventual sentence is to be reduced to take account of
the infringement of his rights.
</P>
<P>
Barayagwiza, 50, arrested on March 27, 1996, was a founder
member of the Radio Television des Mille Collines, which incited
Hutus to kill Tutsis.
</P>
<P>
He played an important role as the foreign policy advisor to
the Rwandan interim government in the 1994 genocide.
</P>
<P>
Rwanda has hailed the latest ICTR decision, saying it was a
victory for genocide victims.
</P>
<P>
Rwanda has argued that the sufferings of Barayagwiza as a
result of a violation of his rights are negligible as compared to
the sufferings of the victims and survivors of genocide.
</P>
<P>
The ICTR, created on November 8, 1994 by the United Nations
Security Council resolution 955, is responsible to try suspects
involved in the 100- day massacre starting on April 7, 1994 and
killing 800,000 ethnic Tutsis and moderate Hutus.
</P>
<P>
The ICTR has so far issued 28 indictments against 45
individuals, and a total of 38 indicted individuals are in custody
including several former senior cabinet ministers in former
interim government, former military commanders, political leaders,
journalists and senior businessmen.
</P>
<P>
The five detainees who have already been convicted by the Trial
Chambers of the Tribunal are still held in Arusha, pending outcome
of their appeals.
</P>
<P>
Three of the convicts were sentenced to life imprisonment and
the other two were sentenced to 25 and 15 years of imprisonment
respectively. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
