<DOCNO> XIE20000404.0005 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-04 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> First Africa-Europe Summit Closes </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CAIRO, April 4 (Xinhua) -- The first-ever Africa-Europe summit
ended here on Tuesday with the issuing of a final declaration and
adopting of a plan of action.
</P>
<P>
Egyptian President Hosni Mubarak, Algerian President Abdelaziz
Bouteflika, Secretary General of the Organization of African Unity
Salem Amhad Salem and European Union (EU) Foreign Affairs and
Security Coordinator Javier Solana addressed the closing ceremony.
</P>
<P>
Hailing the summit as having succeeded in reflecting the depth
of historical relations between Africa and Europe, Mubarak said it
also was able to come up with joint positive visions of how the two
continents' future should be like.
</P>
<P>
Mubarak's remarks are in tune with the theme of the first-ever
such summit that was designed to forge a new and strategic
relationship between the two continents in the 21st century.
</P>
<P>
President Mubarak expressed hope that the end of the summit
would be the beginning of real partnership, with serious work on
that score getting underway.
</P>
<P>
He also pressed for immediate action on solving pending problems
between the two sides, with emphasis on the African debt crisis.
</P>
<P>
During the summit on Monday and Tuesday, the leaders from 66
African states and European Union (EU) member countries discussed a
wide range of political, economic and social development issues,
with calls from African countries for debt reduction or
cancellation dominating the meeting.
</P>
<P>
The total African external debts have reached staggering 350
billion U.S. dollars and African states are spending 23 billion
dollars, or 30.9 percent of their exports, to service the debts
every year. Africa's average annual economic growth stands at 3
percent while the debt growth rate reached a stunning 23 percent a
year.
</P>
<P>
As a result, the "can't pay" debts sap the revenues of African
countries needed for health, education as well as economic
development.
</P>
<P>
Many leading African leaders noted at the summit that they
realized Africa has lagged far behind and is risking pushing
further outside the development movement with the advent of the
economic globalization, hoping to shed underdevelopment through
more and better EU cooperation for mutual benefit and debt relief
instead of more aid and charity.
</P>
<P>
Seven of the 15 EU member states are former colonial powers in
Africa and the EU gives Africa 15 billion dollars every five years,
more than any other single source. It is also the major creditor of
Africa.
</P>
<P>
The final declaration expressed deep concern over the increasing
debt burden on Africa, and welcomed the enhancement of the Heavily
Indebted Poor Countries initiative launched in 1996 and the
concrete debt-relief moves taken by EU members.
</P>
<P>
France Monday promised to cancel all bilateral debts owed it by
the poorest African countries in one or two years, while Germany
and Morocco also announced to write off part of the states' debts.
</P>
<P>
The two sides also agreed to continue to discuss the debt issue
at their next summit slated for 2003.
</P>
<P>
But pushing a comprehensive debt relief proved not to be an easy
job. Some European countries insisted they have done much to
alleviate the debt burden, they should not shoulder more
responsibilties. Austrian Foreign Minister Benita Ferrero-
Waldner has said that "I think the Africans cannot ask everything
from us Europeans."
</P>
<P>
In addition, they also favored to link the debt reduction or
forgiveness to these countries' economic reforms, democracy
process, human rights and good governance.
</P>
<P>
British Foreign Secretary Robin Cook said at the third session
of the summit said "the political renaissance of Africa provides
the best foundation for the economic renaissance of Africa."
</P>
<P>
As for conflicts in Africa, the declaration called for peaceful
solutions in solving the issue under the U.N. Charter and the
principle of respecting sovereignty and territorial integrity to
pave the way for economic and social development.
</P>
<P>
They agreed to set up a joint mechanism to end the conflicts
that are raging in 14 African countries, according to both the
declaration and the plan of action.
</P>
<P>
The documents said the leaders also deplored all forms of
terrorism and were determined to fight against terrorism through
international cooperation.
</P>
<P>
Referring to the economic and technological issues, the
documents expressed the participants' readiness to support the
efforts of African countries in continuing adopting sound macro-
economic measures and reform programs, including economic structure
adjustment.
</P>
<P>
The declaration underlined EU's determination to pay due
attention to trade liberalization as a mechanism, and the
establishment and support of the process of technology transfer to
Africa.
</P>
<P>
The leaders also agreed to hold a summit every three years, a
ministerial meeting each year and experts meetings twice a year to
follow up steps aimed at boosting cooperation. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
