<DOCNO> XIE20000404.0006 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-04 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Africa, EU Pledge to Give Strategic Dimension to Partnership </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CAIRO, April 4 (Xinhua) -- African and European Union (EU)
leaders on Tuesday pledged to give a new strategic dimension to
the partnership between Africa and Europe for the 21st century
through dialog on economic, political, social and development
issues.
</P>
<P>
At the end of the first-ever Africa-Europe summit, the leaders
of 67 African and EU countries issued the Cairo Declaration, which
demonstrated consensus on a wide range of issues included in 110
articles.
</P>
<P>
The declaration said the leaders agreed to work together to
integrate Africa into the world economy and enhance its prospects
of economic development through trade liberalization, encouraging
private sector investment, regional cooperation and development
aid.
</P>
<P>
They would exert efforts to reduce Africa's 350 billion U.S.
dollars of external debt, through existing initiatives for highly-
indebted poor countries, and have a senior officials' group from
both regions submit a report to ministers on the issue "within a
reasonable time frame."
</P>
<P>
The leaders would help reinforce African and regional mechanisms
for conflict prevention, management and resolution by strengthening
the mechanisms of the Organization of African Unity (OAU),
developing an OAU early warning system and improving Africa's own
operational capabilities for peacekeeping and conflict resolution.
</P>
<P>
The African and EU countries will take measures to stop the
illegal exploitation of natural resources and illicit trade in
high-value commodities such as diamonds, and to increase
cooperation against terrorism and illicit trafficking of small
arms.
</P>
<P>
The countries will have senior officials from both regions study
and report to ministers on the legal and practical consequences of
further action to return cultural goods stolen or exported
illegally.
</P>
<P>
They are to create a follow-up mechanism with further summits "
based on the principle of continuity," the next one to be held in
Europe in 2003, with a meeting of ministers between summits, plus a
bi-regional group of senior officials. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
