<DOCNO> XIE20000404.0007 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-04 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Israel Increases Funds for Fortifying Northern Settlements: Deputy DM </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JERUSALEM, April 4 (Xinhua) -- Israeli Deputy Defense Minister
Ephraim Sneh announced on Tuesday that his ministry has increased
its budget for reinforcing security of northern settlements by 14
million shekels (about 3.5 million U.S. dollars).
</P>
<P>
While touring northern settlements along the border between
Israel and Lebanon, Sneh also said further budgets, if they are
needed, will be available in the future, Israel Radio reported.
</P>
<P>
These settlements are facing the threat of possible cross-border
guerrilla attacks after Israel Defense Forces scheduled withdrawal
from the Israeli-occupied security zone in south Lebanon by July.
</P>
<P>
The 15-kilometer-deep buffer zone was set up by Israel in 1985
with a self-claimed aim of preventing such attacks on its north.
</P>
<P>
Since then, Lebanese Hezbollah guerrillas, a Shiite Muslim
militant group in the zone, has been fighting to end the Israeli
occupation. The militia launched Katyusha rocket attacks several
times in the past years against Israel's settlements along the
northern border, causing some casualties.
</P>
<P>
Earlier this year, the guerrillas escalated its activities in
south Lebanon, killing seven Israeli soldiers and a senior
commander of Israeli-backed South Lebanon Army.
</P>
<P>
The guerrillas also threatened to launch Katyusha attacks again,
which forced Israeli settlers in these towns to lock themselves in
their bomb shelters and basements for nearly a week.
</P>
<P>
To ease growing public pressure, the Israeli cabinet on March 5
gave backing to a key pledge made by Barak to withdraw from the
zone by July, with or without a peace deal with Syria, the major
power broker in Lebanon.
</P>
<P>
Some experts predicted that Hezbollah, which is backed by Syria
and Iran, will not keep Israel's northern border quiet in the case
of a pullout without agreements.
</P>
<P>
During his meeting with visiting U.S. Secretary of Defense
William Cohen on Monday, Barak said that Israel is the strongest
country in the region and he doubts whether there will be any
country venturing to test its strains by attacking its northern
settlements.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
