<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-04 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Kuwaiti DM Re-stresses Importance to Buy U.S. Howitzers </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KUWAIT CITY, April 4 (Xinhua) -- Kuwaiti Deputy Prime Minister
and Defense Minister Sheikh Salem Al-Sabah on Tuesday re-emphasized
the importance to buy the U.S.-made Paladin howitzers.
</P>
<P>
In remarks to Kuwait News Agency, Sheikh Salem underlined the
need to purchase the U.S. guns "because the Ministry of Defense
needs this formidable machinery and in order to develop Kuwait's
arsenal."
</P>
<P>
But the official said that any final decision regarding the
purchase needs a political decision, adding that "as for the
technical decision, we have already taken it."
</P>
<P>
This was the second time within two weeks the Kuwaiti defense
chief stressed the need to go ahead with the controversial
purchase.
</P>
<P>
On March 20, Sheikh Salem said Kuwait was still wishing and
insisting on purchasing the American guns because the Army needs
them.
</P>
<P>
The Public Fund Protection Committee at the Parliament has been
studying, since last December, the purchase of the Paladin
howitzers in a deal estimated at some 400 million U.S. dollars.
</P>
<P>
The committee was supposed to report to the parliament about the
deal later last month.
</P>
<P>
Kuwait planned to equip three battalions with howitzers and has
received offers from several big powers including the United
States, which are worth of some 750 million dollars. The U.S.
offered its M109 A6 Paladin howitzers.
</P>
<P>
But the purchase sparked controversy in Kuwait's previous
parliament, with many lawmakers arguing that the U.S-made Paladin
is outmoded and not compatible with the Kuwait armament system.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
