<DOCNO> XIE20000404.0011 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-04 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> France Rules Out New Devaluation of African Franc </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
PARIS, April 4 (Xinhua) -- France ruled out on Tuesday a new
devaluation of the African franc which is pegged with the European
single currency euro because of its fixed rate with the French
franc.
</P>
<P>
At a meeting of the ministers of finance of the African franc
zone held in Malabo, Equatorial Guinea, French Minister of
Cooperation Charles Josselin and State Secretary for Exterior
Trade Francois Huwart said the African franc, or CFA franc, still
remains competitive after its 50 percent devaluation in 1994.
</P>
<P>
Rumors on a devaluation of the African franc has been
circulating because of the high exchange rate between the euro and
other currencies and the replace of the French franc by euro in
two years' time.
</P>
<P>
French officials said that while the French franc will
disappear when the euro becomes currency in 2002, the African
franc will remain.
</P>
<P>
The exchange rate between the French franc and African franc is
fixed at one for 100. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
