<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE20000404.0012 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-04 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> First Direct Shipment of U.S. Meat Departs for China </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, April 4 (Xinhua) - The United States has sent its
first direct shipment of meat to China's market in line with new
rules Beijing has formulated to carry out a farm agreement signed
last year.
</P>
<P>
The shipment of meat, which departed from San Francisco on a
plane bound for Shanghai on Sunday night, "represents the first
direct opening of China's market to U.S. meat and poultry
producers," said U.S. Trade Representative Charlene Barshefsky.
</P>
<P>
"Direct exports of U.S. meat to China should increase
dramatically as further market opening and sales opportunities are
presented by China's accession to the WTO. But full access will
only happen if Congress votes to approve permanent normal trade
relations with China," she said.
</P>
<P>
Agriculture Secretary Dan Glickman, who announced the shipment
along with Barshefsky, said that China, as one of the world's
largest and fastest growing economies, holds "enormous potential
for growing agricultural exports."
</P>
<P>
The shipment of meat, which was imported by City Supermarket
Company Limited in Shanghai, came after China decided to buy its
first shipment of wheat from the Pacific Northwest earlier this
month, and shipments of citrus sailed from ports in Florida and
California last week.
</P>
<P>
"The first shipment of U.S. citrus to China in 20 years, a
contract pending for a shipment of U.S. wheat, and now this
shipment of U.S. beef and pork demonstrates the tangible benefits
of increased trade with China," Glickman said.
</P>
<P>
"I hope and expect that these shipments are only the first of
many more sales to come," he added.
</P>
<P>
China issued new rules governing the importation of U.S. citrus,
meat, and wheat on March 22, in an effort to implement the
Agreement on U.S.-China Agricultural Cooperation. The agreement,
signed on April 10, 1999, lifted long-standing bans on the export
of U.S. citrus, wheat and other grains from the Pacific Northwest,
and meat and poultry.
</P>
<P>
China imported 1.3 million metric tons of beef, pork, and
poultry from all sources in 1999. U.S. meat exports are shipped to
China, but as transshipments through Hong Kong. In 1999, Hong Kong
was the fourth largest market for U.S. pork and pork variety meat
exports, with a value of 32.3 million dollars, and more than half
of these imports were transshipped to China, according to a news
release from the office of the U.S. Trade Representative. 
</P>
</TEXT>
