<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Robertson, Albright Meet Over European Security </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Speaking at a joint press conference following a meeting here,
Robertson called Russia a "strategic partner" with which NATO will
discuss common security problems.
</P>
<P>
The two met to prepare for NATO's meeting next month in
Florence, Italy. Robertson said European allies are assuming some
of the burden that has been carried disproportionally by the
United States in dealing with security problems in Europe.
</P>
<P>
On the European Security and Defense Identity (ESDI), Robertson
said, it "is designed to strengthen NATO and to, inside the
Alliance, share more of the burdens."
</P>
<P>
"I will remain vigilant and robust, and I'll make sure that the
Alliance's interests are the major interests and the ones that
will be paramount," he added.
</P>
<P>
Albright reiterated the U.S. support for ESDI, saying the
United States is "most supportive of it."
</P>
<P>
"The interests of allies who are not EU members have to be
protected, and our twin goals are an EU that is more effective on
security issues and an Alliance that remains united and strong,"
she added.
</P>
<P>
Robertson, who visited Moscow recently, told reporters that the
relationship with Russia has been resumed after his visit.
</P>
<P>
The relationship "is built on the NATO-Russia Founding Act"
while NATO and Russia should join together to "deal with and to
discuss the problems that face us together, and not trying to deal
with them on a separate and isolated basis," he said.
</P>
<P>
Moscow cut off its the relationship with NATO on March 24 last
year when NATO launched a 78-day air campaign against Yugoslavia,
a close ally of Russia.
</P>
<P>
Earlier this year, Russia's Security Council approved a new
doctrine in February but it will not be published until an amended
version has been signed by President-elect Vladimir Putin.
</P>
<P>
The published draft doctrine says that Russia will use all
possible means, including nuclear weapons to ward off a foreign
aggression.
</P>
<P>
On Monday, Wesley Clark, NATO's Supreme Allied Commander in
Europe, said that the new doctrine, which upgrades the role of
nuclear weapons, was a step in the wrong direction and should be
revised. 
</P>
</TEXT>
