<HEADLINE> U.S. Army to Buy Over 1,200 New-Generation Helicopters </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
At a press conference, the officials unveiled the Army's post-
Cold War aviation plan and said the service was "fully committed"
to obtain all of its planned new RAH-66 Comanches.
</P>
<P>
The centerpiece of U.S. Army aviation in the 21st century is
supposed to be the Comanche, an armed reconnaissance helicopter
with more radar-evading stealth technology than any chopper in the
current fleet.
</P>
<P>
The Comanche helicopters will replace the OH-58 Kiowa Warrior
helicopters, which will be retired in 2013, about seven years
earlier than planned. The first Comanches are to enter the fleet
in 2006.
</P>
<P>
The Comanche is being produced by Boeing Co. and Sikorsky
Aircraft Corp., a subsidiary of United Technologies Corp.
</P>
<P>
The overall U.S. Army helicopter fleet will be reduced from six
types to four with the addition of the Comanche.
</P>
<P>
The last of the AH-1 Cobras, combat mainstays in the Vietnam
War that now average 30 years old, will be retired this October,
and UH-1 Huey helicopters will be retired in 2004. That will leave
the UH-60 Black Hawk utility helicopter fleet, the Vietnam-era CH-
47 Chinook transports and the AH-64 Apache attack helicopters.
</P>
</TEXT>
