<BODY>
<HEADLINE> U.S. Foundation to Help African Countries Fight AIDS </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
DAR ES SALAAM, April 4 (Xinhua) -- A United States-based
foundation announced Tuesday to offer 57 million U.S. dollars to
help four African countries fight against HIV/AIDS.
</P>
<P>
The grant from the Bill &AMP; Melinda Gates Foundation will
tremendously strengthen efforts to protect young people in
Botswana, Ghana, Uganda and Tanzania against HIV/AIDS, the United
Nations Population Fund said in a statement.
</P>
<P>
The foundation is funding a five-year initiative to expand
national campaigns which will educate youth about preventing
HIV/AIDS and ensure that they can protect themselves.
</P>
<P>
Led by billionaire Bill Gates' father, William H. Gates, Sr.,
and Patty Stonesifer, the Seattle-based foundation is dedicated to
improving people's lives by sharing advances in health and
learning with the global community.
</P>
<P>
"This grant puts resources where the need is most urgent:
protecting the most vulnerable and safeguarding each country's
future. The programs it supports will also serve as models for
other hard-hit countries and international aid efforts.
</P>
<P>
"And it will help the international community move towards its
stated goal of reducing HIV/AIDS infections in the most affected
countries by 25 percent by 2005," said the statement.
</P>
<P>
In sub-Saharan Africa, where AIDS is ravaging families,
communities and national economies, half of all new cases of HIV
infection are among young people aged 15-24.
</P>
<P>
In several countries, girls aged 15-19 are five or six times
more likely to be HIV-positive than boys in the same age group,
indicating a critical need to empower adolescent girls, in
particular, with the information and means to avoid infection.
</P>
<P>
Currently very few young people in the countries concerned are
being reached with HIV/AIDS prevention programs.
</P>
<P>
The four countries were chosen based on need and on their
demonstrated commitment to HIV/AIDS prevention among youth.
</P>
</TEXT>
