debt relief initiative to cover more deserving countries when he
addressed the Afro- European summit which closed Tuesday in Cairo,
Egypt.
</P>
<P>
In his speech, Moi welcomed the current debt relief initiative
by the World Bank, the International Monetary Fund and the Group
of 7, saying that initiatives were limited in scope and not
prompt, the Presidential Press Service reported in Nairobi.
</P>
<P>
Noting that substantial percentage of domestic revenue was
spent on debt serving, Moi said that this led to economic
stagnation due to reduced investment.
</P>
<P>
He pointed out that Africa still needed more development
assistance for infrastructure, and support for promotion of good
governance, transparency, accountability and prevention of
corruption among other programs.
</P>
<P>
Even if all external debts were cancelled entirely, Africa
would still need more assistance owing to the extremely fragile
economies, he added.
</P>
<P>
Moi also appealed to Africa's development partners for
supporting in addressing such issues as poverty alleviation and
HIV/AIDS, and for cooperation in implementing food policies
especially in areas of production, processing, marketing and
distribution. 
