<HEADLINE> Jordan Pursues Just, Comprehensive Peace in Middle East </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
AMMAN, April 4 (Xinhua) -- Jordanian Prime and Defense Minister
Abdel Rauf Rawabdeh said Tuesday his kingdom was determined to push
forward the Middle East peace process and to work on a just,
durable and comprehensive peace in the region.
</P>
<P>
Rawabdeh made the remarks in a meeting with visiting U.S.
Defense Secretary William Cohen, who is on a 12-day mission to the
region.
</P>
<P>
Rawabdeh and Cohen reviewed relations between Jordan and the
United States in all fields, particularly in the military and
defense fields, and the latest developments of the peace process
between Israel and its Arab neighbors, Jordan's official news
agency Petra reported.
</P>
<P>
The prime minister expressed his government's appreciation for
U.S. aid to Jordan, which amounted to some 300 million U.S. dollars
in 1999 in various economic and military packages as a reward for
its role as a major peace broker in the region after it signed a
peace treaty with Israel in 1994.
</P>
<P>
Rawabdeh also said he hoped to enhance military and defense
cooperation between the two countries, which he said was of a great
importance for Jordan to continue its role of promoting peace in
the region.
</P>
<P>
For his part, Cohen praised Jordan's efforts to achieve a just,
durable and comprehensive peace in the region. He said Washington
was keen to enhance the defensive capabilities of the kingdom,
which Washington takes as an ally in the Arab world.
</P>
<P>
Cohen arrived in Amman earlier in the day for a two-day visit as
part of his regional tour, which has also taken him to Nigeria,
Israel, Cairo and will take him to six Gulf Arab states, to promote
military cooperation between the U.S. and these countries. 
</P>
