<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-04 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> U.N., U.S., UK Agree to Accelerate Cyprus Reconciliation Process </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NICOSIA, April 4 (Xinhua) -- The United Nations, the United
States and the United Kingdom agree to speed up the Cyprus
reconciliation process on the next round of U.N.-sponsored
proximity talks on Cyprus, the Cyprus News Agency (CNA) reported
from New York on Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
For this purpose, envoys from the three sides will pay another
visit to the region in seven weeks prior to the talks to urge
Cyprus' two sides to be as flexible as possible on the proposals
they have put forward during the last two rounds of talks.
</P>
<P>
The decision was made in a meeting in New York on Monday among
U.N. Secretary-General's Special Adviser Alvaro de Soto, U.S.
Presidential Emissary Alfred Moses and British representative for
Cyprus Sir David Hannay.
</P>
<P>
U.N. Secretariat sources told CNA that Monday's meeting was part
of "normal consultations" which concentrated on "developments in
the island and particularly preparations for the next round of the
proximity talks."
</P>
<P>
A British government source at the U.N. headquarters said that
all want to see "a change of gear" during the next round of the
proximity talks and "there has to be an acceleration of the
process."
</P>
<P>
The source said the three sides "are looking at what each can do
in the next seven weeks" and agreed to visit the region again in an
effort to move the process forward.
</P>
<P>
A source at the U.S. permanent mission at the U.N. said that the
three envoys all agreed that it is high time for more "substantive"
talks.
</P>
<P>
The source indicated that during the last two rounds of talks in
New York and Geneva the parties involved "were in a listening mode"
but now they have to "move forward."
</P>
<P>
Cyprus has remained divided into the Turkish Cypriots-controlled
north and the Greek Cypriots-dominated south since 1974 when Turkey
invaded and occupied the northern third of the island after a pro-
Athens coup.
</P>
<P>
The U.N. has been pushing for reunification of Cyprus under a
bizonal, bicommunal federation formula but all efforts have so far
failed.
</P>
<P>
The leaders of the two communities have already completed two
rounds of proximity talks under U.N. auspices in an effort to find
a solution. They agreed to start a new round of talks in New York
on May 23. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE20000404.0027 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-04 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Roundup: International Pressure Against Sanctions Mounting  by Li Xuejun </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BAGHDAD, April 4 (Xinhua) -- To protest the decade-long U.N.
sanctions on Iraq, a European airplane carrying three persons, with
no prior approval from the U.N., landed at Baghdad's Al-Rashed
military airport Monday evening.
</P>
<P>
It was the first group who arrived in Baghdad by plane
disregarding U.N. resolutions that require all flights to or from
Iraq must get permission from the U.N. Sanctions Committee.
</P>
<P>
At the airport, Jean-Marie Benjamin, head of the group, read a
declaration to the media, demanding an immediate and total lifting
of the sanctions.
</P>
<P>
Benjamin and his companions are among the growing numerous
figures worldwide calling for an end to the sanctions since 1990.
</P>
<P>
British Member of Parliament George Galloway arrived here by
plane in 1997 for the same aim.
</P>
<P>
At that time it was the first airplane from Europe that arrived
in Iraq since sanctions were clamped on the country after its
invasion of Kuwait.
</P>
<P>
Galloway, who is now on a visit to the United Arab Emirates
(UAE), has affirmed that the public opinion in the West has started
to show opposition to the continuation of the sanctions, Iraq's
English-language Baghdad Observer reported.
</P>
<P>
It is high time for the sanctions to be lifted, said Galloway.
</P>
<P>
Besides Galloway, more than 70 members of the U.S. Congress have
signed a letter to President Bill Clinton, calling for an end to
the humanitarian crisis in Iraq by having the sanctions lifted.
</P>
<P>
The Clinton administration has been strongly opposed ending the
sanctions on Iraq.
</P>
<P>
The call by the U.S. Congressmen coincided with the resignations
of top U.N. officials in Baghdad in protest against the devastating
impact of the U.N. sanctions on the Iraqi people.
</P>
<P>
Hans von Sponeck, who left his post as the U.N. Humanitarian
Coordinator for Iraq at the end of last month, has been a vocal
critic of the stringent U.N. sanctions, arguing the sanctions have
resulted in a true humanitarian tragedy in Iraq.
</P>
<P>
Sponeck followed the example of his predecessor, Denis Halliday,
who quit his job in mid-1998 after months of voicing similar views.
</P>
<P>
Jota Burkhart, ex-representative of the World Food Program in
Iraq, also resigned from her post in protest against the
continuation of sanction on Iraq.
</P>
<P>
Within the U.N. Security Council, Russia, China and France have
been calling for ending the sanctions.
</P>
<P>
In the Gulf area, UAE President Sheikh Zayed Bin Sultan Al-
Nahyan has demanded to stop the trade embargo on Iraq, emphasizing
the necessity of ending the sufferings of the Iraqi people.
</P>
<P>
Iraqi people, especially children and the elderly, have been
hardest hit by the sanctions.
</P>
<P>
According to the World Health Organization (WHO), during 1984-
1990, children who died below the age of five were 36.5 per
thousand, while the current figure stands at 120 per thousand in
Iraq.
</P>
<P>
Iraqi Health Ministry has said that the sanctions have claimed
lives of more than 1.2 million people, and such a high mortality is
a direct result of malnutrition and medical shortage caused by the
sanctions.
</P>
<P>
In a recent report, the International Committee of the Red Cross
has drawn a grim picture of Iraqi people's lives under the
sanctions.
</P>
<P>
"Deteriorating living conditions, inflations and low salaries
make people's everyday lives a continuing struggle," said the
report.
</P>
<P>
However, there are already signals that the sanctions regime
have begun to erode.
</P>
<P>
Bahrain, who withdrew its ambassador from Iraq in 1990, has sent
charge d'affaires Hasan Malullah Al-Ansari back to its embassy in
Baghdad.
</P>
<P>
A senior Arab diplomat has pointed out that Ansari's return
marked the reopening of Bahraini embassay.
</P>
<P>
Bahrain has followed Qatar and Oman to reactivate diplomatic
relations with Iraq recently.
</P>
<P>
There has been a thaw in relations between Iraq and its
traditional rivals such as Syria and Saudi Arabia, who took part in
the U.S.-led coalition against Iraq during the 1991 Gulf War.
</P>
<P>
Iraq has opened an interests section in Syria, the first formal
diplomatic link between the two countries in almost 20 years. Syria
is expected to follow suit shortly.
</P>
<P>
Syria-influenced Lebanon has already restored diplomatic
relations with Iraq in October 1998, after a four-year break.
</P>
<P>
The volume of trade between Iraq and Saudi Arabia has reached
more than 100 million U.S. dollars a year. In August last year,
Saudi Arabia released one million dollars of Iraqi assets frozen in
Saudi banks.
</P>
<P>
Iraq's neighboring countries, including Jordan and Turkey, have
benefited a lot from developing trade relations with Iraq.
</P>
<P>
Iraq's reconstruction, a lucrative market of about 200 billion
dollars, has been attracting flocks of trade officials and business
delegations worldwide to develop trade ties with Baghdad despite
the sanctions.
</P>
<P>
These countries, including Russia, France, Italy, Spain,
Austria, India, Pakistan, Malaysia, Algeria, Egypt, Tunisia,
Mexico, are vying for a slice of Iraq's market by gaining contracts
under the U.N. oil-for-food program and trying to get a firm
foothold once the sanctions are lifted.
</P>
<P>
France, for example, has opened a trade center and upgraded its
representation in Iraq last year, sending a diplomat to run an
interests section in Baghdad for the first time since 1990.
</P>
<P>
Even the U.N. is showing a bit flexibility in dealing with Iraq.
U.N. Secretary-General Kofi Annan has called on the U.N. Sanctions
Committee to quicken the process of examining and approving Iraq's
contracts.
</P>
<P>
The Security Council unanimously adopted a resolution on March
31 to allow Iraq to double the amount of fund it can use to import
oil spare parts, meaning that Iraq can draw 600 million dollars
from its oil revenues in six months to buy oil equipment and spare
parts within the framework of the oil-for-food program.
</P>
<P>
Under the U.N. deal now in its seventh phase, Iraq is allowed to
export limited amount of crude oil to finance imports of food,
medicine and other humanitarian supplies to help offset the effects
of the sanctions. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
