<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Annan Welcomes Assurances From Israel </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>

<P>
UNITED NATIONS, April 4 (Xinhua) -- U.N. Secretary-General
Kofi Annan on Tuesday welcomed the assurances from Israel's
Foreign Minister, David Levy, that his country would cooperate
fully with the United Nations throughout the peace process in the
Middle East.
</P>
<P>
 Annan met Levy today in Geneva and discussed Israel's
withdrawal from southern Lebanon.
</P>
<P>
In a statement issued by his spokesman's office, Annan said
the Foreign Minister reaffirmed his Government's decision to
withdraw Israeli troops from Southern Lebanon in accordance with
Security Council resolution 425, fully and without conditions.
</P>
<P>
"The Minister informed me that the withdrawal will occur in '
one go' by the end of July," Annan said.
</P>
<P>
 "The Minister assured me of his Government's intention to
cooperate fully with the United Nations throughout the process,
within the framework of the relevant Security Council resolutions,
" the U.N. chief said.
</P>
<P>
"The Minister and I agreed that cooperation by all parties
concerned would be needed in order to avoid any deterioration of
the situation during the withdrawal," Annan added.
</P>
<P>
Israeli Prime Minister Ehud Barak has pledged to end Israel's
occupation of the "security zone" in southern Lebanon by July with
or without a peace deal with Syria and Lebanon.
</P>
<P>
Annan said Monday in New York "If the withdrawal comes outside
a broader agreement, obviously it is not an ideal situation. We
will have to cope with it."  
</P>
</TEXT>
