<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Hundreds of U.S. Employees Rally For PNTR </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, April 4 (Xinhua) -- More than 500 employees of
American corporations from around the United States joined
together here Tuesday to urge members of Congress to extend
permanent normal trade relations (PNTR) to China.
</P>
<P>
The employees, representing large and small businesses in the
telecommunications, aerospace, insurance, manufacturing, airline
and service industries, began their lobbying campaign with a rally
at the Commerce Department and then went to Capitol to meet with
Congressmen to advocate PNTR.
</P>
<P>
U.S. Trade Representative Charlene Barshefsky, speaking at the
rally, said the Congress vote on PNTR this year is "one of the
most profound and important decisions America will make in this
decade".
</P>
<P>
Barshefsky said support for PNTR on Capitol Hill is growing in
recent weeks.
</P>
<P>
"This is a tough vote for many members, but we are optimistic
that we will succeed in achieving permanent normal trade relations
status for China," she said.
</P>
<P>
U.S. Treasury Secretary Lawrence Summars, speaking on the same
occasion, said the vote will make American workers and businesses
to benefit from the trade deal reached between the U.S. and China
in November last year.
</P>
<P>
"It can be a landmark in the United States embrace of an
economic strategy based on working to take advantage of the global
economy, a strategy that's brought us the lowest unemployment and
the highest productivity in a generation," he said.
</P>
<P>
The rally was sponsored by the Business Coalition for U.S.-
China Trade, consisting of more than 1,200 leading American
companies, trade associations and farm organizations that support
PNTR.
</P>
<P>
Ruth Harkin, Senior Vice President of United Technologies
Corporation who is speaking on behalf of the business coalition,
said that it's Americans who will reap the benefits when the doors
fling open to a market of 1.3 billion people.
</P>
<P>
"Extending NTR permanently will nearly double U.S. exports to
China, raise farmers' foreign sales by 2.2 billion dollars each
year and create thousands of new, high-wage American jobs like the
200,000 that already support trade with China," she said. "The
deal is just too good to pass up."  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
