<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-04 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> U.S. Threatens to Sue Mexico for Unfair Telecom Practices </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, April 4 (Xinhua) -- The U.S. government on Tuesday
accused Mexico and several other nations of erecting unfair
barriers to keep American telecommunication companies out of their
markets.
</P>
<P>
The administration set deadlines for later this year for the
barriers to be removed and raised the prospect that cases would be
brought to the World Trade Organization (WTO) if the most
objectionable barriers are not dealt with.
</P>
<P>
"We will follow up to ensure that expected actions are taken on
a timely basis and that those actions are consistent with WTO
commitments," U.S. Trade Representative Charlene Barshefsky said
in statement, after concluding an annual review of major U.S.
trading partners and their compliance with WTO telecom rules.
</P>
<P>
The others named in the annual review of telecommunication
practices were Germany, South Africa, Britain, Canada, Peru,
Israel and Taiwan Province of China.
</P>
<P>
Last week, the Clinton administration issued a separate report
accusing Japan of violating its WTO commitments by refusing to
lower high interconnection fees that U.S. telecommunication
companies complain are designed to keep them out of the Japanese
market.
</P>
<P>
In the report, the United States singled out Mexico for attack,
accusing authorities of failing to open a telecommunications
market dominated by Telefonos de Mexico (Telmex), the former
Mexican state phone monopoly.
</P>
<P>
Mexican long-distance operators affiliated with U.S.-based AT&AMP;T
and MCI WorldCom have struggled for years to compete with Telmex,
and have put pressure on the Clinton administration to take action.
</P>
<P>
"In Mexico, it appears that progress towards a level playing
field for telecommunications carriers now is stalled," Barshefsky
said.
</P>
<P>
She said the United States would decide by July 28 whether to
take action against Mexico, its partner in the North American Free
Trade Agreement. The administration also had set a deadline of
July 28 for resolving the Japanese case.
</P>
<P>
Other review deadlines set by the administration Tuesday
included June 15 for Germany, South Africa and Britain, and
October 2 for Canada and Peru.
</P>
<P>
In addition, the administration said it would also be watching
to see that Israel lives up to commitments to terminate
objectionable telephone barriers by the end of 2001, and to see
that Taiwan carries forward with the elimination of certain
exclusive licensing arrangements. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
