<HEADLINE> Zimbabwe Urges Britain to Compensate for Land Seizure </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HARARE, April 4 (Xinhua) -- Zimbabwe's Justice, Legal and
Parliamentary Affairs Minister Emmerson Mnangagwa said on Tuesday
the British government should compensate for white farmers whose
land would be seized for black resettlement.
</P>
<P>
Mnangagwa, who is also the leader of the House, made the
remarks during a second reading of the Constitution of Zimbabwe
Amendment Bill.
</P>
<P>
The Bill sought to amend the constitution with regard to the
compulsory acquisition of land and to provide for the
establishment and functions of the Anti-Corruption Commission.
</P>
<P>
The minister said: "We have provided for the mechanism for the
British government to pay compensation through a fund to be
established for that purpose."
</P>
<P>
"But on the other hand if the British government fails to pay
compensation, then the Zimbabwean government has no obligation to
the farmers whose land would be compulsorily acquired for
resettlement," he said.
</P>
<P>
The Constitution amendment intended to close the gap on the
land imbalances since 1890 when the British government and
subsequent white governments pushed the blacks of this country to
communal lands which were marginal rainfall areas, he said.
</P>
<P>
"We count ourselves lucky that after 110 years of land denial,
today we are poised to make history by enacting a piece of
legislation that will put to rest the constraint to correct the
land deprivation to our people by the colonial past," he added.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
