<DOCNO> XIE20000404.0037 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-04 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Turkish PM Makes Last-Ditch Efforts for Extension of President's Term </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ANKARA, April 4 (Xinhua) -- Turkish Prime Minister Bulent Ecevit
said that the ruling coalition leaders will continue to push for
the extension of President Suleyman Demirel's term in office,
despite objections from the opposition and some coalition deputies.
</P>
<P>
Ecevit made the remarks in a written statement on Monday after
meeting his coalition partners, Nationalist Movement Party (MHP)
leader and Deputy Prime Minister Devlet Bahceli, and Motherland
Party (ANAP) Chairman Mesut Yilmaz, Turkish Daily News reported
Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
Ecevit was astonished and upset in the first round of vote last
Wednesday when only 303 deputies from the 550-member parliament
voted for his proposal which would reduce the president's term from
seven to five years, but allow for a second five-year term.
</P>
<P>
The "yes" votes were far short not only of the required minimum
of 330 votes for an amendment to be legislated, but also of the 406
votes Ecevit was promised to gain from the ruling coalition and the
opposition True Path Party (DYP).
</P>
<P>
Ecevit said that 324 deputies of the ruling parties and 82
deputies from the DYP who signed the constitutional amendment
package should stick to their pledge and vote for the changes in
the second and the final round of vote on Wednesday (tomorrow).
</P>
<P>
This is important for the credibility and prestige of
Parliament, he said, adding that the coalition leaders would take
the necessary measures to ensure that their deputies would vote for
the amendment.
</P>
<P>
The first round result showed that most ANAP deputies are
against Demirel's extension in office and, to make things worse,
quite a few DYP deputies joined the forces against Demirel who just
came from this party.
</P>
<P>
Ecevit, who felt betrayed, said Monday that in view of the fact
that deputies will cast their ballots in secret, he cannot ensure
that the amendment will get enough "yes" votes namely two-thirds
majority.
</P>
<P>
Analysts here said that Ecevit wants the bill passed to avoid
squabbling in the ruling coalition over the select of a successor
to Demirel. However, many deputies clearly believe it is time for
the 75-year-old leader to step aside from politics.
</P>
<P>
Public support for the extension of Demirel's presidential term
has been in steady decline since January, a poll conducted by the
Ankara Social Researches Center (ANAR) revealed on Saturday.
</P>
<P>
Among those who reject the extension of Demirel's presidency,
59.5 percent say it is because of his age, and 16.7 percent believe
that a new person should be given the opportunity to take the
presidential post.
</P>
<P>
Analysts said that the passage of the amendment package in the
final vote on Wednesday, depends on Ecevit' efforts to bring
renegade coalition deputies back in line or strike a bargain with
the main opposition Islamist Virtue Party (FP).
</P>
<P>
The FP, founded at the ashes of the banned fundamentalist
Welfare Party in 1998 and embroiled in a closure case, insisted
that they will vote against the bill unless it is appended with a
legislation that would reduce the danger of their party's ban by
the constitutional court in coming weeks. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
