<BODY>
<HEADLINE> New Commander of Israel Air Force Assumes Office </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JERUSALEM, April 4 (Xinhua) -- Major General Dan Halutz
officially became the 14th commander of the Israel Air Force (IAF)
in a ceremony at the Tel Nof air base Tuesday afternoon.
</P>
<P>
Halutz, 52, deputy commander before the promotion, replaced
Major General Eitan Ben-Eliahu, according to Israel Radio reports.
</P>
<P>
As a promising commander, with shot-downs of two Migs and a
helicopter to his credit, Halutz joined the force in 1966 and
quickly implemented flight actions with then advanced F-4 fighters
during the War of Attrition with Israel's Arab neighbors in the
late 1960s and early 1970s.
</P>
<P>
After the Yom Kippur war broke out in 1973, he abandoned his
plan to study and went into battle, flying at least 43 combat
sorties during the time.
</P>
<P>
He went on as F-16 pilot, weapon systems head, and commander of
Hatzor airbase. In 1998, he was promoted to major general and
appointed to the General Staff as head of the IAF Operations
Directorate, the deputy post in the force.
</P>
<P>
He had good professional relations with Israeli Prime Minister
Ehud Barak as they cooperated well when Barak was Chief of General
Staff of Israel Defense Forces.
</P>
<P>
Halutz spoke highly of his predecessor during the office-taking
ceremony for Ben-Eliahu's contribution to the IAF in the past four
years,
</P>
<P>
Ben-Eliahu took his final flight in a fighter jet last Friday to
wind up his over-4500-flight-hour career and announced his retiring
from the service.
</P>
<P>
Some military experts pointed out the 56-year-old outgoing
commander had done many things to revive the IAF, which is
drastically different from the one he took over four years ago.
</P>
<P>
His early period on the job was overshadowed by the worst
accident in IAF's history when two transport Choppers ran into
head-to-head, killing all 72 soldiers they were ferrying to Lebanon
in 1996.
</P>
<P>
But later, he achieved many of his goals: sending two Israeli
astronauts to train with U.S. counterparts in a NASA (National
Aeronautics and Space Administration) base, improving IAF's long-
range transporting and attacking capability, opening the once
closed cooperation with foreign air forces, introducing a
Helicopter Air Division, and so on. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
