<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-04 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> 2 Iraqi Civilians Killed in U.S., British Air Raids  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BAGHDAD, April 4 (Xinhua) -- Two civilians were killed and a
number of people injured in U.S. and British warplanes' attacks in
southern and northern Iraq on Tuesday, an Iraqi military spokesman
announced.
</P>
<P>
The spokesman said that at 12:50 (0950GMT), 16 formations of U.
S. and British planes made 38 armed sorties from Saudi Arabia and
Kuwait, bombing civilian and service facilities in the southern
provinces of Basra, Misan, Thi-Qar, Qadissiyah, Wasit, Muthana and
Najaf, killing two and injuring an unspecified number of people.
</P>
<P>
The spokesman added that at 10:05 (0705GMT), nine hostile
formations of the U.S. and British planes made 18 armed sorties
over the northern provinces of Dohuk, Neiveva and Erbil from
Turkish airspace.
</P>
<P>
On both occasions, Iraqi air defense artillery fired at the
enemy planes, forcing them to flee back to their bases.
</P>
<P>
Since the U.S. and Britain launched the four-night air strikes
against Iraq in December 1998, their warplanes have made a total of
20112 armed sorties over the two no-fly zones in southern and
northern Iraq.
</P>
<P>
The no-fly zones were imposed on Iraq by the U.S.-led Western
coalition following the 1991 Gulf War, with the claimed aim of
protecting the Kurds in the north and the Shiite Muslims in the
south from possible attacks by Iraqi government troops.
</P>
<P>
Iraq has never recognized the restricted zones for no explicit
authorization from the U.N. Security Council. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
