<HEADLINE> Arab-Israeli Water Talks Cancelled, Says Omani Source </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MUSCAT, April 4 (Xinhua) -- Arab-Israeli talks on water
resources, due to be held in Muscat on April 11-12, have been
cancelled as Oman would not act as a host due to its obligations to
the Arab League.
</P>
<P>
An Omani foreign ministry source said his country has not
invited member countries of the working group on water under the
multilateral negotiations, which include Israel, to hold such
talks.
</P>
<P>
A multilateral meeting in Moscow on February 1 scheduled the
talks on water resources in Muscat.
</P>
<P>
The source said Oman has to respect Arab League resolutions on
the peace process, referring to call by the pan-Arab body on March
11 on member states to review ties with Israel and to "reconsider"
their participation in the multilateral talks until "tangible"
progress has been made on all tracks of the peace process.
</P>
<P>
Israeli-Syrian peace talks have been deadlocked since January
due to the two sides' differences over the Golan Heights. Syria has
demanded full Israeli withdrawal from the plateau, but Israel wants
to keep part of the area adjacent to Lake Tiberias which is crucial
to its water security.
</P>
<P>
The meeting in Moscow also scheduled talks on regional economic
development in Amman on May 8-11, on Palestinian refugees from May
16-18 in Ottawa, and on May 31-June 1 in Tunis on the environment.
</P>
</TEXT>
