<BODY>
<HEADLINE> U.S. Leading Indicators Fall In February </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NEW YORK, April 4 (Xinhua) -- The Composite Index of Leading
Economic Indicators in the United States fell 0.3 percent in
February, following a strong performance in the previous three
months, the Conference Board said Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
The Board, a prominent research group, said the index fell to
106 in February from 106.3 in January.
</P>
<P>
"Signals for the immediate future point to continued expansion,
although not at the breakneck pace of the fourth quarter of 1999,"
said the Board's economist Ken Goldstein. The U.S. economy grew at
7.3 percent annual rate in the final quarter of 1999.
</P>
<P>
Goldstein said "The biggest risk to the ongoing expansion
continues to be interest-rate increases and the prospect of still
more Federal Reserve Board action."
"The data now suggest some sectors are beginning to respond to
Federal tightening, but certainly not enough to prevent the
economy from reaching new records for longevity," he added.
</P>
<P>
The composite indexes are the key elements in an analytic
system designed to signal peaks and troughs in the business cycle
in the next three to six months. The U.S. economy is in the 109th
consecutive month of expansion, surpassing the record of 106 month
expansion in 1960s.
</P>
<P>
The Conference Board said, eight of the ten indicators that
make up the leading index declined in February. The most
significant decreases are interest rate spread, building permits,
and new orders for nondefense capital goods. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
