<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-04 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Progress Against Poverty Calls for New Empowering Strategy </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
UNITED NATIONS, April 4 (Xinhua) -- A U.N. poverty report said
Tuesday that the world's poverty agenda remains adrift, and it
needs new focus and fresh approaches that are concentrated more on
governance and empowering people and less on social welfare.
</P>
<P>
"Old-school prescriptions of supplementing rapid growth with
social welfare and safety nets have proved inadequate," the report
authors said at a press conference here to introduce the report,
launched here Tuesday by the United Nations Development Program (
UNDP).
</P>
<P>
The report, "Overcoming Human Poverty: UNDP Poverty Report
2000," finds that five years after the commitments of World Social
Summit for Social Development, nations with genuine action plans
to end poverty, remain in the minority.
</P>
<P>
While over three-quarters of the world's poorer nations have
estimated the dimensions of poverty in their midst, fewer than one-
third have set targets for eradicating extreme poverty or
substantially reducing overall poverty.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, the wealthy donor countries have not backed up
their pro-poor rhetoric; they have been cutting back on aid and
failing to focus what remains on reducing poverty. They are
committed to debt relief, but not to helping poorer countries
trade more to pay off their debts.
</P>
<P>
"Much remains to be learned about how to make anti-poverty
plans effective," the authors said. Plans need to be comprehensive
-- based on much more than a few targeted projects.
</P>
<P>
Backed by funds and effective organization, a national plan
puts poverty on the public agenda. "A plan is evidence of a
national commitment and of an explicit allocation of resources to
the task," they said. "It is also a means to build a constituency
for change. Without such organized public action, market-driven
economies rarely promote social justice."
</P>
<P>
The report said, "Many donors still do not make poverty
reduction a priority, or know how to focus their resources on the
poor, or monitor their impact."
</P>
<P>
In the forward to the report, UNDP Administrator Mark Brown
stressed that "We should aim to help build up the capacities of
governments, at both national and local levels, to assume control
and direct their own poverty initiatives. This is the vitally
important capacity-building agenda for external assistance."
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE20000404.0051 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-04 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Gel Protect Rats' Hair Loss From Chemotherapy </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
The gel, a compound code-named GW8510, was developed by Stephen
Davis and his colleagues at Glaxo Wellcome. Lab tests on rats
showed it is safe and carries no side effects.
</P>
<P>
In the experiments, scientists gave rats a chemotherapy drug.
Without using the gel, 90 percent of the rats had hair loss.
GW8510 prevented hair loss totally in half of the rats.
</P>
<P>
The clear ointment works by inhibiting an enzyme that
stimulates cell divisions and thus temporarily stopping hair
follicles from dividing. As a result, the follicles are shielded
from the effects of chemotherapy.
</P>
<P>
Davis described the research at a meeting of the American
Association for Cancer Research in San Francisco this week.
</P>
<P>
He said that if further testing on human holds up, patients
would rub the gel into their hair before getting cancer treatment
and then wash it out a few hours later. Davis said it is not
absorbed into blood stream in rat trials. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
