<HEADLINE> German President Apologized for Nazi Atrocities in Greece </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>

<P>
ATHENS, April 4 (Xinhua) -- Visiting German President Johannes
Rau Tuesday apologized indirectly for the atrocities committed by
the Nazi occupation forces in Greece during the Second World War,
saying that he felt deep sorrow and shame.
</P>
<P>
Rau, along with his Greek counterpart Costis Stephanopoulos,
Tuesday visited the town of Kalavrita in southern Greece and laid
a wreath at the monument of the Greeks killed in 1943.
</P>
<P>
In one of the worst wartime massacres in Greece, the Nazi
occupation forces burned all the houses in Kalavrita and executed
1,436 males over the age of 15 on December 13, 1943.
</P>
<P>
The German president said that he came in Kalavrita to keep
the memory of this event alive in Germany.
</P>
<P>
"Here, at this place, I feel immense grief and shame, and only
one who knows and accepts his past can find the path to a better
future," said Rau, who arrived in Athens Monday for a three-day
official visit.
</P>
<P>
Early Tuesday, Rau also met with Greek Prime Minister Costas
Simitis in Athens and both sides described the relations between
the two countries as very good and positive, particularly in the
economic sector.
</P>
<P>
The German president will end his visit Wednesday and fly to
Turkey. 
</P>
</TEXT>
