<DOCNO> XIE20000404.0054 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-04 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> U.N. Reports "Miss Link" in Poverty Reduction </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
UNTIED NATIONS, April 4 (Xinhua) -- A new U.N. Development
Program (UNDP) poverty report Tuesday said that good economic
policies and growth are not enough for poverty reduction, and the
"miss link" between poverty and its reduction in scores of
developing countries and economies in transition is effective
governance institutions.
</P>
<P>
This is one of the main conclusions of "Overcoming Human
Poverty: UNDP Poverty Report 2000," a global report on human
deprivation and policies to reduce it. The report was launched
here Tuesday by UNDP.
</P>
<P>
The authors told a press conference here that even when a
country gets its poverty reduction policies right, "inept or
unresponsive governance can nullify the impact."
</P>
<P>
"When governments are unaccountable or corrupt, poverty
reduction programs have little success in targeting benefits," the
authors said. "The poor cannot gain a hearing for their views from
undemocratic and authoritarian political regimes."
</P>
<P>
"They cannot gain access to public services from an
unresponsive central bureaucracy -- or know that the services
exist if they lack information," the authors said.
</P>
<P>
The report maintains that the "bottom-line" requirement for
reducing poverty in any country is to have a government that is
accountable to people. It adds, however, that democracy alone is
not a "vaccination" against poverty.
</P>
<P>
The report argues for the decentralization of power to
municipal and community levels, but adds that holding government
officials accountable is a key function for civil society
organizations, ranging from community self-help groups to trade
unions and political parties.
</P>
<P>
"Without the continuous pressure of popular organizations,
democracy can be locked up and carted away with the ballot boxes
after each election," the report said.
</P>
<P>
In the final analysis, the authors said, rooting out poverty
requires that the "non-poor" give their support to the campaign,
but, most important, that the poor be sufficiently organized to
demand.
</P>
<P>
The report is rich in examples. They cover: anti-corruption
efforts in countries from Thailand to Uganda, to Bolivia and
Georgia, democratization through use of the Internet to share
information in Egypt, Jamaica, Mongolia and Ukraine, and the
decentralization of government power to communities in Ghana,
Kyrgyzstan, Morocco and Nepal. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE20000404.0055 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-04 </DATE_TIME>
