<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-04 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> World Bank: Growth Prospects for Developing World Look Stronger </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, April 4 (Xinhua) -- The average growth rate for
developing countries is likely to reach 4.6 percent in 2000, up
from 3.3 percent last year, and climb slightly to 4.8 percent in
2001-2002, as their economies start to recover from the 1997-98
global financial crisis, according to a new World Bank report
released Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
However, the report said that not all developing countries will
benefit equally in this recovery, which has been fuelled by
stronger than anticipated growth in industrial countries, an
exceptionally strong recovery in global trade, and higher
commodity prices.
</P>
<P>
Global Development Finance 2000, the World Bank's yearly report
on external financing prospects for developing and transition
countries, said that a much larger number of these countries will
record positive per capita growth in 2000 than in 1998/99.
</P>
<P>
But it warned that some 41 low-income countries, with a
combined population of more than 1 billion people, will barely
cross the threshold into positive growth. This underscores the
still fragile path of reform and recovery that lies ahead for
these countries, the report said.
</P>
<P>
"Developing countries are finally starting to recover from the
worst impact of the global crisis, but this recovery is uneven,"
said Uri Dadush, director of the World Bank's Prospects Group that
produces the annual Global Development Finance.
</P>
<P>
The report said net long-term flows from international capital
markets, including bank lending, bonds and portfolio equity flows,
to developing countries as a group fell in 1999 to levels last
seen in the early 1990s.
</P>
<P>
For the next few years, a gradual recovery is expected in such
capital markets flows, with gross flows rising from about 161
billion dollars in 1999 to around 185 billion dollars in 2000, and
to between 220-230 billion dollars in 2001. This would represent a
recovery to levels seen in 1995, but well below the extraordinary
levels experienced during the speculative bubble of 1996 and 1997,
in the run-up to the outbreak of the financial crisis.
</P>
<P>
In contrast, the report found that foreign direct investment
flows, which remained resilient during the crisis, have become the
single-largest and most stable source of long-term development
finance for developing countries. These flows have jumped from 35
billion U.S. dollars in 1991 to 131 billion dollars in 1996 and
192 billion dollars in 1999.
</P>
<P>
"It's time to reflect on the lessons of the crisis to better
protect the world economy in the future. One strong conclusion is
that we have to take steps therefore to reduce the downside of
capital volatility," said Dadush. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE20000404.0057 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-04 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> UNHCR Voices Concerns Over Refugees' Rights </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JOHANNESBURG, April 4 (Xinhua) -- The United Nations High
Commissioner for Refugees (UNHCR) on Tuesday voiced concern over
the "arbitrary" arrests of refugees as part of the national
police anti-crime operations.
</P>
<P>
The UNHCR said in a statement that treating refugees as
criminals violated the basic principles of international law.
</P>
<P>
The detentions also violated asylum seekers' rights to
protection and assistance in South Africa, it said.
</P>
<P>
In the past few days, the South African police have rounded up
 thousands of suspects involved in various crimes in a nationwide
crackdown on crimes. Press reports said many refugees from
neighboring countries were among those arrested.
</P>
<P>
"While the zeal with which this cleaning up operation is to be
admired and is indeed supported from many quarters, it is also a
violation of the basic principles of international law that
genuine asylum seekers and refugees have been rounded up with
criminal elements and treated as such," the statement said.
</P>
<P>
The UNHCR worked closely with the South African government to
draft terms of references to process asylum applications but more
needs to be done to ensure that junior officials and security
personnel be cognizant of refugees' rights, the statement said.
</P>
<P>
While the government played an exemplary role in assisting
South Africa' s neighbors in times of trouble, this example had to
be emulated by South African nationals, it said.
</P>
<P>
"The country must be seen to be practising what it preaches on
the continent as well as ensuring that civil servants, in
particular, are instrumental in upholding human rights in their
interaction with non- nationals," the statement said.
</P>
<P>
On Tuesday afternoon the office of the Gauteng Provincial
Commissioner reacted in a statement, saying a program to educate
members about protection of refugees was in place.
</P>
<P>
Police spokeswoman Henriette Bester said booklets and posters
had been distributed to all police stations and workshops "to
educate members" would be held throughout the province.
</P>
<P>
"Where abuses come to the attention of the police, it will be
investigated," said Bester.
</P>
<P>
"It needs to be mentioned that a number of illegal immigrants
arrested were in possession of false documentation," she added.
</P>
</TEXT>
