<HEADLINE> S.Africans to Observe Three Planets Together </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JOHANNESBURG, April 4 (Xinhua) -- South Africans have a rare
opportunity to see the planets Jupiter, Saturn and Mars together
shortly after sunset on Thursday, the South African Astronomical
Observatory said on Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
Viewers looking toward the northwestern horizon will see
Jupiter, the brightest of the three planets, directly below the
moon, and Mars slightly below and to the right of Jupiter, the
observatory said in a statement, adding that Saturn will be to the
right of the moon.
</P>
<P>
The best time to spot the planets will be between 20 and 30
minutes after sunset.
</P>
<P>
"All three planets and the moon will be quite low in the sky
even then. By an hour and a half after sunset, they'll be below
the horizon. If you wait too long, you'll miss the show," the
statement said. 
