<HEADLINE> S. Africa Plans to Sell 28 Tons of Ivory to Japan </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JOHANNESBURG, April 4 (Xinhua) -- Over 28 tons of ivory from
South Africa's Kruger National Park could soon be on its way to
Japan, South African Tourism and Environment Minister Valli Moosa
said on Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
The deal, which will be worth about 30 million rand (about five
million U.S. dollars), now depends on international acceptance of
a controversial South African proposal to allow a restricted sale
of the world-renowned game park's ivory stockpile.
</P>
<P>
The proposal will be presented by Moosa to the 11th conference
of the Convention on International Trade in Endangered Species
(CITES) in Nairobi, Kenya during April 10-20.
</P>
<P>
Speaking at a media briefing in Cape Town, Moosa said South
Africa's position on the sale of ivory is "very carefully
considered" and its proposal is modest.
</P>
<P>
"We are not interested in opening up a free trade in ivory. We
would be very concerned if you could walk down a street in Cape
Town or Johannesburg and purchase an elephant tusk."
</P>
<P>
South Africa is a very strong supporter and proponent of CITES
and will not be in favor of elephants being killed for their
ivory, he stressed.
</P>
<P>
However, South Africa's proposal has sparked strong protest
from some environmental pressure groups, which claimed that
illegal elephant poaching has risen since 1998 when CITES
delegates voted to allow an experimental sale of ivory from
Zimbabwe, Namibia and Botswana. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
