<HEADLINE> Africa-Europe Summit To be Held Every Three Years </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CAIRO, April 4 (Xinhua) -- African and European Union (EU)
leaders have decided to hold a summit every three years,
ministerial meeting each year and expert meeting every six months,
a diplomatic source said Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
The venue for the next summit will be moved to Europe, probably
Greece, the diplomatic source added.
</P>
<P>
This is the result of two sessions of discussions at the ongoing
Africa-Europe summit in Cairo that is involving leaders from most
of the 53 African countries and the 15-member EU.
</P>
<P>
At the first such summit, which opened Monday, African leaders
have strongly urged the summit to be held on a regular basis and
proposed once every three years with ministers meeting in between.
</P>
<P>
The two-day summit that will end Tuesday evening will cover a
wide range of political, economic and social development issues,
with an eye on forming a new and strategic relationship between the
two continents in the 21st century.
</P>
<P>
Seven of the 15 EU member states are former colonial powers in
Africa and the EU gives 15 billion U.S. dollars to Africa every
five years, more than any other single source.
</P>
<P>
Debt issue dominated the summit, with many African participating
countries putting their quest for debt reduction and cancellation
top of their lobbying. 
</P>
</TEXT>
