<HEADLINE> Robertson, Albright Stress Close Ties with Russia </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, April 4 (Xinhua) -- NATO Secretary-General Lord
Robertson and U.S. Secretary of State Madeleine Albright stressed
on Tuesday that NATO is resuming close ties with Russia under the
leadership of President-elect Vladimir Putin.
</P>
<P>
Speaking at a joint press conference following a meeting here,
Robertson called Russia a "strategic partner" with which NATO will
discuss common security problems.
</P>
<P>
The two met to prepare for NATO's meeting next month in Florence,
Italy. Robertson said European allies are assuming some of the
burden that has been carried disproportionally by the United
States in dealing with security problems in Europe.
</P>
<P>
The relationship between NATO and Moscow has been deteriorating
since the alliance conducted a 78-day air campaign against
Yugoslavia last year.
</P>
<P>
Earlier this year, Russia's Security Council approved a new
doctrine in February but it will not be published until an amended
version has been signed by President-elect Vladimir Putin.
</P>
<P>
The published draft doctrine says that Russia will use all
possible means, including nuclear weapons to ward off a foreign
aggression.
</P>
<P>
On Monday, Wesley Clark, NATO's Supreme Allied Commander in
Europe, said that the new doctrine, which upgrades the role of
nuclear weapons, was a step in the wrong direction and should be
revised. 
</P>
</TEXT>
