<HEADLINE> Europe Decides to Help Africa End Conflicts </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CAIRO, April 4 (Xinhua) -- European Union (EU) has decided to
help African nations settle their conflicts, Assistant Secretary-
General of the Organization of African Unity Daniel Antonio said
here Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
Antonio told Xinhua after the second session of the Europe-
Africa summit that the EU member states agreed to help the African
continent set up a mechanism for ending all their conflicts in the
region.
</P>
<P>
Wars and conflicts are raging in 14 of the 53 African countries,
leaving 8 million people as refugees and further worsening the
already fragile economic situation in the continent.
</P>
<P>
The OAU official also said that the EU countries agreed to
provide assistance in sweeping mines left over from the past wars.
</P>
<P>
There are an estimated 50 million mines scattered in 18 African
countries and about 250,000 African people have been killed in mine
explosions between 1961 and 1997.
</P>
<P>
He said that positive results have been produced in the
extensive consultations at the two-day summit, which is being
attended by leaders from more than 60 African and European
countries.
</P>
<P>
The summit that opened Monday is the first and biggest
conference between Africa and Europe with an aim to forge a new and
strategic relationship between the two continents.
</P>
<P>
But he noted that differences still remained on some issues and
the third session that will be held later in the afternoon, will
focus on the prospects of cooperation in economy, investment,
technology transfer. 
</P>
</TEXT>
