<HEADLINE> Turkey Exposes New Illegal Religious Group </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ANKARA, April 4 (Xinhua) -- The Provincial Directorate of
Security in Ankara has uncovered a new illegal pro-fundamentalist
organization named Jihad.
</P>
<P>
Security officials said Tuesday two extremists drove into the
Haskoy District of Ankara and put three pipe-bombs inside a trash
can, reported the Anatolia News Agency on Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
The two men were injured afterward when a bomb exploded
accidentally in their own car. They rushed to a hospital for
treatment, saying they injured themselves while cutting meat.
Suspicious, the doctors reported to hospital security guards who
called the anti-terrorism police.
</P>
<P>
During initial interrogation, the two men confessed their crime
and surrendered leaflets cursing "damned with secular infidels."
</P>
<P>
The security officials revealed that the extremists were members
of a new illegal organization named Jihad.
</P>
<P>
A total of 18 Jihad members had been arrested in operations
carried out by anti-terrorism police against their hideouts in the
Kecioren and Balgat Districts.
</P>
<P>
Three pistols, pipe-bombs and floppy discs were discovered in
the hideouts.
</P>
<P>
The security officials said Jihad was founded by those who
detected from other illegal pro-fundamentalist organizations such
as the Islamic Great Eastern Raiders-Front (IBDA-C), the Vasat and
the Hezbollah.
</P>
<P>
Jihad aims to establish a state based on the Islamic religious
Sharia Law, according to the officials.
</P>
<P>
Under the Turkish Constitution, Turkey is a Muslim-populated but
democratic and secular state. 
</P>
</TEXT>
