<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Chip Demand Expected to Rise in Double-digits </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
The Fabless Semiconductor Association, a group of 240 chip
companies that don't own their own factories, expects demand for
chip wafers, the underlying materials from which chips are made,
to increase 39 percent in 2000 and 48 percent in 2001.
</P>
<P>
In 1999, sales increased 55 percent, well above an expected 43
percent. The so-called fabless companies are strongest in the
communications market, which is experiencing a boom driven by the
growth of the Internet and cellular phones.
</P>
<P>
Contract chip makers are therefore more than doubling their
capacity expansions this year. About 54 percent of fabless company
sales are expected to be a communications-related this year,
compared with about 27 percent for the personal computer.
</P>
<P>
Fabless companies accounted for 8.3 percent of the world-wide
semiconductor industry's 1999 revenue of 144 billion U.S. dollars.
</P>
</TEXT>
