<HEADLINE> France Optimistic About Truce in Southern Lebanon </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
PARIS, April 4 (Xinhua) -- France expressed its optimism
Tuesday over a truce in southern Lebanon between Israel and the
Hezbollah guerrillas in near future following several months of
tit-for-tat attacks between them.
</P>
<P>
The assistant spokesman of the French Foreign Ministry,
Francois Rivasseau, said that French and U.S officials met with
Israeli officials Monday in Tel Aviv on a resumption of the
session of the Truce Monitoring Committee for Southern Lebanon
this week.
</P>
<P>
The committee's session has been suspended since February
because of Israeli protest over Hezbollah attacks upon Israeli
soldiers in the security zone in southern Lebanon.
</P>
<P>
"I am not in a position to precise a date for a meeting of the
committee, but we have good hope that our efforts could lead to
the results soon," said the spokesman.
</P>
<P>
The committee, established in 1996 after an Israeli operation
in Lebanon, consists of the United States, France, Israel, Syria
and Lebanon.
</P>
<P>
It supervises a truce agreement which calls on both Israel and
Hezbollah to avoid attacking civilian targets. 
