<HEADLINE> Xinhua World News Summary at GMT1500, April 4 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ADDIS ABABA -- The wild fire in the Bale region, about 250
kilometers south of Addis Ababa, has been put out completely by
earlier this week, the Ethiopian Herald newspaper reported Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
The one-month-and-half-old fire is now completely under control
following a fire-fighting campaign launched by more than 36,000
farmers, students and other sections of the society, the report
quoted a local official as saying. (BC-Ethiopia-Fire)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
CAIRO -- The United States has decided to sell Egypt short-
range missiles to upgrade the Northern African country's air
defense capability, U.S. Defense Secretary William Cohen said here
on Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
The U.S. will provide Egypt with short-range surface-launched
missiles of a new air-defense system, Cohen told reporters after
meeting with Egyptian President Hosni Mubarak. (BC-Egypt-US-Arms)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
TOKYO -- Japanese Prime Minister Keizo Obuchi's cabinet
resigned en masse Tuesday evening to pave the way for Obuchi's
successor to form a new cabinet.
</P>
<P>
Yoshiro Mori, secretary general and the No. 2 figure of Japan's
ruling Liberal Democratic Party (LDP), is most likely to succeed
Obuchi as party leader and hence Japanese prime minister,
political sources said.
</P>
<P>
At 7 p.m. (1000 GMT) the cabinet convened an emergency session
at which all ministers resigned. (BC-Japan-Cabinet-Mori)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
BANGKOK -- The Thai government will conduct a minor cabinet
reshuffle next week, Prime Minister Chuan Leekpai announced here
Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
Chuan told reporters after a weekly cabinet meeting that he had
personally discussed a cabinet reshuffle with leaders of the
ruling coalition parties.  (BC-Thailand-Reshuffle) 
</P>
