<DOCNO> XIE20000404.0087 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-04 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Fair Competition Stressed for Advertising Sector </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, April 4 (Xinhua) -- China has stepped up efforts to
combat irregularities involving advertisements released through
various channels, to promote fair competition in this booming
sector.
</P>
<P>
China's advertising industry has registered double-digit
growth in annual turnover for two consecutive years, earning 62.2
billion yuan in 1999 alone, sources at the State Administration of
Industry and Commerce (SAIC) said.
</P>
<P>
The number of advertising firms has been surging since 1992,
and had reached 36,000 by the end of 1999. Other advertising units
include TV stations, radio stations, newspapers and magazines.
Currently, some 58,000 people are working in the sector.
</P>
<P>
However, illegal practices, including fake advertisements, have
cropped up. China handled 51,494 advertisement malpractice cases
in 1999, up 36.6 percent from 1998. Fake advertisement accounted
for some 10 percent.
</P>
<P>
"China enacted its Advertisement Law in 1995, and since then a
number of rampant illegalities have been effectively curbed, such
as fake tobacco ads" said Wang Jinjie, a SAIC official in charge
of advertisement supervision.
</P>
<P>
"However, the proportion of fake drugs, medical service and
food advertisements has been increasing rapidly, now accounting
for the lion's share of all fake ads," he noted.
</P>
<P>
He attributed the surge mainly to the emergence of new media
channels and new marketing patterns, such as the Internet.
</P>
<P>
"This has made supervision more difficult, as there is yet no
specific law to regulate these new ads," Wang pointed out.
</P>
<P>
The SAIC is drafting new regulations to monitor advertisement
contents and new marketing activities, especially Internet ads and
TV ads, according to Wang.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
