<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-04 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China Drafting Action Plan to Clean Polluted Sea </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
According to Wang Jirong, vice director of the State
Environmental Protection Administration of China (SEPA), the SEPA
is formulating the plan following a recent joint investigation of
the pollution situation in the Bohai sea by central and local
government departments as well as the Chinese Navy.
</P>
<P>
A special report on the investigation's findings was submitted
to the central government by the provinces of Liaoning, Hebei and
Shandong and the coastal city of Tianjin (which are all located on
the Bohai Rim), the Ministry of Communications, the Ministry of
Agriculture, the Chinese Navy, and the State Maritime
Administration of China.
</P>
<P>
The Bohai Sea covers 77,000 sq km, and an annual discharge of 3.
8 billion tons of waste water, much of it untreated, into it has
resulted in a serious deterioration of the water there during the
past decade.
</P>
<P>
The waste water has caused frequent red tides and rapid
depletion of the Bohai fish stocks.
</P>
<P>
Less than 40 percent of waste water is treated in urban China,
and a growing number of cities are building sewage treatment
plants with or without overseas funds.
</P>
<P>
Efforts to reduce land-based industrial pollutants in areas
surrounding the Bohai Sea began last year. 
</P>
</TEXT>
