<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-04 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Iran Assures Fair Trial of Jews, Rejects Foreign Meddling </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TEHRAN, April 4 (Xinhua) -- Iran said on Tuesday that its
judiciary will handle independently the case of Jews arrested on
spy charges and it is opposed to any foreign intervention in the
issue.
</P>
<P>
Foreign Ministry spokesman Hamid Reza Asefi told reporters that
any pressure from any countries will be rejected in order that the
accused can get a fair trial.
</P>
<P>
He was responding to remarks by a French counterpart, who said
Paris and its European partners would follow the case with great
care, in addition to repeatedly announcing their great concern.
</P>
<P>
The 13 Jews, arrested last year along with eight Muslims, were
charged with spying for the United State and Israel, both of whom
denied any link with them. They will face the death penalty if
found guilty.
</P>
<P>
Asefi said the trial is a domestic issue, and any intervention
and prejudgment regarding the case should be rejected, the official
Islamic Republic News Agency (IRNA) reported.
</P>
<P>
The policy of Iran is based on securing rights of all citizens,
and judicial officials have assured that the rights of Iranian Jews
will be respected during the legal proceedings, Asefi said.
</P>
<P>
The accused will be dealt with fairly, he said. Three of the 13
charged are currently free on bail.
</P>
<P>
The Ministry of Justice said on Monday that the trial, due to
start on April 13, could be postponed. "If the lawyers of the 13
accused needed more time to prepare their defense, the court would
grant the request," a ministry spokesman said.
</P>
<P>
The trial is to take place in one of the revolutionary courts,
which hear all national security cases. It can be an open trial or
behind closed doors, with the judge deciding the nature of the
trial.
</P>
<P>
The case has attracted international attention, while Iranian
authorities, including President Mohammed Khatami, have insisted
they receive a fair trial and warned other countries against "
interfering" in Iran's affairs. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE20000404.0095 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-04 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Israel to Revive Talks on Importing Egypt Natural Gas </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JERUSALEM, April 4 (Xinhua) -- Israeli Minister of National
Infrastructure Eli Suissa is scheduled to meet Egyptian officials
in Cairo next week to revive talks on the purchase of natural gas
from Egypt, a ministry official said Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
Although he had not made a final decision on the import, Suissa
expressed his inclination to accede to Egyptians' requests in
recent weeks, the official revealed without elaborating on those
requests.
</P>
<P>
The project has been discussed over the past six years, under
which Egypt would sell natural gas to Jerusalem by extending its "
pipeline of peace" into Israeli territories.
</P>
<P>
The pipeline is currently being constructed from the Nile Delta
to El Arish in the Sinai Peninsula, some 25 kilometers from Israel
borderlines. It is designed to provide gas to the Palestinian self-
rule areas, Jordan and in the future possibly to Lebanon, Syria and
Turkey.
</P>
<P>
The Egyptian-Israeli talks on the project are contingent upon
the progress of the Middle East peace process.
</P>
<P>
As part of the Camp David peace accord signed with Egypt in
1979, Israel is allowed to import 2 million tons of oil from Egypt.
In the past three years, however, the imports were reduced for "
commercial reasons," or the chill in bilateral relations during the
reign of former Israeli Prime Minister Benjamin government.
</P>
<P>
Last December, Egyptian government finally agreed to sell
natural gas to Israel, a decision coming shortly after the Israeli-
Syrian peace talks were resumed.
</P>
<P>
But the commercial negotiations proceeded very slowly and were
temporarily frozen by Suissa last month, as his ministry officials
referred to the Egyptians as "not being serious negotiators" by
making exorbitant requests and intentional delay.
</P>
<P>
Israeli oil companies, which had announced a series of initial
gas discoveries off Israeli waters near Ashdod and Ashkelon, two
coastal towns south of Tel Aviv, have been lobbying extensively
against the gas import.
</P>
<P>
Three recent drillings there indicate that Israel can meet its
own natural gas needs for the next 15 years, thus there is no need
for the Egyptian gas anymore, according to these companies.
</P>
<P>
They launched a campaign in recent months to press the
government to halt negotiations with Egypt, saying the import could
deal a severe blow to local gas-exploration industry and harm
national interests.
</P>
<P>
Some analysts disagreed, however, saying that it is still too
early to determine the amount of natural gas that those areas can
provide and any additional suppliers would be welcome.
</P>
<P>
Amit Mor, director of a leading Israeli consulting group on
energy and environmental issues, said that more suppliers would
only enhance competition and reduce gas prices, which have a direct
effect on economic development.
</P>
<P>
To echo Mor's views, the Ha'aretz daily reported on Tuesday that
Suissa's decision on resuming the negotiations with Egypt has sent
a signal to Israeli gas providers that their exclusivity is not
guaranteed.
</P>
<P>
Egyptian officials were quoted recently as saying that natural
gas reserves in Egypt could amount to 120 trillion cubic feet
(about 3.24 trillion cubic meters), enough to meet the country's
domestic needs for 100 years.
</P>
<P>
Industry experts say importing natural gas, a cleaner and
cheaper fuel than oil or coal, from Egypt would save Israel 150
million U.S. dollars annually as compared to any viable
alternative. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE20000404.0096 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-04 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Chirac Calls Africa-Europe Summit Important, Urges Joint Development </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CAIRO, April 4 (Xinhua) -- French President Jacques Chirac
Tuesday termed the ongoing Africa-Europe summit as "important"
while urging joint development in economic globalization.
</P>
<P>
Chirac said at a press conference on the sidelines of the
Africa-Europe summit that "the summit is important when assessing
the results" because it enabled the Europe to better understand
Africa and African leaders to speak and meet with European
officials.
</P>
<P>
Heads of state or government, or their representatives from most
of 53 African states and the 15 European Union members are
participating in the two-day summit.
</P>
<P>
The first and biggest gathering between Africa and Europe under
the aegis of the Organization of African Unity and the EU opened
Monday in Cairo International Conference Center.
</P>
<P>
On African debt issue that dominated the summit, Chirac,
acknowledging debt is a "drawback and hindrance to development,"
stressed that debt reduction should be beneficial to both debtors
and creditors.
</P>
<P>
He pointed out that the most indebted poor African states will
take priority in debt forgiveness and the medium-income countries
should pay back, at least part of their debts.
</P>
<P>
Outcries for debt reduction or cancellation from the EU, the
major creditor of Africa, are strong among the African leaders at
the summit. The African countries are spending 23 billion dollars,
or 30.9 percent of their exports, every year to service the
staggering 350 billion dollars of debts.
</P>
<P>
France Monday announced to cancel debts of the poorest countries
within one or two years. Germany and Morocco also decided to make
contributions to the African debt relief.
</P>
<P>
At the conference, he also criticized the so-called Afro-
pessimists," saying they do not know the reality of Africa and
their ideas are "misleading and wrong" and are "one tree hides the
whole forest."
</P>
<P>
He said that Africa has achieved a 5 percent economic growth,
surpassing its demographic growth, and there are increased
democracy and real progress in good governance there.
</P>
<P>
He urged French investors to go on to invest in Africa, not to
be influenced by those "Afro-pessimists."
</P>
<P>
France, the former colonial power in Africa, has close
relationship with Africa, especially the French-speaking African
countries. The Franco-African summit between France and French
speaking African countries is held on an annual basis.
</P>
<P>
On globalization, Chirac urged control of its negative effect,
promoting the development of poor countries and avoiding
marginalizing them. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
