<HEADLINE> Japan's Three Parties to Form Coalition Under New Prime Minister </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TOKYO, April 4 (Xinhua) -- Japan's three parties agreed Tuesday
to form a new coalition government under a successor to outgoing
Prime Minister Keizo Obuchi who remains in a coma after suffering
a stroke Sunday, party officials said.
</P>
<P>
Secretaries general of the three parties, the Liberal
Democratic Party (LDP), the New Komeito party and the newly
launched Conservative Party (CP), reached the accord in a meeting
earlier in the day, the officials said.
</P>
<P>
The three parties agreed to carry on the Obuchi cabinet's basic
policy line. Leaders of the three parties will meet Wednesday to
confirm the agreement, the officials said.
</P>
<P>
LDP secretary Yoshiro Mori, who is expected to succeed Obuchi
to become party president and prime minister Wednesday, proposed
in the meeting to proceed with the policies agreed in the previous
coalition government and asked for the CP's cooperation in that
line, the officials said, adding that CP secretary general Takeshi
Noda accepted the request.
</P>
<P>
The Conservative Party was formed Monday following the breakup
of the Liberal Party, which ended its coalition with the LDP and
the New Komeito Saturday.
</P>
<P>
Obuchi's cabinet resigned en masse Tuesday evening as Obuchi
remains in a coma and is unlikely to recover in near future.
</P>
</TEXT>
