<HEADLINE> China, Vietnam Vow to Promote Ties (1) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, April 4 (Xinhua) -- China will, as always, make
efforts to develop its good-neighborly and friendly relations with
Vietnam, according to Chinese top legislator Li Peng here today.
</P>
<P>
In afternoon talks with Nong Duc Manh, chairman of the National
Assembly of Vietnam, Li, chairman of China's National People's
Congress (NPC) Standing Committee, said that the NPC places great
importance on its friendship and cooperation with Vietnam's
National Assembly. He added that he hoped that the two sides would
promote exchanges and learn from each other.
</P>
<P>
Extending a welcome to Nong Duc Manh and his delegation, Li
called Nong Duc Manh, who visited China in 1994, an old friend,
and said that he was very happy to meet Nong Duc Manh in Beijing.
</P>
<P>
Nong Duc Manh expressed his thanks for Li's invitation for him
to visit China again.
</P>
<P>
Li said that relations between the two parties and countries
have been rapidly restored and comprehensively developed since the
normalization of Sino-Vietnamese relations more than eight years
ago, adding that top leaders of the two countries have had
exchanges of visits and reached consensus on major issues in
bilateral relations, thus playing an irreplaceable role in pushing
forward the smooth development of relations between the two
parties and countries, and properly solving issues left over by
history.
</P>
<P>
He described the signing of a land border treaty between the
two countries on December 30 last year as a major event in
bilateral relations, and said that China hopes that the Sino-
Vietnamese land border will serve as a bridge of peace, friendship
and stability between the people of the two countries.
</P>
<P>
Nong Duc Manh said that Vietnam speaks highly of the treaty,
which benefits the two peoples.
</P>
<P>
Li said the two countries share similar national conditions,
with both adhering to the leadership of the communist party and
socialism, and as well as reform and opening up, adding that there
exists enormous potential for cooperation.
</P>
<P>
Li also recalled his two visits to Vietnam in the 1990s, and
said that Vietnam's achievements in its renovation and opening up
as well as construction left him with a deep impression.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
