<HEADLINE> No One Against Israel's Withdrawal: Hezbollah </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIRUT, April 4 (Xinhua) -- No one in Lebanon disapproves
Israeli troop withdrawal from south Lebanon, said a senior leader
of the Lebanese Hezbollah guerillas on Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
Sheik Naim Qassem, deputy secretary general of Hezbollah, or
Party of God, described Israel's planned complete withdrawal by
July as a victory for Lebanon's resistance movement and Palestinian
cause, the People's Voice radio reported.
</P>
<P>
Commenting on what the Israeli government claimed "Lebanon's
reluctance to Israel's withdrawal," the Hezbollah leader said that
it reflected the Jewish state's fearfulness in which they have
lived all along.
</P>
<P>
Israel carved out a self-styled 15-kilometer-deep security zone
in south Lebanon in 1985 with a claimed aim of protecting its
northern border from cross-border guerrilla attacks.
</P>
<P>
The Israeli cabinet on March 5 passed Prime Minister Ehud
Barak's plan to pullout its troops from south Lebanon with or
without framework agreement with Lebanon and Syria, the main power
broker in Lebanon.
</P>
<P>
The Iranian- and Syrian- backed Hezbollah is spearheading a war
of attrition against Israel's occupation in south Lebanon. It has
repeatedly reiterated that the guerrilla will not cease fire until
Israel withdraws completely from the occupied land. 
</P>
</TEXT>
