<DOCNO> XIE20000404.0115 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-04 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> French President Terms Africa-Europe Summit as " Important" </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CAIRO, April 4 (Xinhua) -- French President Jacques Chirac
Tuesday hailed the Africa-Europe summit as an important event,
saying through the meeting Europe better understood Africa and
African leaders got an opportunity to speak and meet with European
officials.
</P>
<P>
Chirac made the remarks at a press conference Tuesday on the
fringe of the first Africa-Europe summit that befalls on Monday and
Tuesday and was attended by heads of state or government, or their
representatives from most of the 53 African states and the 15-
member European Union (EU).
</P>
<P>
Chirac said he only "partly agrees with analysis that the summit
is superficial," and he thinks "it is important when assessing the
results."
</P>
<P>
On African debt issue that dominated the summit, Chirac,
acknowledging debt is a "drawback and hindrance to development,"
stressed that debt reduction should be beneficial to both debtors
and creditors.
</P>
<P>
Outcries for debt reduction or cancellation from the EU, the
major creditor of Africa, are strong among the African leaders at
the summit. The total debts have reached 350 billion U.S. dollars
in 1999 and the African countries are spending 23 billion dollars,
or 30.9 percent of their exports, every year to service the debts.
</P>
<P>
Chirac said Monday night that France will cancel debts of the
poorest countries within one or two years.
</P>
<P>
Portuguese Foreign Minister Jaime Gama also announced Monday
night that Germany and Morocco will make contributions to the
African debt relief.
</P>
<P>
At Tuesday's press conference, Chirac urged other European
states to follow the lead on debt issue.
</P>
<P>
But he also noted the debt forgiveness or reduction should be
carried out in a process of gradualness. The poorer and most
indebted countries will take the priority and the medium-income
states should pay back or at least repay part of their debts, he
added. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
