<HEADLINE> Thailand to Launch Agricultural Warning System </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BANGKOK, April 4 (Xinhua) -- The Thai government will soon
launch the country's first warning system for the agricultural
sector, a senior Agriculture and Cooperatives Ministry official
said here Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
Rachai Cholasinsongkramchai, director of the Planning and
Special Programs Division of the ministry, was quoted by Thailand
News Agency as saying that the planned warning system is expected
to be launched next year.
</P>
<P>
The system is aimed at providing local farmers with updated
agricultural information and reports on changing situations and
possible problems that may affect the production and sale of their
products, he said.
</P>
<P>
The system will also help reduce the government's budget on
assisting victims of natural disasters each year, Rachai said.
</P>
<P>
The warning system will cover six key disasters, including
drought, flood, storm, forest fire, plant epidemics and animal
epidemics.
</P>
<P>
The Agriculture and Cooperatives Ministry is cooperating with
the Asian Institute of Technology in studying and planning the
system, he said. 
</P>
