<HEADLINE> EU Urged to Invest More in Africa </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JOHANNESBURG, April 4 (Xinhua) -- South African President Thabo
Mbeki Tuesday urged the European Union (EU) to invest more in the
African continent.
</P>
<P>
The African continent needs "ample supplies" of capital to
provide for infrastructure, industrialization and modernization,
said Mbeki while addressing delegates from 15 European and 52
African nations attending a two-day European Union-Africa summit
in Cairo, Egypt.
</P>
<P>
"We seek the agreement of our European friends that
extraordinary measures will have to be taken to encourage larger
foreign direct investment inflows into Africa," he was quoted as
saying by South African Press Association.
</P>
<P>
He said that in many African countries, progress has been made
in areas that are important for the creation of a climate
conducive to foreign direct investment.
</P>
<P>
These include trade liberalization, the strengthening of the
rule of law, improvements in legal and other instruments, as well
as the telecommunications and transport infrastructure, he said.
</P>
<P>
According to Mbeki, foreign direct investment is crucial to
Africa's economic growth and development, but Africa's share of
foreign direct investment among developing countries declined from
more than 11 percent during the period of 1976-1980 to four
percent in 1996-1997. 
</P>
</TEXT>
