<HEADLINE> JMC Calls for Cessation of Hostilities in Congo </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KAMPALA, April 4 (Xinhua) -- The Joint Military Commission
(JMC) set up under the Lusaka cease-fire agreement opened its
sixth session here Tuesday morning with a call for all involved
parties to cease hostility and disengage their military forces in
the Democratic Republic of the Congo (DRC).
</P>
<P>
"It is high time that we reaffirm our commitment for the total
cessation of hostilities," said Acting JMC Chairman Timothy
Kazembe, a Zambian brigadier general, in his opening speech.
</P>
<P>
"I am appealing to the Political Committee and the parties here
present to assure their responsibilities so that effective
cessation of hostilities and disengagement of forces on the ground
is achieved," he stressed.
</P>
<P>
He said the people in the DRC should be relied on for their
political will and resolve in the implementation of the Lusaka
cease-fire agreement inked by all parties to the 19-month-long
armed conflict.
</P>
<P>
According to Kazembe, "the sixth plenary session of the JMC is
an evaluation meeting whose crucial agenda items cover immediate
cessation of hostilities and disengagement plan, and review of JMC
activities."
</P>
<P>
The two-day meeting is expected to review the reported
violations of cease-fire and come out with some recommendations in
this respect.
</P>
<P>
The first plenary meeting of the JMC was held here during
October 12-14, 1999, at which all parties identified common
positions on the map as well as the numerous cases of cease-fire
violations. 
</P>
</TEXT>
