<HEADLINE> Uganda to Withdraw Troops in Congo: Minister </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KAMPALA, April 4 (Xinhua) -- Ugandan State Minister for
Regional Cooperation Amama Mbabazi said here Tuesday morning that
all foreign forces including Ugandan army would withdraw from the
Democratic Republic of the Congo (DRC) under the Lusaka
cease-fire agreement.
</P>
<P>
He made the remarks to several reporters after officially
opening the sixth plenary session of the Joint Military Commission
(JMC). Earlier, there were reports saying that Ugandan troops
deployed in the DRC would be part of the United Nations
peacekeeping forces.
</P>
<P>
Uganda is deeply concerned about the deteriorating security
situation in the third largest African country, Mbabazi said,
urging the JMC to prepare a contingency plan to implement the
Lusaka accord even in the absence of the United Nations or
international community.
</P>
<P>
He reaffirmed Uganda's commitment to the peace accord and urged
all parties to the conflict to implement the agreement fully.
</P>
<P>
The two-day JMC meeting would be followed by a meeting of the
Joint Political Committee of which Mbabazi is the chairman.
</P>
<P>
There have been reports of continuous violations of the
cease-fire agreement in the DRC, casting doubt over the prospects
of its full implementation. 
</P>
