<DOCNO> XIE20000404.0126 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-04 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Euro-zone Unemployment Rate Unchanged  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BRUSSELS, April 4 (Xinhua) -- The euro zone unemployment rate
remained unchanged at 9.5 percent in February this year, the same
as a revised rate for January, the European Union's statistical
office Eurostat said Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
The figure was slightly lower than that of the same month in
1999, when 10.3 percent of the workforce were jobless.
</P>
<P>
About 12.4 million men and women were unemployed in the 11-
country euro zone and 15.0 million in the 15-nation EU area in
February, the Eurostat said. Across the EU, the figure was 18
million in March 1997, 17 million in May 1998 and 16 million in
March 1999.
</P>
<P>
The figures are seasonally-adjusted in line with criteria of
the International Labor Organization.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, the EU as a whole recorded a jobless rate of 8.8
percent in February, the same as a month earlier. The rate in
February 1999 was 9.5 percent.
</P>
<P>
According to the Eurostat, the lowest rates were registered in
Luxembourg (2.2 percent), the Netherlands, and Austria, while the
highest rate was still recorded in Spain with 15.2 percent.
</P>
<P>
However, unemployment decreased in all EU member states in the
last 12 months, and notable relative falls were recorded in the
Netherlands (from 3.8 percent to 2.7 percent) and Ireland (from 6.
4 percent to 5.1 percent).
</P>
<P>
The euro zone comprises Belgium, Germany, Spain, France,
Ireland, Italy, Luxembourg, Netherlands, Austria, Portugal and
Finland. Britain Sweden, Denmark and Greece are the EU members not
in the euro zone. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
