<HEADLINE> Major Chinese Development Zone Draws Overseas Investors </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
QINGDAO, April 4 (Xinhua) -- The Qingdao Economic and
Technological Development Zone, a state-level development zone in
east China's Shandong Province, has drawn an increasing number of
overseas investors since it was established in 1985.
</P>
<P>
The latest statistics show investors from more than 50
countries, including France, Sweden and Japan, have set up 1,126
businesses in the zone, with combined overseas capital of about 2.
24 billion US dollars.
</P>
<P>
Of these businesses, 15 were funded by 12 of the world's top
500 corporations.
</P>
<P>
Overseas-funded enterprises have helped the zone create eight
pillar industries, including electrical home appliances, bio-
pharmaceutical products, machinery and chemical fibers.
</P>
<P>
Local analysts attributed the rapid growth in overseas
investment in the zone to the improving business environment.
</P>
<P>
The zone has set the goal of operating in accordance with
international practices. More than 20 regulations have been issued
to ensure standardized administration of the zone.  
</P>
</TEXT>
