<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-04 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Archeologists Uncover Well-preserved Ancient Corpse </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CHANGSHA, April 4 (Xinhua) -- Chinese archeologists have
uncovered the well preserved body of a woman who died 400 years
ago.
</P>
<P>
The body was unearthed in Hengyang City, in central China's
Hunan province.
</P>
<P>
The woman is estimated to have been 1.60 meters tall when she
was alive. However, she has now shrunk to 1.54 meters.
Archeologists say she died at the age of about 50.
</P>
<P>
A forensic investigation at the Hengyang Medical College found
that the thorax was full of mercury, which had been used as a
preservative. The left lung showed traces of a serious disease,
such as tuberculosis or a tumor.
</P>
<P>
The tomb was found on March 23 by workers of a foreign trade
company who were constructing a warehouse.
</P>
<P>
In the same tomb were the badly decomposed remains of a man,
the coffin of whom had been damaged.
</P>
<P>
A large quantity of clothing made of silk, flax and cotton,
delicately woven with colorful patterns, was also found in the
tomb.
</P>
<P>
The man seems to have been a Ming Dynasty army officer.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
