<HEADLINE> U.S. to Sell Egypt New Air-Defense System: Cohen </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CAIRO, April 4 (Xinhua) -- The United States has decided to sell
Egypt short-range missiles to upgrade the Northern African
country's air defense capability, U.S. Defense Secretary William
Cohen said here on Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
The U.S. will provide Egypt with short-range surface-launched
missiles of a new air-defense system, Cohen told reporters after
meeting with Egyptian President Hosni Mubarak.
</P>
<P>
"When fielded, the missile system will update Egypt's air
defense system by replacing an older Russian-made missile, the SAM-
6," he said.
</P>
<P>
Cohen arrived here on Monday from Israel for a two-day visit and
left after for Jordan after the meeting with Mubarak. He will also
visit Persian Gulf states in his annual Mideast tour.
</P>
<P>
A Pentagon statement said the missiles can be launched from a
mobile unit on the ground and is intended to improve Egypt's short-
range air defense capability.
</P>
<P>
It would also help complement U.S. capability and enhance
Egypt's ability to participate in future combined force operations,
the statement added.
</P>
<P>
Cohen said the two sides still have to work out details of the
sale, including timing of delivery. "In terms of what it will cost,
that is too early to say at this point," he said.
</P>
<P>
When he visited Cairo in March 1999, Cohen announced plans to
sell Egypt 3.2 billion U.S. dollars of military hardware, including
24 F-16 warplanes, 200 M-1A1 tanks and 32 Patriot-3 missiles.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
