<DOCNO> XIE20000404.0133 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-04 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Roundup: Manila Backs Estrada Amid Coup Rumors by Pan Jiaxu </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MANILA, April 4 (Xinhua) -- Manila Mayor Lito Atienza on
Tuesday voiced solid support to President Joseph Estrada and his
administration amid a domestic political wave to undermine his
presidency.
</P>
<P>
Atienza expressed his position by signing a manifesto
supporting the administration of Estrada, whom reports said has
been the "subject of mudslinging or character assassination."
</P>
<P>
Atienza, along with other city leaders including councilors,
community heads and congressmen who signed the manifesto, said the
spate of attacks against the presidency could slow down the
country's economic recovery.
</P>
<P>
"We are calling on our constituents and all concerned citizens
to speak up in the defense of what the people truly want -- an
opportunity to be economically productive without being subjected
to a daily dose of propaganda to discredit the president and the
presidency," he said.
</P>
<P>
Propaganda efforts to undermine the presidency in particular
and the government in general, Atienza said, could only benefit
few --armed organized groups and those with a political agenda.
</P>
<P>
Recently, rumors of a coup are back, abetted by groups calling
for the resignation of President Estrada.
</P>
<P>
On Monday, the Philippine Senate's minority leader Terofidto
Guingona urged President Estrada to resign before the nation
plunged into "more protests, more convulsions and possible chaos."
</P>
<P>
Earlier, reports said former Commissioner of the National
Telecommunication Commission Linggoy Alcuaz was also spearheading
a campaign calling for the resignation of Estrada.
</P>
<P>
According to Alcuaz, he has close links with the Reform of the
Armed Forces Movement which launched six failed coup attempts
against the Aquino government from 1986 to 1989.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, an amorphous group of "concerned" citizens launched
Monday a "silent protest," whose symbol is a white, slanted
exclamation mark against a black background.
</P>
<P>
The protesters were complaining of what they called the "
disappointing governance" of the Estrada administration, alleging
that the government has been hit by "corruption, cronyism and the
failure to eradicate poverty."
</P>
<P>
On the other hand, the presidential palace accused the camp of
former President Fidel Ramos of orchestrating the campaign to
topple the Estrada administration.
</P>
<P>
A ranking official of the Defense Department alleged that
officials of the Ramos administration had joined forces with the"
silent protest" movement in denouncing the government.
</P>
<P>
However, Estrada's supporters pointed out that two years is too
short a period for deciding that a president must be replaced,
adding that Estrada has a constitutionally guaranteed tenure of
four more years.
</P>
<P>
According to Foreign Secretary Domingo Siazon, foreign
diplomats here did not express interest in the coup rumors.
</P>
<P>
"They have been able to read through the lines in the
Philippine news press. They know that some headlines are made to
sell newspapers," he said.
</P>
<P>
Anyway, the military is reportedly solid behind President
Estrada.
</P>
<P>
"The military is solid behind the president. The military is
solid behind the constitution and the constitutionally-elected
authorities,"Deputy Chief of Staff Jose Calimlim of the Armed
Forces of the Philippines said over the weekend.
</P>
<P>
To the presidential palace's relief, results of a quarterly
survey issued Monday by the Social Weather Station showed that
Estrada's nationwide approval rating did not drop to the negative
level but remained at 5 percent, the same level as last December.
</P>
<P>
However, earlier last month, some reports quoted results of
less comprehensive surveys as saying Estrada's rating had dropped
to the negative. Such reports had added up to the negative impact
on the image of the president.
</P>
<P>
The results of the Social Weather Station, a nationwide
pollster,are deemed here as a more comprehensive and accurate
gauge of the people's sentiment. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
