<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-04 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Malaysia Formulates Governance Framework for Insurance Industry </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KUALA LUMPUR, April 4 (Xinhua) -- Malaysia's central bank (Bank
Negara) is formulating a framework of good corporate governance
for the insurance industry, the bank's Assistant Governor Zamani
Abdul Ghani said Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
The framework in line with the government's effort to nurture
good governance practices in the corporate sector will embody
several of the principal and best practices dealing with the
duties and responsibilities of directors as spelt out in the
Malaysian Code of Corporate Governance, he said here at a two-day
conference on corporate governance.
</P>
<P>
He said the framework would establish basic principles of good
corporate governance in other key organizational aspects of
insurance operations including management accountability,
corporate independence, internal controls, operational risk
management, public accountability and financial and management
reporting.
</P>
<P>
He said sound corporate governance is important for broadening
and deepening local capital markets by attracting domestic
institutional and individual investors apart from long-term
foreign capital.
</P>
<P>
In addition, good corporate governance practices are now
becoming a necessity for every country and business enterprise and
no longer restricted to the activities of public-listed
corporations in advanced economies, he added.
</P>
<P>
Zamani said the financial crisis that hit the East Asian
economies has highlighted the importance of good corporate
governance and best business practices to many countries in this
region.
</P>
<P>
There is a growing recognition that good corporate governance
is essential to protecting the interests of investors,
shareholders, bankers and insurers and the public at large, he
said.
</P>
<P>
He said the recent volatility and instability experienced by
emerging markets highlighted weak management practices and poor
control and governance on the part of the board of directors,
which in turn contributed to the financial collapse of many large
companies.
</P>
<P>
The practice of good corporate governance demands a sense of
conviction and commitment from the board of directors and senior
management to ensure that the interests of all parties are
protected, he added. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
