<DOCNO> XIE20000404.0137 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-04 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Roundup: Angola-IMF Accord to Benefit Angolan Economy </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
The accord means a start of the new cooperation between Angola
and the IMF, which followed the bitter memory of the aborted
monitored accord signed in 1998 due to the recrudescence of the
civil war.
</P>
<P>
According to the Angolan financial authorities, with the aim to
 stabilize and relaunch the economy, the two sides signed the
accord, following a series of negotiations resumed last year.
</P>
<P>
Experts said that the program will help improve the country's
external credibility, its institutional capacity and create
conditions for the development of the national economy.  The
accord also include the improvement of the living standard of the
Angolan population, reshuffle of the country's external debt and
the access to loans for funding its economic and social
development under advantageous terms.
</P>
<P>
According to the Angolan finance minister Joaquim David and
the head of the IMF's African and Middle East division Paulo, the
accord is valid until December of this year.
</P>
<P>
David said that the program, which was drafted by the Angolan
government in 1999 with the aim to rescue the country from the
economic and social crisis, has served as a basis for the
negotiations with the world financial body.
</P>
<P>
The IMF representative said the negotiations with the Angolan
authorities have been very productive.
</P>
<P>
The measures contained in the package are very demanding in
terms of transparency in the state's accounts and the like.
</P>
<P>
The accomplishment of the program is expected to create
conditions for the Angolan government to get access to another
accord called ESAF (Reinforced Structural Adjustment Facility).
</P>
<P>
The ESAF comprises two important components. The first includes
an IMF funding under good terms, while the second provides for
access to the country's external debt reshuffling. During the
visit to Angola, the IMF delegation also reviewed with the
government on inflation, exchange and interest rates, the
country's external debt, the budgetary performance in the coming
two months and the government's public investment program.
</P>
<P>
After 25 years of civil war, Angola is facing grave economic
and humanitarian crisis. Most Angolans living in the central
highland left their hometowns for fleeing the rampant military
conflicts, with most of their industry shutdown and arable lands
deserted.
</P>
<P>
As the second-largest oil-producing country in the African
continent, Angola's economy is now solely depending on exporting
crude oil to western countries.
</P>
<P>
The country has good natural conditions for the agricultural
production. But in 1999, the country had to import some 500,000
tons of aliments. After winning a upper hand in the battle fields,
the government is determined to make use of the abundant natural
resources and develop its own manufacture and agriculture, which
need much funds and equipments for the kick-off of the industrial
and the agricultural programs.
</P>
<P>
But local analysts said that the signing of the accord does
not mean the start of the acquirement of international investment
and assistance. The Angolan government's economic policies have to
accept the review of the IMF delegation.
</P>
<P>
The so-called reform plan for the aid-receiving countries made
by the IMF was accused by some aid-receivers of being arbitrary
and unpractical. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
