<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-04 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Obuchi's Cabinet Resigns, Mori Expected to Be Successor </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TOKYO, April 4 (Xinhua) -- Japanese Prime Minister Keizo
Obuchi's cabinet resigned en masse Tuesday evening to pave the way
for Obuchi's successor to form a new cabinet.
</P>
<P>
Yoshiro Mori, secretary general and the No. 2 figure of Japan's
ruling Liberal Democratic Party (LDP), is most likely to succeed
Obuchi as party leader and hence Japanese prime minister,
political sources said.
</P>
<P>
At 7 p.m. (1000 GMT) the cabinet convened an emergency session
at which all ministers resigned.
</P>
<P>
The cabinet's resignation, which came two days after Obuchi
collapsed due to a stroke, is based on Article 70 of the Japanese
Constitution, which states that all cabinet members must resign
when there is a vacancy in the post of the prime minister.
</P>
<P>
Earlier in the day, Acting Prime Minister Mikio Aoki, who
concurrently serves as chief cabinet secretary, said, "We cannot
allow a political vacuum to continue."
</P>
<P>
A senior LDP official said Obuchi's successor is likely to be
picked at plenary sessions of both chambers of Japan's Diet (
parliament) to begin at 1 p.m. (0400 GMT) Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
Prior to that, the official said, the LDP will hold a meeting
of its lawmakers in both houses of parliament at 10:30 a.m. (0130
GMT) Wednesday to choose Obuchi's successor as LDP president.
</P>
<P>
The LDP president entails the Japanese premiership as ruling
camp enjoys an overwhelming majority in the powerful House of
Representatives (lower house).
</P>
<P>
LDP sources said most of the cabinet ministers, including Aoki
in the capacity of chief cabinet secretary, are likely to be
retained under the new prime minister.
</P>
<P>
Obuchi remained in a coma Tuesday afternoon, breathing only
with the help of a respirator, Aoki told a press conference after
visiting the Tokyo hospital where Obuchi is staying.
</P>
<P>
Obuchi, 62, is not brain-dead, Aoki added. 
</P>
</TEXT>
