<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-04 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Coulthard Loses Appeal against Disqualification </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
PARIS, April 4 (Xinhua) -- McLaren's British driver David
Coulthard has lost an appeal against his disqualification from
second place at last month's Brazilian grand prix.
</P>
<P>
Motor racing's world governing body International Automobile
Federation (FIA) said here on Tuesday its appeal body "decided to
confirm the stewards' decision pronouncing the exclusion of car
number two (Coulthard's) from the classification of the 2000
Brazilian Grand Prix".
</P>
<P>
Coulthard was disqualified by stewards at Interlagos nine days
ago because his McLaren broke technical regulations relating to
front-wing end planes. The stewards ruled the front wing was two
millimeters out of tolerance.
</P>
<P>
In a statement the FIA said Monday's meeting of its appeal body
had decided the distance between the planes exceeded the tolerance
allowed under FIA regulations, and it was up to the teams to
ensure their cars conformed.
</P>
<P>
McLaren had argued the infringement was caused by the bumpy
track at Interlagos but the FIA said this argument was "unfounded".
</P>
<P>
" ... all the competitors - including the appellant - had been
subjected to the rigors of the circuit in question from the first
practice session onwards, and ... all steps could thus have been
taken to make the necessary adjustments to the cars to allow them
to cope with these difficulties," it said.
</P>
<P>
Citing FIA rules, the statement said "it is the duty of each
competitor to prove that his car complies with the regulations in
their entirety at all times during an event."
</P>
<P>
The FIA ruling left the McLaren team, Formula One's top team
the last two seasons, without a point after the first two races of
the F-1 season, in either the drivers' or constructors' standings.
</P>
<P>
The F-1 season continues with the San Marino Grand Prix at
Imola in Italy this Sunday.
</P>
<P>
The court of appeals was comprised of FIA Chairman Philippe
Roberti de Winghe and judges from the Netherlands, Portugal,
Ireland and Spain.
</P>
<P>
The FIA opened its International Court of Appeal on Monday to
hear McLaren's protest over the disqualification.
</P>
<P>
In a similar case five months ago, the same FIA appeal panel
reinstated Ferrari's 1-2 finish in the Malaysian Grand Prix after
stewards ruled aerodynamic deflectors were out of compliance by
one centimeter.
</P>
<P>
At the time, McLaren's managing director Ron Dennis harshly
criticized the reversal and said the FIA had two standards.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE20000404.0141 </DOCNO>
