<HEADLINE> Strict Measures to Prevent Forest Fire in Northeast China </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SHENYANG, April 4 (Xinhua) -- On today's Qingming Festival, the
traditional Chinese day for remembering the dead, the government
of northeast China's Liaoning province declared that the province
is embarking on a serious forest fire prevention campaign.
</P>
<P>
The government firmly bans burning joss paper at cemeteries,
which is the traditional way to show respect for the dead, and
also a cause for forest fire.
</P>
<P>
Several thousand kilometers of forest-covered mountains can be
found in the eastern part of Liaoning Province.
</P>
<P>
Related provincial departments have published bulletins and
carried out educational training programs to arouse public
awareness of preventing forest fires.
</P>
<P>
Those who smoke or burn something near flammable materials or
in no-smoking areas will be seriously punished or even detained,
according to the provincial fire department.
</P>
<P>
The province has also spent about 15,000,000 yuan (1,800,000 US
dollars) for fire-fighting equipment. 
</P>
</TEXT>
