<HEADLINE> CMC Vice Chairman Meets Chilean Army Commander </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
"The election of a new leader in the Taiwan region does not
change the fact that it is an inalienable part of Chinese
territory," said Zhang in a meeting with Ricardo Izurieta
Caffarena, commander-in-chief of Chilean army.
</P>
<P>
"Our attitude towards the new leader in the Taiwan region is to
listen to his words and watch his deeds. We will wait and see in
which direction he will lead cross-Straits relations," the CMC
vice chairman said.
</P>
<P>
Expressing gratitude to the Chilean government for its
adherence to the one China stand, Zhang also spoke highly of the
development of the Sino-Chilean friendly relations and cooperation.
He said that China and Chile are developing countries, and have no
differences of fundamental interest. Although the two countries
are far apart, they share common ground in many fields.
</P>
<P>
He noted that Sino-Chilean relations have developed smoothly
and the relations between the two armies have been satisfactory
since the two countries forged diplomatic ties in 1970, adding
that China will continue to hold a positive attitude toward
exchanges and cooperation between the armies of two countries.
</P>
<P>
During the meeting, Zhang briefed the guests on the Chinese
government's view of the international situation and foreign
policy.
</P>
<P>
Izurieta expressed his appreciation of the achievements China
has scored since it undertook reform and opening-up, and said he
is committed to making the utmost efforts to boost Sino-Chilean
friendly relations in the military field.
</P>
<P>
Guo Boxiong, a member of the CMC and executive deputy chief of
the general staff of the PLA, also attended the meeting.  
</P>
