<HEADLINE> East China City to Host Int'l Peony Fair </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, April 4 (Xinhua) -- The city of Heze in Shandong
Province plans to host its ninth international peony fair from
April 22-28 in an effort to boost the local economy and exchanges
with the rest of the world.
</P>
<P>
Government officials from this east China city briefed local
reporters on the event, saying that Heze is one of the largest
peony producers, exporters, and researchers in the world.
</P>
<P>
Heze, which has cultivated the elegant flower for hundreds of
years, now plants 3,300 hectares of 600 peony varieties, according
to the officials. Peonies are also one of the major attractions
for domestic and overseas tourists, they said.
</P>
<P>
Last year, Heze-cultivated peonies won two top prizes and 79
other prizes at the '99 Kunming World Horticultural Exposition,
accounting for 73.2 percent of the total number of awards of the
largest international floral show.
</P>
<P>
Since 1992, when Heze hosted its first international peony fair,
the city has earned over two billion yuan from flower sales,
including over 30 million U.S. dollars from exports.
</P>
<P>
The city currently occupies 78 percent of the domestic market-
share in the sales of peonies and 85 percent of the country's
total flower exports.
</P>
<P>
Over the past eight years, more than 15 million domestic and
overseas tourists, including 3,500 foreign business people have
visited Heze, bringing in 320 million U.S. dollars worth of
overseas capital and domestic trade totaling 18 billion yuan.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE20000404.0155 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-04 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Africa-Europe Summit Tackles Political Issues </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CAIRO, April 4 (Xinhua) -- Leaders of 67 African and European
Union (EU) countries held on Tuesday the second working session of
their first-ever summit to debate political issues in Africa.
</P>
<P>
The leaders will discuss the decades-old wars and conflicts in
Africa, which have destroyed peace and stability and seriously
hindered the economic development of the continent.
</P>
<P>
The discussions will also focus on the African mechanism of
dispute prevention and settlement in addition to strategic
political dialogue between Africa and the 15-nation European bloc,
according to the agenda of the summit.
</P>
<P>
The session will discuss Afro-EU cooperation in fighting
terrorism and issues of border democratization and human rights in
Africa.
</P>
<P>
The two-day summit opened on Monday, with leaders of the two
continents calling, in their speeches, for strategic partnership
aimed at closer cooperation in promoting economic and social
development of the black continent.
</P>
<P>
After the inaugural ceremony, the leaders went into the first
working session dedicated to debates on economic issues in Africa,
including foreign debt, investment, trade, economic globalization
and EU's role in helping Africa boost its economy.
</P>
<P>
Later Tuesday, the summit will discuss Africa's social problems,
including environmental protection, disease, refugees. It will end
in the evening with the issuing of a final declaration and a plan
of action guiding further joint efforts exerted by the two sides.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE20000404.0156 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-04 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Middle East Economic Briefs </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CAIRO, April 5 (Xinhua) -- The following are economic briefs
from the Middle East countries.
</P>
<P>
ANKARA -- Turkish Foreign Minister Ismail Cem will seek ways to
boost Japanese investments in Turkey during his forthcoming five-
day visit to Japan, Turkish Daily News reported on Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
Among other things, Cem will exchange views with the Japanese
side on Bosphorus Rail Tube Crossing and Bozuyuk-Mekece Road
Improvement projects.
</P>
<P>
The Japanese government is extending a loan totalling around 41,
831 million Japanese yen (about 399 million U.S. dollars) for both
projects.
</P>
<P>
When completed, the Bosphorus Rail Tube Crossing will be able to
cope with peak demand in 2015 while the Bozuyuk-Mekece Road
Improvement project will reduce traffic congestion by expanding the
existing two-lane stretch and also by building a bypass in the
Bozuyuk city area.
</P>
<P>
ANKARA -- The Azerbaijan International Oil Company issued a
statement saying that prematurely produced Azerbaijani oil will
begin to be pumped along the Baku-Novorrossiik (Russia) pipeline
from April 10, Turkish Daily News reported on Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
The pipeline has been closed down many times for various reasons
since it came into operation, and this has led to tension between
Azerbaijan and Russia.
</P>
<P>
It also said that the Baku-Supsa (Georgia) pipeline was
operating at full capacity and that a super tanker had left the
Supsa terminal on April 1 loaded with oil for export.
</P>
<P>
DAMASCUS -- The Syrian Oil Ministry is to launch the Second
International Oil and Gas Fair on April 10-13 with the
participation of 190 countries.
</P>
<P>
The event is designed to get Syrian technicians acquainted with
the up-to-date technology in the oil and gas field, to establish
ties and exchange know-how with Arab and world oil firms.
</P>
<P>
CAIRO -- The European Union (EU) will grant Egypt 1 billion
Egyptian pounds (about 289.86 million U.S. dollars) over the coming
10 years to help upgrade Egypt's industrial competitiveness in the
world markets.
</P>
<P>
The donation comes within the Egyptian-EU partnership agreement
under which the 15-nation bloc is to open its markets to Egyptian
exports right after the deal takes effect. In return, Egypt is to
open its markets to Europe gradually in 19 years.
</P>
<P>
MUSCAT -- Oman Liquefied Natural Gas Corporation will export its
first shipment to South Korea this month.
</P>
<P>
The company, 51 percent of its shares held by the state, has a
25-year contract to sell to the South Korean Gas Corporation 4.1
million cubic meters of liquefied gas every year. It also signed
exporting contracts with Japanese and U.S. companies.
</P>
<P>
BAGHDAD -- Iraq will start to raise its oil output to reach the
targeted 3.1 million barrels per day level as early as next May,
said Iraqi Oil Minister Amir Muhammad Rashid.
</P>
<P>
This week, Iraq increased its daily output by 150,000 barrels
with another 150,000 barrels boom to be launched next week, he
said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
