<HEADLINE> Afghan Province Governor Shot Dead in Pakistan </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ISLAMABAD, April 4 (Xinhua) -- Sitting Governor of Kunduz
Province of Afghanistan Arif Khan was shot dead Tuesday when his
jeep was ambushed in northwestern Pakistan.
</P>
<P>
According to reports, Arif was on his way to visit one of his
friends when a single armed man opened fire upon the vehicle at
Hayatabad town in Peshawar, capital of Pakistan's North West
Frontier Province.
</P>
<P>
Arif died after being sent to a local hospital. His driver and
another man received serious wounds, police sources said.
</P>
<P>
The gunman fled after the shooting. No one has claimed
responsibility for the attack.
</P>
<P>
Arif's family said the governor was in Pakistan for treatment
of his illness, Peshawar sources told Xinhua.
</P>
<P>
However, other sources said Arif had recently developed
differences with the ruling Taliban and had been living in
Peshawar for two and half months.
</P>
<P>
Arif, who previously belonged to Jamiat-e-Islami of the ousted
Afghan President Burhannudin Rabbani, joined the Islamic Taliban
when the latter captured Kunduz in 1997 and has been governor of
the northern Afghan province.
</P>
