<HEADLINE> Nigeria's Northern States to Harmonize Sharia with Extant Laws </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LAGOS, March 4 (Xinhua) -- Governors of Nigeria's 19 northern
states met on Monday, resolving to constitute a panel, which would
harmonize provisions of the Islamic Sharia law with the extant
penal code.
</P>
<P>
The Guardian, a leading Nigerian newspaper, Tuesday quoted a
communique published after their meeting in the country's
northern Kaduna state as stating that the panel would comprise
Moslem and Christian leaders.
</P>
<P>
The governors condemned the recent agitation over confederation
or national sovereignty conference by some states, and pledged
their loyalty to "the federal structure of Nigeria" and federal
government under the leadership of President Olusegun Obasanjo."
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, the governors said that "we have resolved to uphold
the whole north as one indivisible and geo-political entity within
the Federation of Nigeria." The population of northern Nigeria is
predominately Muslim as against the Christian south.
</P>
<P>
The governors also condemned the bloody clashes one month ago
in Kaduna and other parts of the country over the introduction of
Sharia, in which about 1,000 people died.
</P>
<P>
They said they were contended with a statement by the
Conference of the State at the end of the Kaduna crisis that
Sharia provisions had already existed in the country's
constitution.
</P>
<P>
On the same day, Emirs, Ulamas and other traditional rulers in
the north also started their meeting in Kaduna on the same topic.
</P>
</TEXT>
