<HEADLINE> Ethiopia Rejects Using Eritrean Port for Relief Food: Report </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ADDIS ABABA, April 4 (Xinhua) -- Ethiopia has rejected
Eritrea's offer to use its port of Assab to deliver relief food
for Ethiopian famine victims, the Monitor newspapers reported
Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
The newspaper quoted a statement by the Ethiopian Foreign
Ministry as saying that Eritrea had looted "some 50,000 tons of
USAID-donated food grain and other relief items destined for
Ethiopia from Assab port and used it to feed its army."
</P>
<P>
Eritrea's proposal to use its port of Assab to deliver food aid
for Ethiopian drought-affected population is the "the latest
Eritrean public relations gimmick...", the statement said.
</P>
<P>
Eritrea made its proposal to Hugh Parmer, the USAID assistant
administrator for humanitarian relief during a recent meeting with
Eritrean President Isaias Afewerki.
</P>
<P>
It was reported that there are more than eight million
Ethiopians suffering from hunger.
</P>
<P>
Ethiopia became a land-locked country after Eritrea declared
independence in 1993. It stopped using Eritrean ports of Assab and
Massawa following the outbreak of their border conflict in May
1998. 
</P>
</TEXT>
