<HEADLINE> Traffic Death Toll in Cyprus Up </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NICOSIA, April 4 (Xinhua) -- Thirty-one people have been killed
in traffic accidents since the beginning of the year, up 35 percent
from the same period of last year.
</P>
<P>
Cyprus remains the third worst country in the European league
table for traffic deaths, the Cyprus Mail newspaper reported
Tuesday. Ahead of it are Portugal and Greece.
</P>
<P>
There are 20 traffic deaths every year for every 100,000
residents, while the European rate is barely half of that.
</P>
<P>
According to a British study, Cyprus in 1998 suffered a loss of
approximately 58 million Cyprus pounds (116 million U.S. dollars)
incurred by traffic accidents.
</P>
<P>
In Cyprus, with a population of 665,000, the road death toll in
1999 stood at 112. Since 1974, 2,539 people had died on the roads.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
