<DOCNO> XIE20000404.0183 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-04 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Malaysia Committed to Change to K-Economy </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KUALA LUMPUR, April 4 (Xinhua) -- Malaysia is committed to
transforming its economy from production-based to knowledge-driven
by drafting a k-economy master plan as part of the overall plan to
enhance its international competitiveness and efficiency in order
to sustain long-term growth.
</P>
<P>
The first draft of the k-economy master plan may be completed
by the yearend, "aimed at increasing the knowledge content of the
economy as a key to moving up the value-added chain," Mustapa
Mohamed, the Finance Ministry advisor, said Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
The master plan will be used as input into the formulation of
the 2001 budget and the Eighth Malaysia Plan (2001-2005) to
expedite the country's transformation to a knowledge-driven
economy, Mustapa, former second finance minister, said here when
opening a seminar on challenges facing Malaysia's economic
recovery.
</P>
<P>
He said sustaining the recovery in the immediate term does not
present a problem as the Malaysian economy has picked up
sufficient momentum amid the relative stability of financial
markets and the encouraging world economic environment.
</P>
<P>
But, in the medium term, he added, there are a number of
potential risks and uncertainties that might impact on the
otherwise strong recovery.
</P>
<P>
Aside from recovery policies and strategies to ensure continued
growth, new sources of growth in agriculture, manufacturing and
the k-economy are being identified and strategies are being
designed to intensify their growth prospects, he said.
</P>
<P>
Malaysia is also focusing on identifying fresh strategies to
attract foreign investments and stimulate local private
investments in an overall effort to provide financial resources
necessary to sustain the recovery process.
</P>
<P>
Given the current trends in globalization and liberalization,
the Malaysian economy could not afford to take a break, Mustapa
said.
</P>
<P>
He expressed the view that Malaysia's economic outlook in the
immediate term remains encouraging and barring any adverse
external developments to change the current favorable external
environment, the real gross domestic product growth is expected to
be 5.8 percent this year.
</P>
<P>
He said Malaysia hopes the recent East Asian financial crisis
has increased the awareness of the international community and
there would be a more discernible move toward greater coordination
of policy initiatives and measures aimed at crisis prevention and
containment. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
