<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Sydney Drivers Threaten Strike in Olympics </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CANBERRA, April 4 (Xinhua) -- Some 10,000 train and bus drivers
in Sydney threatened to go on strike during the Olympics unless
the New South Wales state government approves their bonus claim.
</P>
<P>
Pat Ryan, spokeswoman of the Rail, Tram and Bus Union, said on
Tuesday that she had lodged a claim, demanding a bonus of 300
Australian dollars (181 U.S. dollars) for each week of the
Olympics and extra vacation time for the workers as a payoff for
their increased workloads during the Games slated from September
15 to October 1.
</P>
<P>
The Union has given the state authorities the deadline of April
30 to meet its demands.
</P>
<P>
The Olympics Roads and Transport Authority said it was
expecting 32 million rail passengers over 17 days during the Games
on a rail system which usually carries 12 million people over a 21-
day period. 
</P>
</TEXT>
