<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-04 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Beijing Stresses Fire Safety </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, April 4 (Xinhua) -- The capital city of China has
launched a 17-day fire safety inspection, an official from the
Beijing Municipal Fire-fighting Bureau said today.
</P>
<P>
Hou Tiesheng, deputy director of the bureau, said the
inspection is being launched at a time when several disastrous
fires have occurred in the country, causing deaths and heavy
economic losses.
</P>
<P>
Hou also warned people of fire dangers during the dry spring
season.
</P>
<P>
Statistics show that Beijing had 5,395 fires last year which
killed 53 people and injured 92 others. Direct economic losses
caused by these fires totaled 31.65 million yuan (4.35 million U.S.
dollars).
</P>
<P>
The 17-day inspection will cover all the city's karaoke and
dancing halls, cinemas, electronic games centers, saunas and bath
facilities, department stores, markets, hotels, hospitals, schools,
and work units, as well as places producing, storing or selling
flammable and explosive chemicals.
</P>
<P>
Units with sub-standard fire-fighting equipment will be urged
to improve them within a set period of time. 
</P>
</TEXT>
