</P>
<P>
Ha'aretz:
</P>
<P>
-- U.N. Secretary General Kofi Annan and the French government
are working to adjust Security Council Resolution 425 in order to
clarify the terms of a deployment of international peacekeeping
forces in south Lebanon after the Israeli troops withdraw from the
region.
</P>
<P>
Israeli Foreign Minister David Levy will meet Tuesday in Geneva
with Annan and present the Israeli government's decision to pull
out of Lebanon this July. Levy will tell the U.N. secretary general
that the withdrawal will comply with Resolution 425, passed in
March 1978.
</P>
<P>
Prior to leaving for Switzerland, Levy met on Monday with U.S.
and French ambassadors to Israel, Martin Indyk and Jacques
Hunzinger. The discussion focused on alternatives for the
deployment of an international force in southern Lebanon after an
Israel Defense Forces (IDF) pullout.
</P>
<P>
Ma'ariv:
</P>
<P>
-- South Lebanon Army (SLA) commander General Antoine Lahad
vowed Monday that his men would choose to "die on their own land,"
as Jewish partisans did at Masada, rather than live in Israel as
refugees.
</P>
<P>
He was referring to a hilltop fortress in the Judean desert
where Jewish rebels and their families resisted Roman soldiers for
years. When they saw the Romans were about to breach their
defenses, 960 people killed themselves rather than surrender in 73
A.D.
</P>
<P>
Lahad said that the Israeli-trained and armed militia will
continue to operate even after the IDF pulls out of south Lebanon.
It was the first time that the SLA commander has specifically said
that it would remain a fighting force after an Israeli withdrawal.
</P>
<P>
Yediot Aharonot:
</P>
<P>
-- Labor Party Secretary-General Ra'anan Cohen has been
officially invited to visit Libya by the top Libyan delegate to the
Inter-parliamentary convention on security and cooperation of
Mediterranean Countries, now meeting in Marseilles.
</P>
<P>
"He invited me to visit his country," Cohen said. "They believe
that the (Israeli) government headed by Ehud Barak is one...that
will bring changes and peace to the Middle East."
</P>
<P>
Israel's Channel One reported Monday night that Libya denied
there was an official invitation extended to Cohen. However, Cohen
told Israel media that he stands by his story. 
