<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-04 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Turkey Uneasy Over U.S. Use of Cluster Bombs in Iraq </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ANKARA, April 4 (Xinhua) -- Turkey feels uneasy over the secret
use by U.S. forces of cluster bombs against Iraqi troops over the
so-called no-fly zone in northern Iraq, Turkish Daily News reported
on Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
The U.S. action has been discovered by Turkish military
intelligence, said the report.
</P>
<P>
Turkish and U.S. military authorities have been holding talks to
address the sensitive issue of using cluster bombs against Iraqi
forces during their reconnaissance flights in the U.S.-Britain-
imposed no-fly zone north of the 36th parallel over Iraq.
</P>
<P>
Under the rules of engagement agreed upon between Turkey and the
United States last year, the U.S. should inform Turkey of the
nature of the mission which U.S. warplanes carried on each flight
taking off from the NATO Incirlik Air Base in southern Turkey to
monitor the no-fly zone.
</P>
<P>
However, the U.S. fighter jets began to use cluster bombs in
question last September and continued to do so unnoticed.
</P>
<P>
The code-named Operation Northern Watch (ONW) based at Incirlik
is composed of Turkish, U.S. and British forces conducting
surveillance flights in the region to deter Iraqi forces from what
the U.S. claimed attacking Kurds living in northern Iraq.
</P>
<P>
Turkey, a NATO member and also Iraq's neighbor, does not take
part in the reconnaissance flights over northern Iraq. But Turkish
pilots join in Airborne Early Warning and Control aircraft flights
in the region.
</P>
<P>
The nature of arms deployed on a single U.S. F-16 aircraft
during flights over northern Iraq has always been an issue of
discontent between the U.S. and Turkey. Turkey classifies cluster
bombs as offensive weapons and has asked the U.S. not to use them
against Iraqi forces.
</P>
<P>
Turkey used to maintain close economic and trade ties with Iraq
before the 1991 Gulf war triggered by Iraq's 1990 invasion of
Kuwait. The U.N. sanctions imposed on Iraq since 1990 have caused
Turkey billions of U.S. dollars in losses.
</P>
<P>
It was reported that Turkey supports lifting or largely easing
the sanctions, but its maneuverability is very limited. On one side
there is the U.S., which is a strategic partner and on the other
side is Iraq, which is Turkey's neighbor and a potentially vital
trading partner. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE20000404.0195 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-04 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Europe, U.S. Urged to Push for Cyprus Solution </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NICOSIA, April 4 (Xinhua) -- Cyprus President Glafcos Clerides
has urged Europe and the United States to renew efforts to push for
a Cyprus solution, Cyprus News Agency reported Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
Europe and the U.S. will have to consider what will happen if
Turkish Cypriot side continues to insist on the creation of two
separate "states" in Cyprus during the third round of the U.N.-
sponsored talks on Cyprus, Clerides said in New York on Monday.
</P>
<P>
Clerides left here for New York on Sunday to attend the opening
of the new Cypriot Galleries at the Metropolitan Museum of Art.
During the five-day visit he was scheduled to have meetings with
officials from various countries dealing with the Cyprus issue.
</P>
<P>
Clerides told the press Monday after arrival that no one can
predict what stance the Turkish Cypriot side will maintain during
the next round of talks.
</P>
<P>
He said that the Greek Cypriot side is not concerned about
whether the talks will be proximity or direct, but whether the
other side is willing to negotiate.
</P>
<P>
"We have no new evidence on what stance the Turkish side will
maintain during the next round of the talks," Clerides said.
</P>
<P>
Cyprus has been divided into the Greek and Turkish Cypriot
communities since 1974 when Turkey invaded and occupied the
northern third of the island after a failed pro-Athens coup.
</P>
<P>
The United Nations has been trying for years to bring the two
sides back together through a bizonal, bicommunal federation
formula, but no tangible results have been achieved.
</P>
<P>
Turkish Cypriot leader Rauf Denktash insists on the recognition
of his breakaway regime in the north, now backed only by Turkey,
and a confederation of two states on the island.
</P>
<P>
The two communities have held two rounds of U.N.-sponsored
indirect talks in New York and Geneva. They will hold another round
in New York, starting May 23.
</P>
<P>
Clerides will return to Cyprus next week, and on April 10 he is
due to meet British Prime Minister Tony Blair in London. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
