<HEADLINE> Kenya to Build More Museums </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NAIROBI, April 4 (Xinhua) -- The Kenyan government is to
establish more museums to educate Kenyan ethnic communities on
their culture and history.
</P>
<P>
This was announced by Minister Katana Ngala for Home Affairs,
Heritage and Sport at the weekend when he officially opened the
Kabarnet Museum in Baringo District, central Kenya.
</P>
<P>
He was quoted by Tuesday's Kenya Times newspaper as saying that
museums play an important role since they can serve as a medium of
educating Kenyans, especially the youth, on their cultural values
and in the process they can check the western cultural influence
on the young generation.
</P>
<P>
Museums will expose Kenyans to lifestyles of various ethnic
communities and how they used to co-exist peacefully in past
years, he said, adding that they would reduce any form of
animosity among the communities and harmonize their good
neighborliness.
</P>
<P>
The minister noted that the Kabarnet Museum has tourism and
research potential because it is located in Baringo, a region
globally reputed for archaeological heritage.
</P>
<P>
According to Ngala, his ministry has set aside 800,000
shillings (some 108,000 U.S. dollars) for the construction of the
Daniel arap Moi Gallery at the Kabarnet Museum. 
</P>
