<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Kenya to Raise Prices of Pyrethrum </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NAIROBI, April 4 (Xinhua) -- The Pyrethrum Board of Kenya will
raise buying prices of the cash crop from farmers in a bid to
encourage production since Kenya faces a deficit of 7,000 tons in
the world market.
</P>
<P>
Kenyan farmers provided 4,000 tons to the international market
in the 1998-1999 season, earning the country more than 407 million
shillings (about 5.5 million U.S. dollars). The board hoped that
the production would increase 1,300 tons to hit 5,300 tons this
year due to the hike in the buying prices.
</P>
<P>
The Daily Nation newspaper Tuesday quoted some growers as
saying that persistent shortage of planting material and high
labor demand for weeding and harvesting are the major obstacles
for the development of the sub- sector.
</P>
<P>
The farmers also regretted that in spite of a high potential
for the crop in the east African country, which produces more than
70 percent of the world's pyrethrum, many farms lay idle for lack
of seeds.
</P>
<P>
The board has released more than 10,000 packets of seed and
cautioned farmers against being exploited by middlemen. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
