<DOCNO> XIE20000404.0199 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-04 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> E. Africa Sets Giant Project to Alleviate Poverty </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
DAR ES SALAAM, April 4 (Xinhua) -- The East African Community
(EAC), including Kenya, Uganda and Tanzania, needs a total of 9.67
billion U.S. dollars to develop two major infrastructure projects
aimed at alleviating poverty in the region, a senior EAC official
has said.
</P>
<P>
Francis Muthaura, EAC's Executive Secretary, was quoted by
local media on Tuesday as saying that the projects covering
regional road networks (nine billion U.S. dollars and
telecommunications (67 million U.S. dollars) are in the final
stages of analysis.
</P>
<P>
Muthaura said last weekend at the EAC headquarters in
Tanzania's northern town of Arusha that EAC has also planned to
develop other projects in sectors of energy, civil aviation and
shipping.
</P>
<P>
"Promotion of trade and investments, joint management and
rational utilization of shared natural resources, health,
education and development of science and technology are also on
the agenda," he told visiting David Katele, Project Coordinator of
International Council on Social Welfare (ICSW) - Africa region.
</P>
<P>
He said, however, the budgets and funds for the projects are
yet to be finalized and secured though they all have social
dimension in development aspects.
</P>
<P>
"EAC is working closely with the public and take into account
'the social dimension' including gender, the environment and
poverty eradication concerns when formulating the regional
projects," he said.
</P>
<P>
"It is important not only to enlighten the people on their
basic needs and to remind governments of their obligations to
eradicate poverty but also that additional resources from the
development partners are necessary to move people out of the
'poverty trap'," Muthaura added.
</P>
<P>
The EAC was founded on November 30, 1999 when Kenya, Tanzania
and Uganda signed a treaty to replace the then East African
Cooperation.
</P>
<P>
The EAC will expand and deepen economic, political and social
cooperation among the three neighboring states with a combined
population of about 80 million and territories of 1.8 million
square kilometers.
</P>
<P>
The 153-Article Treaty for the Establishment of the East
African Community says that a Customs Union will be established as
the entry point of the Community, followed by a Common Market,
subsequently a Monetary Union and ultimately a Political
Federation of the East African States.
</P>
<P>
The main organs of the EAC are the Summit of Heads of State,
the Council of Ministers, the Coordination Committee, the Sectoral
Committees, the East African Court of Justice, the East African
Legislative Assembly and the Secretariat. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
