<HEADLINE> Falling Tea, Coffee Prices to Hit Kenya Economy: World Bank </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NAIROBI, April 4 (Xinhua) -- Price drops in coffee, tea and
other agricultural commodities in the world market will produce
trade losses for Kenya this year and worsen its economic
performance in the coming year, a World Bank report warns.
</P>
<P>
Countries heavily dependent on agricultural exports like Kenya
could suffer a decrease of more than 1.5 percentage points in
their growth rates over the next two years, the Daily Nation daily
newspaper Tuesday quoted the bank's latest survey, Global
Development Financing 2000, as saying.
</P>
<P>
A continued rise in the world oil prices would further hurt
Kenya's economy, the report said.
</P>
<P>
However, the report suggested that Kenya's slow-down in
economic growth resulted as much from internal factors as from
global conditions. 
