<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Kaunda's Retirement Welcomed in Zambia </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
by Wang Nengbiao
</P>
<P>
LUSAKA, April 4 (Xinhua) -- The retirement from active politics
by Kenneth Kaunda, Zambian former president and leader of the
biggest opposition party, the United National Independence Party
(UNIP), has been widely welcomed.
</P>
<P>
Kaunda should now be accorded the respect and status he
deserves, said Secretary General of Zambia Congress of Trade
Unions (ZCTU) Sylvester Tembo.
</P>
<P>
The trade union leader called on old politicians to emulate
Kaunda's move and retire to pave way for upcoming politicians.
</P>
<P>
Zambian Alliance for Progress (ZAP) Chairman Ben Kapita said
that the retirement is a blessing in disguise because the former
leader will now truly be a national and international asset.
</P>
<P>
ZAP Secretary General Sylvia Masebo said Kaunda should continue
working to conclude the desire for a strong opposition alliance.
</P>
<P>
Anti-Voter Apathy Project executive director Bonnie Tembo said
"we would like him to be a political resource center for all
political parties in order to enhance clean and mature politics."
</P>
<P>
Zambia Independent Monitoring Team President Alfred Zulu
welcomed Kaunda' s retirement but said it should have happened a
few years ago.
</P>
<P>
UNIP cadres should not feel sad about his departure because he
had ruled the country for almost three decades and had been at the
helm of UNIP for about 40 years, Zulu said.
</P>
<P>
Zulu urged Kaunda to assist the party to identify a successor
and join the league of other statesmen who have involved
themselves in conflict resolution after retiring from active
politics.
</P>
<P>
According to Inter African Network for Human Rights executive
director Ngande Mwanajiti, the challenge now is on the Zambian
people and government to make sure Kaunda is utilized to the
maximum for the benefit of the country.
</P>
<P>
UNIP members In Ndola, in the north of the country, are now
consulting over the person they will rally behind to take over as
the party president.
</P>
<P>
Ndola district UNIP chairman James Chasaya said that the Kaunda
team, abruptly abandoned by their master, are looking for another
leader to back at the UNIP national congress to be held at the end
of this month and early May to elect new leadership of the party.
</P>
<P>
UNIP Chairman Malimba Masheke urged his supporters and those
who are for Kaunda to forget about their differences and think of
how best they will revamp the party.
</P>
<P>
Kaunda, 76, reaffirmed here last Sunday his decision to quit
party politics.
</P>
<P>
Kaunda ruled Zambia after it won independence from British
colonial rule in 1964 until 1991, when he was defeated by
incumbent President Frederick Chiluba.
</P>
<P>
In the 1996 presidential election, Kaunda was barred from
contesting the position because of his Malawian parentage.
</P>
<P>
However, Kaunda has vowed repeatedly to run for the presidency
in the next general elections despite the government utterance
that Kaunda is not qualified for it.
</P>
<P>
His rival Chiluba has repeatedly urged him to quit party
politics to be respected as the founding father of the country
like Nyerere of Tanzania.
</P>
<P>
Kaunda resigned from UNIP soon after his party lost in the 1991
 elections but he returned to UNIP in 1994 and was elected UNIP
presidency in 1995.
</P>
<P>
On December 25, 1997, three days after his return from overseas
trip, Kaunda was arrested for his alleged involvement in the coup
attempt on October 28, 1997.
</P>
<P>
On June 1, 1998, Kaunda was released and in return for the
release, he announced his retirement from party politics three
days later.
</P>
<P>
However, at the end of 1998, Kaunda vowed not to retire, saying
nobody can prevent him from contesting the 2001 elections.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
