<DOCNO> XIE20000404.0204 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-04 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Burundi Peace Agreement Might be Signed in June </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
During the just ended round of peace talks in Tanzania's north
town of Arusha, all 19 Burundian delegations demonstrated their
readiness to speed up the peace process towards durable peace in
the "nearest future," reliable sources were quoted as saying in
Dar es Salaam on Monday.
</P>
<P>
The signed peace agreement could also facilitate the
possibility of Burundi to be accommodated into an enlarged East
African Community (EAC). According to the sources, a group of
journalists from Tanzania would visit Burundi any time from now to
witness the release of political prisoners and closure of
"regrouping camps."
</P>
<P>
Immediate release of political prisoners, closure of regrouping
camps which shelter an estimated 350,000 civilians so as to
isolate rebels and allowing political parties and the media to
operate freely were conditions given by international facilitator
of the Burundi conflict, ex-South African President Nelson Mandela
to President Buyoya.
</P>
<P>
Mandela took over as mediator in Burundi's peace talks in
December last year and is pushing hard a quick end to the ethnic
conflict that has cost 200,000 lives and uprooted more than 1.2
million others since 1993. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
