<HEADLINE> Obuchi Cabinet to Resign En Masse Tuesday Evening: Acting PM </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TOKYO, April 4 (Xinhua) -- Japanese Prime Minister Keizo
Obuchi's cabinet will resign en masse Tuesday evening to pave the
way for a successor to ailing Obuchi, Acting Prime Minister Mikio
Aoki said.
</P>
<P>
"At 7 'o clock tonight we are going to hold an extraordinary
cabinet meeting on the resignation of the cabinet in view of the
fact that we cannot allow a political vacuum even for a moment,"
he said at a press conference.
</P>
<P>
Aoki, who took over as acting premier after Prime Minister
Keizo Obuchi collapsed with a stroke and later fell into a coma,
made the announcement shortly after returning from a Tokyo
hospital where Obuchi is in an intensive care unit and on
artificial respirator.
</P>
<P>
He said Obuchi remains in a coma but his blood pressure is
stable. But Doctors have concluded that the prime minister will
find it hard to understand questions or make statements, the
acting prime minister said.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, A high-ranking official of the ruling Liberal
Democratic Party (LDP) said Obuchi's successor is likely to be
picked Wednesday afternoon at a plenary session of the House of
Representatives at 1 p.m. (0400 GMT).
</P>
<P>
The official said the dominant LDP will hold a meeting of its
lawmakers in both houses of parliament at 10:30 a.m. (0130 GMT)
Wednesday to choose Obuchi's successor as LDP president, which
also entails the Japanese premiership. 
</P>
