<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Obuchi Is Not Brain Dead, Acting PM Says </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TOKYO, April 4 (Xinhua) -- Japanese Prime Minister Keizo Obuchi,
who is in a Tokyo hospital intensive care unit after suffering a
stroke Sunday, is not brain dead, the acting Prime Minister Mikio
Aoki said Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
Aoki, who took over as acting premier after Prime Minister
Keizo Obuchi collapsed and later fell into a coma, made the
announcement at a press conference shortly after returning from
the Juntendo hospital where Obuchi is on an artificial respirator.
</P>
<P>
He said Obuchi, 62, remained in a coma Tuesday afternoon but
his blood pressure was stable.
</P>
<P>
Aoki said that doctors have concluded that the prime minister
will find it hard to understand questions or make statements.
</P>
<P>
The Obuchi cabinet will convene a cabinet session at 7 p.m. (
1000 GMT) and then resign en masse to pave the way for a successor
to ailing Obuchi, the top government spokesman said.
</P>
<P>
"Any political vacuum cannot be allowed," Aoki told a press
conference.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, A high-ranking official of the ruling Liberal
Democratic Party (LDP) said Obuchi's successor is likely to be
picked at a plenary session of the House of Representatives at 1 p.
m. (0400 GMT) Wednesday afternoon.
</P>
<P>
The official said the dominant LDP will hold a meeting of its
lawmakers in both houses of parliament at 10:30 a.m. (0130 GMT)
Wednesday to choose Obuchi's successor as LDP president, which
also entails the Japanese premiership.
</P>
<P>
LDP sources said Yoshiro Mori, secretary general and the No.2
figure of the LDP, is most likely to succeed Obuchi. 
</P>
</TEXT>
