<DOCNO> XIE20000404.0224 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-04 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Chinese Official Urges to Curb HIV/AIDS </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, April 4 (Xinhua) -- Vice-Premier Li Lanqing has urged
government officials to pay close attention to HIV/AIDS control,
noting this is vital to the future of the Chinese nation.
</P>
<P>
Li, who called a State Council meeting on prevention and
control of HIV/AIDS and sexually transmitted diseases (STD) on
Monday, said that governments and officials at all levels should
regard this work as "a strategic issue of vital importance to the
nation's fortune and state development."
</P>
<P>
Confirmed HIV/AIDS cases throughout China totaled 17,316 by the
end of last year, including 647 fully developed AIDS patients,
among whom 356 died, according to the Ministry of Health.
</P>
<P>
But Minister of Health Zhang Wenkang noted that HIV infection
has in fact exceeded 500,000 people scattered in 31 provinces,
municipalities and autonomous regions across China because most
cases are not reported.
</P>
<P>
Health experts warn that outbreak of STDs could make HIV/AIDS
control even more formidable.
</P>
<P>
The number of confirmed STD cases hit a record 836,655 last
year, a rise of 30 percent over 1998. However, estimates put the
real figure at above four million.
</P>
<P>
Vice-Premier Li has called for the thorough implementation of a
national program of HIV/AIDS control, with the goal of keeping
China's HIV infection level under 1.5 million people by the year
2010, while ending the transmission of HIV through blood
transfusions and intravenous drug use.
</P>
<P>
It was also determined that the annual increase rate of the
incidence of STDs should be under 15 percent by 2002, compared
with from 20 to 30 percent at present.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE20000404.0225 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-04 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Tigers Still Under Threat from Poaching and Trade: Report (1) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
The report, titled "Far From A Cure: The Tiger Trade Revisited,
" revealed that the trade in tiger parts in traditional Asian
medicine continues to be a threat to wild tigers, with the trade
in some markets shifting to skins and other products besides bones.
</P>
<P>
The report, made by the Trade Records Analysis of Flora and
Fauna in Commerce (TRAFFIC), a wildlife trade monitoring program
under the WWF, examines the tiger trade in the late 1990s. In
particular, it looks at the extent to which illegal trade in tiger
bones can still be considered a threat to the tiger's survival.
</P>
<P>
This report follows the highly successful TRAFFIC Report "
Killed For A Cure: A Review of the Worldwide Trade in Tiger Bone,"
which was released in 1994 and has become the leading reference
for those in the conservation community seeking to understand the
trade in tigers. Since the publication of that report, definite
progress has been seen in some aspects of controlling the trade.
But problems still exist.
</P>
<P>
"The report revealed that major illegal supplying markets still
operate openly in southeast Asian countries such as Cambodia,
Indonesia, Laos, Myanmar, and Vietnam," said Samuel Lee, program
officer of TRAFFIC East Asia.
</P>
<P>
Thailand has a significant retail market for tiger skins,
trophies, and teeth and claws; and demand for tiger products also
appears to be high in Vietnam, Cambodia, and Indonesia, Lee said.
</P>
<P>
The report praises China's efforts in clamping down on the
trade in tigers, and says the trade in tiger bones for use in
medicine appears to have decreased since a ban was implemented in
China in 1993.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE20000404.0226 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-04 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Those Going Against People's Will Be Doomed to Failure: Commentary( 2) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
During his 12 years in office, Lee has talked a lot about
democracy while always acting as a self-willed dictator.
</P>
<P>
Lee has played politics in the Kuomintang Party, and his high
pressure tactics has forced many dissidents to either leave the
party or keep quite out of fear.
</P>
<P>
Under his leadership, the Kuomintang experienced one election
defeat after another as well as internal dissension. At the end,
the party was forced out of office in the last election, the
commentary said.
</P>
<P>
In Taiwan society, Lee appeared first as a so-called "strongman
" and gradually established an authoritarian regime of personal
dictatorship, it said.
</P>
<P>
By changing the political system, Lee gathered most of the
island's power. With his connivance and support, the separatist
forces on the island grew stronger, while people in favor of
reunification were suppressed.
</P>
<P>
In the meantime, Lee did all he could to suppress any medium
daring to voice any criticism, and even the Western media pointed
out that Lee had actually become an emperor.
</P>
<P>
"What people see is actually the ugly face of a dictator when
Lee, the so-called Mr. Democracy, is unmasked," the commentary
noted.
</P>
<P>
The commentary stressed that politicians on the island should
draw lessons from Lee's disgraceful end, and make the right
choices that conform with the interests of the Taiwan people and
the Chinese nation as a whole. 
</P>
</TEXT>
