<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE20000404.0227 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-04 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Tigers Still Under Threat from Poaching and Trade: Report (2) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
China now is promoting the bones of sailong, a type of mole rat,
as a substitute for tiger bones.
</P>
<P>
In 1999, China made several large seizures involving over 11
tiger skins but no bone seizures were reported.
</P>
<P>
Rob Parry-Jones, another program officer at TRAFFIC East Asia,
noted that, "These signs are positive. However, illegal trade in
tiger products into China does still continue."
</P>
<P>
Seizures of raw tiger parts suggest a shift in market demand,
and are indicative of the on-going smuggling of tiger products,
said Rob Parry-Jones, adding that while the efforts of China's
Customs officials are to be commended, increased vigilance is
needed.
</P>
<P>
The report urges the countries of origin of tigers to strictly
enforce trade bans, improve their anti-poaching capacity, develop
specialized enforcement units for undercover investigations, and
provide incentives against commercial tiger poaching.
</P>
<P>
The report also urges continued close cooperation and work with
traditional medicine practitioners. The community can play an
important role in eliminating any remaining trade, promoting the
use of substitutes, and raising conservation awareness among
consumers.
</P>
<P>
"While advances were made in the 1990s towards reducing the use
of tiger bones in traditional Asian medicines, we must not be
complacent with the successes so far," said Steven Broad,
executive director of TRAFFIC International. "Some old problems
still exist and new ones have emerged, all of which pose serious
threats to the future survival of the tiger."  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
