<HEADLINE> IRNA Chief Summoned to Press Court over Complaints </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TEHRAN, April 4 (Xinhua) -- Managing Director of the official
Islamic Republic News Agency (IRNA) Fereydoun Verdinejad was
summoned to the conservative press court on Monday, IRNA said on
Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
The subpoena was issued after Iran's security forces filed
complaints against Verdinejad, who was required to appear in the
court within three days to present his clarification, IRNA said.
</P>
<P>
However, the agency did not give more details about what the
complaints were and whether they were linked with the performance
of IRNA itself or newspapers affiliated to it.
</P>
<P>
IRNA and its newspapers, widely believed to be close to the
President Mohammad Khatami, have been under heavy attack by the
conservatives since the moderate president came to power in 1997.
</P>
<P>
The conservatives blamed IRNA and its newspapers for siding with
the reformists and thus losing their impartiality.
</P>
<P>
Iran's politically-charged press has been active in urging for
changes and reforms. In the past Iranian calendar year ended on
March 19, the conservatives revoked licenses of 78 publications in
the capital city alone.
</P>
<P>
In the past weeks, several prominent reformist journalists were
summoned to the press court, the Intelligence Ministry and other
authorities.
</P>
<P>
On March 30, Mohammad Reza Khatami, the president's brother and
managing director of the reformist daily Mosharekat (participation)
was called to the press court.
</P>
<P>
Reza Khatami was the top winner in the Tehran constituency in
the February 18 parliamentary election, in which reformists won an
overwhelming victory. The conservatives, though defeated, still
retain their grip on most of the state powers.
</P>
<P>
Managing Director of the reformist daily Sobh-e Emrouz (This
Morning) Saeed Hajjarian, a close ally of the president, was shot
and seriously wounded by gunmen on March 12, days before the
Iranian new year.
</P>
<P>
After several journalists were summoned by the courts and the
Intelligence Ministry, the Iranian Union of Journalists on Monday
expressed concern over restrictions on the press.
</P>
<P>
"Summoning journalists to the Intelligence Ministry and the
Public Court on journalistic charges will threaten their job
security and independence," the union said in a statement.
</P>
<P>
The union called on authorities concerned to treat the
journalists under the constitution and pertinent laws, IRNA said.
</P>
</TEXT>
