<HEADLINE> Manila Conducts Study on Poverty </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MANILA, April 4 (Xinhua) -- With the help of Latin American
economist Hernando de Soto, the Philippine government is
conducting an in-depth study on poverty in the country, a senior
cabinet member said Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
Executive Secretary Ronaldo Zamora said in a radio speech that
de Soto's work will play a major role in President Joseph Estrada'
s efforts to map out a long-term plan against poverty.
</P>
<P>
President Estrada has commissioned a team, which is led by
political economist de Soto from Peru, to conduct a study on
poverty in the Philippines.
</P>
<P>
Zamora described de Soto as a respected economist who
concentrates on poverty, as opposed to other economists who look
at market forces,the stock market and capital accumulation.
</P>
<P>
On Monday, Estrada reportedly made public a plan to end what he
called"the economic apartheid" of the poor and give them a
fighting chance to improve their lives.
</P>
<P>
According to Estrada, the plan aims to achieve three goals:
reform the legal system to make it more accessible to the poor,
help low-income Filipinos make their assets liquid and transform
the Philippine bureaucracy into a user-friendly entity that the
poor can tap to help them improve their lives. 
</P>
