<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-04 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> COMESA to Launch Customs Bond Guarantee </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LUSAKA, April 4 (Xinhua) -- The Common Market for Eastern and
Southern Africa (COMESA) has announced that it will soon launch
the COMESA Customs Bond Guarantee system which will utilize 1.2
billion U.S. dollars tied up in commercial banks in the region.
</P>
<P>
COMESA assistant secretary general Sindiso Ngwenya confirmed
the development in an interview here on Monday.
</P>
<P>
Tuesday's Zambia Daily Mail newspaper quoted Ngwenya as saying
that the launching of the Customs Bond Guarantee will safeguard
the economic activities of respective member states as it will
stop business by any organization or individual in another country
without paying duty.
</P>
<P>
"COMESA is not only about the Free Trade Area. There are a lot
of programs which we are working on and which will benefit the
economies of the members," he said.
</P>
<P>
He said as one of the many such ventures and programs, COMESA
Customs Bond is simply a COMESA community transit system.
</P>
<P>
"The COMESA Customs Bond Agreement will make transporters and
business people moving goods across the region obtain bonds
locally and have that bond be guaranteed for their goods in those
countries they will go to," Ngwenya said.
</P>
<P>
He explained that the bond will be required so that people who
have declared goods and are in transit do not sell them in the
country for which they were declared.
</P>
<P>
"It will ensure that people don't sell without paying duty
because allowing such business practices can destroy local
economies," Ngwenya said, adding that "1.2 billion U.S. dollars
worth of cash is tied up in customs bonds in commercial banks and
other financial organizations in the region."
</P>
<P>
COMESA is currently working on a zero rating program that will
culminate in the creation of a Free Trade Area by the end of
October this year. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
