<HEADLINE> S. African Gov't Supports Well Organized Trade Unions </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JOHANNESBURG, April 3 (Xinhua) -- South African Deputy
President Jacob Zuma reaffirmed Monday the government's support
for a strong labor movement amid growing tension between
government and the Congress of South African Trade Unions( Cosatu)
over the federation's job loss campaign.
</P>
<P>
Zuma was speaking at the 17th world congress of the
International Confederation of Trade Unions in Durban, South
Africa.
</P>
<P>
The congress, which is being attended by about 1,000 labor
delegates from across the world, is jointly hosted by Cosatu,
Nactu (National Congress of Trade Unions) and Fedusa (Federated
Unions of South Africa).
</P>
<P>
"We are firmly in favor of a strong, well-organized, visionary
and independent trade union movement as this can only be to the
advantage of the transformation project in our country," Zuma
said.
</P>
<P>
His comments came as Cosatu continued its countrywide campaign
against, among others, job losses. The campaign will culminate in
a national strike by Cosatu's 1.8 million members on May 10.
</P>
<P>
Cosatu has claimed that since 1994 there have been 500,000 job
losses. It started its mass action campaign against these job
losses on January 31, with various unions affiliated to the
federation organizing workplace protests and demonstrations.
</P>
<P>
Zuma told the conference that growing unemployment remained one
of the biggest challenges facing trade unions, not only in South
Africa, but across the world.
</P>
<P>
There are still insufficient flows of foreign investment into
African countries, which is vital to their economic prospects such
as job creation, he said.
</P>
<P>
He called on trade unions to focus on issues such as debt
relief and protectionist practices by developed countries who
continually failed to open up markets to developing nations on
favorable conditions.
</P>
<P>
He suggested that trade unions in developed countries invest a
percentage of their retirement and annuity funds towards job
retention and creation in developing countries. 
</P>
