<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Chevron Adds Investment in China's Offshore Oil Exploration </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, April 4 (Xinhua) -- The U.S. oil company Chevron plans
to invest 45 million U.S. dollars in China's offshore exploration
and development this year, a senior Chevron official said here
today.
</P>
<P>
Most of this money is expected to be spent on existing
exploration projects, and the rest on new ventures, said Wes Lohec,
managing director of Chevron Overseas Petroleum Inc's Asia
Business Unit.
</P>
<P>
Chevron was among the first group of foreign oil firms to
become involved in Sino-foreign oil offshore exploration in the
Huizhou Oilsfield of the South China Sea, which now boast the
largest production of any offshore oilfields in China.
</P>
<P>
The Huizhou production center, approximately 160 km offshore of
Hong Kong, came on stream in 1990. Total production from four of
the major fields in Huizhou is now 120,000 barrels of oil per day.
</P>
<P>
China has formed a joint operation team, called the CACT
Operators Group, which includes the China National Offshore Oil
Corporation, Agip, Chevron, and Texaco, to take charge of
operations at the Huizhou fields.
</P>
<P>
Lohec observed that three Chinese oil flagship companies,
namely China National Petroleum Corp.(CNPC), China Offshore Oil Co.
and China Petrochemical Corp.(Sinopec), are streamlining
production and preparing for initial public offerings this year.
</P>
<P>
"I see more openness from CNPC and Sinopec, and I see signs
that they will be more and more open onshore," said Lohec.
</P>
<P>
He said he hopes that the on-going reform will create more
opportunities for the company to have a broader range of projects
with China, including onshore operations and downstream oil
refining, as well as natural gas exploration.
</P>
<P>
Chevron invested 90 million U.S. dollars in a polystyrene plant
in the port city of Zhangjiagang, Jiangsu Province in east China.
The has a production capacity of 100,000 tons a year, and will
become operational in the second quarter of this year.
</P>
<P>
Chevron, whose roots trace back to 1879, is one of the largest
oil refineries in the United States. The company is now preparing
to sink more oil wells in China's Bohai Bay and South China Sea.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
