<DOCNO> XIE20000404.0240 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-04 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Chongqing Dwellers Bid Farewell to Stilted Houses (2) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
He often complained that he felt lonely now. "I even could not
see a neighbor for a couple of days," as all the doors of the
apartments were closed tightly, said he, a retired doctor.
</P>
<P>
While living in the old house, many patients went to visit him.
The demolishment of the old house forced him to end his career as
a doctor, the old man said, adding that the old house was really
damp and dark, but "I'm used to it."
</P>
<P>
Social scholars also felt a pity for the disappearance of the "
diaojiaolou" house. Li Xiangbei, a professor from the Chongqing
University, said that such houses are unique to Chongqing.
Although similar in outer appearance, each "diaojiaolou" house
reflected the difference in the thinking of each family when they
built house.
</P>
<P>
Yin Guojun, assistant director of the Chongqing municipal
construction committee, held a different view. According to him,
a city must first be habitable and then consider the question of
its appearance.
</P>
<P>
The Chongqing municipal government has also sensed the
importance of preserving the city's characteristics and decided to
reserve some unique "diaojiaolou" houses.
</P>
<P>
There are now 10,000 "diaojiaolou" houses in Chongqing, most of
which are due to be dismantled in the next few years. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
