<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-04 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Industrial Base Woos Foreign Loans </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SHENYANG, April 4 (Xinhua) -- Liaoning Province in Northeast
China, home to one-tenth of the country's state-owned enterprises
(SOE), plans to make use of 500 million U.S. dollars of foreign
loans to develop the local economy this year.
</P>
<P>
The province is also working on establishing a special reserve
to ensure that foreign loans can be repaid on time, a provincial
official said today.
</P>
<P>
As China's reform and opening up drive continues, this
traditional industrial base is finding foreign loans an important
resource for local economic and social development.
</P>
<P>
According to statistics, the province borrowed 271.53 million U.
S. dollars from international financial organizations and foreign
governments in 1999 alone. Nearly two-thirds of these loans came
from the World Bank, the province's largest creditor.
</P>
<P>
With these loans, Liaoning has improved its urban
infrastructure and supported sustainable development programs and
afforestation programs in poor areas, and technology renovation
programs in the SOEs in its capital of Shenyang.
</P>
<P>
Non-state enterprises and private businesses in the province
also have access to foreign loans. In 1999 alone, six such
enterprises have received a total of 3.6 million yuan (about 433,
700 U.S. dollars) of World Bank loans as working capital.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
