<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China Creating On-line Library Project </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, April 4 (Xinhua) -- China is now creating an on-line
library that will soon provide services to readers around the
world.
</P>
<P>
Ren Jiyu, director of the National Library of China, said the
library started working on the digital library in 1998 and has now
developed several information repositories.
</P>
<P>
The digital library project aims to build a cross-regional
information network, according to Ren's article published in today
's People's Daily.
</P>
<P>
Supported by a computer network, the library is now compiling a
data base from libraries, museums, memorial halls, publishers, ad
agencies, art institutes, film and television programs, and
tourism departments across the country.
</P>
<P>
The director said that currently, 90 percent of the Internet
information is in English, and the very little information that is
in Chinese hardly reflects China's abundantly rich culture. Some
collections and repositories come from Hong Kong and Taiwan as
well as Singapore where different coding systems are used, he said.
</P>
<P>
"We're now working to digitalize China's 5,000 years of
history by bringing together all sources," he said in his article.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
