<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-04 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Foreign Investment in Vietnam Sags in 1st Quarter </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HANOI, April 4 (Xinhua) -- Vietnam's investment gloom deepened
in the first three months of the year, with total foreign direct
investment (FDI) amounting to only 26 percent of the same period
last year, according to the latest issue of the local newspaper
Vietnam Investment Review.
</P>
<P>
In the first quarter of the year, Vietnam received just 121
million U.S. dollars in FDI capital for both new investments and
expansion of existing projects, according to the Ministry of
Planning and Investment.
</P>
<P>
Over the first quarter, licenses were issued to 37 new FDI
projects with around 88.5 million U.S. dollars in registered
capital, while 14 existing projects injected a further 32.6
million U.S. dollars to expand existing operations.
</P>
<P>
Half of all newly-invested projects were licensed in industrial
and processing zones, with a total of new capital of 40.5 million
U.S. dollars.
</P>
<P>
By the end of last year, Vietnam had licensed 2,296 foreign
investment projects with about 35 billion U.S. dollars in
registered capital. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
