<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-04 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Afghan Currency Hits All-time Low </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ISLAMABAD, April 4 (Xinhua) -- The Afghan currency Afghani has
plummeted to an all-time low amid reports of damage to the country
's opium crop, news reports reaching here said Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
In the capital of Kabul, the value of the Afghani slumped to
around 59,000 Afghanis against the U.S. dollar, showing a six
percent decline. Last week one dollar could fetch 50,000 Afghanis.
</P>
<P>
Witnesses said dealers in the capital's money market were
trying to sell as much Afghanis as they could.
</P>
<P>
They said the downslide followed an increase in the supply of
Afghanis recently on the markets in Kabul and in the southern
province of Kandahar.
</P>
<P>
Some reports said the Afghani started losing value following
reports that opium poppy crops in southern Afghanistan were
damaged by the current drought, which aroused the concern of the
already impoverished people in the war-torn country.
</P>
<P>
Opium production is one of the main revenue resources of
Afghanistan, which has been at war for 20 years now. Last year the
United Nations said the war-torn country was the biggest opium-
producer in the world with a production of 4,600 tons. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
