<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-04 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> S. Korean Won Back to 1,110-Won Level Over Intervention </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SEOUL, April 4 (Xinhua) -- The South Korean won fell to the 1,
110-won range Tuesday on massive buying of dollars by the Bank of
Korea to curb its fast appreciation against the U.S. dollar.
</P>
<P>
The South Korean currency, which appreciated to 1,104 won
against the dollar Monday, was changing hands at 1,130 won Tuesday
afternoon due to the central bank's intervention, which bought at
least 500 million U.S. dollars through domestic commercial banks,
traders said.
</P>
<P>
The central bank's intervention was seen as determination of
the government to maintain the currency rally above the 1,110-won
support level.
</P>
<P>
The intervention came on top of a continued verbal intervention
by the Ministry of Finance and Economy.
</P>
<P>
In a bid to rein in the rising currency, the ministry has
announced that it will issue about one trillion won worth of
foreign exchange equalization bonds this month.
</P>
<P>
The ministry doesn't want the local currency to appreciate
against the greenback too fast because it fears a high won will
deal a serious blow to the nation's exports, which account for
nearly half of its gross domestic product. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE20000404.0259 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-04 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Russia Launches Crew to Mir Space Station </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MOSCOW, April 4 (Xinhua) -- Russia on Tuesday successfully
launched a two-member crew to the Mir space station from the
Baikonur cosmodrome in Kazakhstan, Russian media reported.
</P>
<P>
The Soyuz PM-30 blast off from Baikonur shortly after 9:01 a.m.
Moscow time (0500 GMT) and entered the planned orbit minutes later,
the Interfax news agency reported.
</P>
<P>
The spaceship, carrying flight commander Sergei Zaletin and
flight engineer Alexander Kaleri, is scheduled to dock with Mir on
Thursday.
</P>
<P>
Zaletin is on his first mission to the 14-year-old station, but
it is the third for Kaleri.
</P>
<P>
The official duration of the current mission is 45 days but it
may be prolonged to 60 or 75 days if additional funding is found.
</P>
<P>
It is the first manned flight since Mir was put on auto-pilot a
year ago prior to its planned scrapping. Moscow decided to go
ahead with a new mission after securing 20 million U.S. dollars
from a group of foreign investors.
</P>
<P>
Mir was to have been brought down this year by plunging it
toward earth and burning up in the atmosphere.
</P>
<P>
The task for Zaletin and Kaleri is to reactivate the station
and conduct maintenance operations and repairs on onboard
equipment.
</P>
<P>
One of the most important and complicated tasks is to detect
tiny cracks from which air escapes from the station.
</P>
<P>
The leak of air, which led to a pressure drop in the station,
does not affect the safety of flights because air is disappearing
very slowly and can be compensated from the stores on Mir,
officials said.
</P>
<P>
Mission Control expressed the hope that at least the module
from which the air is leaking should be discovered. Even if the
escape of air is not stopped, it would be very useful for the
future operation of the International Space Station now under
construction.
</P>
<P>
The crew also has to analyze the reliability of the station and
its capability to function. Any further decisions on Mir's use
will be made on the basis of this analysis.
</P>
<P>
The cosmonauts will also conduct a series of scientific
experiments and make a space walk.
</P>
<P>
Last month, a Progress M1-1 supply ship docked with Mir with
fuel and water. Zaletin and Kaleri are expected to receive another
Progress cargo spaceship in April. 
</P>
</TEXT>
