<HEADLINE> U.S. Business Welcomes Support for China Trade from Governors </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LOS ANGELES, April 3 (Xinhua) -- The U.S. leading coalition of
businesses supporting trade with China Monday welcomed the
overwhelming support by America's governors for permanent Normal
Trade Relations (PNTR) with China.
</P>
<P>
In a letter released during President Clinton's visit to
California Monday, more than 40 governors urged Congressional
approval of PNTR.
</P>
<P>
"Governors know PNTR is a no-brainer because they are closest
to the economic heartbeat of the nation," said Myron Brilliant,
managing director for Asia at the U.S. Chamber of Commerce and co-
chairman of the Business Coalition for U.S.-China Trade, in a
statement.
</P>
<P>
"So many of America's governors are united on this issue
because the benefits of trade with China transcend one state or
one region. Increased access to China's markets would benefit the
hog farmer in the heartland just as much as the software whiz in
Silicon Valley."
</P>
<P>
During the president's visit to California, more than 200 chief
executives from America's high-tech industry also endorsed PNTR
with China in an open letter.
</P>
<P>
"The leaders of America's New Economy understand the power of
the Internet to promote change in China," said Calman J. Cohen,
president of the Emergency Committee for American Trade and
another co-chair of the Coalition, in a statement.
</P>
<P>
Also in a statement, Robert A. Kapp, president of the U.S.-
China Business Council and co-chair of the Coalition, welcomed the
decision made by Rep. Zoe Lofgren (D-CA) who was previously
undecided on PNTR and announced her support for the measure Monday.
</P>
<P>
"The solid core of centrists in both parties who support PNTR
continues to expand," Kapp said. "These Democrats and Republicans
know that for America's workers and farmers, China's market access
concessions will be meaningless without timely approval of PNTR."
</P>
<P>
The Business Coalition for U.S.-China Trade consists of over 1,
200 leading American companies, trade associations and farm
organizations that support PNTR with China. It is co-chaired by
the Business Roundtable, the Emergency Committee for American
Trade, the U.S. Chamber of Commerce and the U.S.-China Business
Council. 
</P>
</TEXT>
