<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-04 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> S. Korean Savings Deposits Sharply Up </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SEOUL, April 4 (Xinhua) -- The savings deposits at South
Korea's domestic banks rose 30.59 trillion won (some 27.2 billion
U.S. dollars in the first quarter of this year, bringing the total
to 307.03 trillion won (roughly 270 billion dollars), the Bank of
Korea said Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
The central bank attributed the jump in savings deposits to
customers' preference of safety over profitability in the wake of
the Daewoo Group crisis.
</P>
<P>
The bulk of money withdrawn from investment funds containing
Daewoo bonds moved into local banks, leading to the surge and due
to the Daewoo shock, customers seem to be putting safety before
profits, analyst said.
</P>
<P>
Savings deposits jumped 9.88 trillion won (roughly 8.9 billion
dollars) in January, 12.57 trillion won (11.3 billion dollars) in
February and 8.24 trillion won (7.4 billion dollars) in March.
</P>
<P>
The increase in savings deposits in the quarter is already
close to half the total gain of 66.8 trillion won (60.1 billion
dollars) last year.
</P>
<P>
In contrast to the boom in bank savings deposits, bond-type
beneficiary certificates at investment trust companies saw an
exodus of 28.17 trillion won (25.3 billion dollars) in the first
quarter of this year, the central bank said.
</P>
<P>
Funds invested in bond-type beneficiary certificates decreased
4.93 trillion won (4.4 billion dollars) in January, 16.87 trillion
won (15.2 billion dollars) in February and 6.35 trillion won (5.7
billion dollars) in March.
</P>
<P>
Money deposited at long-term bond-type beneficiary certificates
fell 24.18 trillion won (21.7 billion dollars) in the three-month
period while 3.99 trillion won (3.6 billion dollars) fled short-
term beneficiary certificates.
</P>
<P>
However, stock-type beneficiary certificates jumped 9.35
trillion won (8.4 billion dollars) in the first three months
because of booming stock market. 
</P>
</TEXT>
