<HEADLINE> Chongqing Dwellers Bid Farewell to stilted Houses (1) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CHONGQING, April 4 (Xinhua) -- Fu Xiaoqing, 45, spent his past
43 years with his eight family members in a 40-sq-m stilted house
on mountain slopes, with no cooking gas, no toilet and no water
supply and bath facilities.
</P>
<P>
Recently, Fu moved into an 80-sq apartment in downtown
Chongqing, known as a "city of mountain" in southwest China, with
all modern household facilities, electrical appliances and
beautiful decorations.
</P>
<P>
Fu was one of the beneficiaries of the city's campaign aimed
at dismantling the stilted houses on mountain slopes which were
mainly built along the banks of the Yangtze and Jialingjiang
rivers by boat trackers in the past.
</P>
<P>
The houses built with bamboo matting and wood were called "
diaojiaolou" in Chinese.
</P>
<P>
Such houses notorious for darkness and dampness were now the
target of the city's clean-up campaign.
</P>
<P>
Over the past three years, the municipal government had
invested nearly 30 billion yuan (about 3.6 billion U.S. dollars)
to construct 58 million sq. m. of residential and office buildings
in the city's old area, and about 4,700 families that used to live
in "diaojiaolou" houses have moved into new apartments with
running water, electricity, cooking gas and closed circuit TV. (
more)
</P>
</TEXT>
