<HEADLINE> Corruption Elimination in Bangladesh Could Help GDP: WB </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
DHAKA, April 4 (Xinhua) -- Bangladesh could add 2.1 to 2.9
percent to its annual Gross Domestic Product growth if it could
reduce corruption level to those in countries with the highest
reputation for honest dealing, a World Bank draft report was
quoted by The Daily Star Tuesday as saying.
</P>
<P>
This could also lower the country's poverty rate by 25 percent.
</P>
<P>
The draft report, entitled "Corruption in Bangladesh, Costs and
Cures," is the donors' official paper to be discussed at the
Bangladesh Development Forum which will be held on April 13-14 in
Paris.
</P>
<P>
The World Bank termed the corruption in Bangladesh "
unaffordable, unacceptable and treatable," saying: "Once the
national will is expressed in a consensus that corruption must be
curbed, it can also be cured."
</P>
<P>
The report said the business community in Bangladesh confronts
numerous costly government-imposed rules and obstacles that
encourage corruption.
</P>
<P>
Indecisiveness on the part of the political leadership,
politicization of the civil service, pervasive corruption and
nepotism among civil servants, and the silence of civil society on
this score can all be faulted, the Bank observed. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE20000404.0272 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-04 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Thailand Has its First Cloned Cow: Report </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BANGKOK, April 4 (Xinhua) -- The first calf born by cloning in
Thailand is healthy and lively while scientists foresee a bright
future on dairy animals but see no objection on ethical grounds,
the Bangkok Post reported Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
"Ing" was born at a farm in the western province of Ratchaburi
on March 6. The 29-day-old calf has glittering black fur and a
vibrant nature, the report said.
</P>
<P>
Farmers who dismissed the idea of a cloned cow have now turned
envious and expressed interest in having similar animals, farm
owner Somsak vichaikul was quoted as saying.
</P>
<P>
He said he has no problem with raising cloned cows. "Now I have
three types cows. The natural ones, an artificially inseminated
one and a cloned one living in the same barn."
</P>
<P>
Scientists have kept the identity of Thailand's first cloned
calf a guarded secret.
</P>
<P>
According to Rangsun Parnpai, pioneer researcher for this
project, Ing's parental origin comprised of the SK 29 prototype
cell which was an ear cell from a 13-month Brahmin cow and an egg
extracted from a uterus obtained from a slaughterhouse.
</P>
<P>
The prototype ear cell and egg were fused together by
electricity before being implanted in the womb of a surrogate
mother cow last June.
</P>
<P>
Ing was not born alone. She has a twin brother, "An", which was
conceived through artificial insemination.
</P>
<P>
Maneewan Kamonpatana, director of the Research Center for
Bioscience in Animal Production, was quoted as saying that the
latest achievement has put Thailand in the frontline of animal
breeding technology in the academic world.
</P>
<P>
In practice, it would take another three years to observe Ing
in comparison with naturally born cows.
</P>
<P>
If the clone proves superior, Maneewan said it could become a
cost-effective breeding method for the dairy farming industry.
</P>
<P>
Cloning technology may provide healthier, higher yielding cows
which cost less to raise.
</P>
<P>
On the question of ethics, Maneewan said she expected no
ethical conflict from this experiment. "It is not against nature
at all. There is no genetic engineering involved and the gene of
Ing was not altered or changed," said Maneewan.
</P>
<P>
The center has a similar experiment with 79 other cloned cells
implanted in recipients, but only about 10 are currently pregnant
while the rest have prematurely aborted. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE20000404.0273 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-04 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Concerted Efforts To Combat TB Urged in Pakistan </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ISLAMABAD, April 4 (Xinhua) -- Pakistani Provincial Minister
for Law and Parliamentary Affairs Barrister Shahida Jamil has
called for concerted efforts to eradicate the tuberculosis disease
from the country.
</P>
<P>
At the inaugural ceremony of an international conference on TB
and lung diseases in Karachi on Monday, Shahida Jamil said: "We
should work in partnership to carry forward the task of
elimination of TB and the non-governmental organizations should
also play their role in this respect," according to a news
dispatch received here Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
She said there is a lack of understanding as to what TB is all
about, adding that something wrong appears to be with the medical
education which is needed to be upgraded.
</P>
<P>
She stressed the need for chalking out an effective TB control
strategy and pledged the government's support for it.
</P>
<P>
The World Health Organization representative in Pakistan,
Mohammed Abide Jam, said eight million people develop TB every
year around the globe and each one of them can infect between 10
and 15 people in one year. Up to 50 million people may be infected
with drug-resistant TB.
</P>
<P>
He warned that some one dies of TB every 10 seconds although
almost every one could have or should have been cured. 
</P>
</TEXT>
