<DOCNO> XIE20000404.0275 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-04 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Judge's Ruling Against Microsoft in U.S. Applauded </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Industry analysts believe U.S. District Judge Thomas Penfield
Jackson's ruling that Microsoft violated the Sherman Antitrust Act
by tying its Web browser to its operating system and changed the
competitive landscape in Silicon Valley.
</P>
<P>
One competitor, Red Hat, a Durham, N.C.-based leader in the
emerging Linux operating system, said the ruling will improve
competition in the marketplace and will eventually benefit
Microsoft.
</P>
<P>
"It's not good or bad news in as much as it's going to create
more opportunities for competitors, such as ourselves, to
negotiate contracts with Dell and IBM," Red Hat Chairman Robert
Young said.
</P>
<P>
"We're successfully creating a lot of interest in the
marketplace, but unless our bigger competitor is restrained from
doing some of the things it has been doing in the marketplace, it'
s going to be difficult for us to deliver to the customer," he
added.
</P>
<P>
Young said the only possible negative in the court's decision
is a public relations problem in which the case has forced
technology companies to take sides.
</P>
<P>
Jim Barksdale, former CEO of Netscape, the Web browser that
dominated the market before competition with Microsoft overwhelmed
the company, said he has personally experienced Microsoft's way of
doing business.
</P>
<P>
Sun Microsystems applauded Judge Jackson's decision saying that
only a combination of "stringent structural and behavioral
remedies" against Microsoft will ensure healthy competition.
</P>
<P>
"Today's important decision confirms what almost everybody in
the world knows: Microsoft is a monopoly that has acted illegally,
" said Scott McNealy, Sun's chief executive officer.
</P>
<P>
"The Justice Department and the states deserve immense credit
for putting together a case that so clearly showed Microsoft's
true colors," he added.
</P>
<P>
Intuit Chairman and acting CEO Bill Campbell said the decision
is crucial to "continued innovation on the Internet and the growth
of electronic commerce."
</P>
<P>
"We trust in the continued good efforts of the Department of
Justice and Judge Jackson to determine a fair way to separate the
Windows operating system from Microsoft's other businesses,"
Campbell said.
</P>
<P>
Oracle Corp. said little in a prepared statement beyond saying
it hopes that Judge Jackson's remedies will match the seriousness
of the violations.
</P>
<P>
"We're eagerly awaiting the opportunity to review in detail the
ruling by Judge Jackson in this most important case affecting our
industry," said Dan Cooperman, senior vice president and general
counsel for Oracle Corp.
</P>
<P>
"We hope that the remedies ultimately imposed or agreed upon
will be commensurate with the seriousness of the violation of
antitrust law, which has now been determined by the court," he
added.
</P>
<P>
Corel Corp. was satisfied with the ruling, and expected it will
help improve competition.
</P>
<P>
"For us, anything that is going to enhance competition in the
marketplace is going to be a good thing for consumers," said
Kathryn Hughes, a spokeswoman for Corel Corp.
</P>
<P>
At least 20 of 50 states filed antitrust suits against
Microsoft during the past years.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE20000404.0276 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-04 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Round-up: S.Korea Launches Campaign to Fight Livestock Disease </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SEOUL, April 4 (Xinhua) -- South Korea has launched an all-out
campaign to fight the spread of a vesicular disease called hoof-
and-mouth disease among livestock
</P>
<P>
Cases of the epidemic disease have been reported in other areas
in the country after livestock in Paju, Hongsong, and Yonki were
found dead from the disease this week.
</P>
<P>
The hoof-and-mouth disease, dubbed livestock AIDS, causes
blisters on the mouths and hoofs of livestock, has killed
innumerable head of livestock in the country.
</P>
<P>
It is caused by a highly infectious virus which spreads very
fast to hoofed livestock through air and fodder, but has up to a
two-week incubation period.
</P>
<P>
Fearing that a nationwide spread of the disease will destroy
the nation's livestock industry, the South Korean government
decided at an emergency meeting Monday to vaccinate 12,000 heads
of cattle and pigs per day and to conduct a serum inspection of
all livestock throughout the country.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, It has also decided to destroy and bury all the
livestock within a 20-kilometer radius of the affected areas.
</P>
<P>
The government has also earmarked 3.5 billion won (3.16 million
U.S. dollars) to compensate the farmers whose livestock were
slaughtered to prevent spread of the epidemic.
</P>
<P>
Owing to the outbreak of the epidemic, Japan and China's Taiwan
have suspended import of livestock and meat from South Korea,
while the United States and Australia have halted import of dairy
products.
</P>
<P>
Experts warned that the entire foundation of South Korea's
livestock industry and exports are at stake, citing the example of
the same disease which cost China's Taiwan astronomical losses,
including 180,000 job losses in the Chinese province in 1997.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, observers said Japan will likely ban imports of
South Korean livestock and meat at least one year. South Korea
exported pork worth 415 million dollars to Japan last year.
</P>
<P>
To make matters worse, domestic consumption of beef and pork
decreased recently in the aftermath of the outbreak of the
livestock epidemic.
</P>
<P>
However, the Bank of Korea officials said that livestock
industry accounts for 0.67 percent of the country's GDP and 26
percent of total production, estimating the yearly damages at 310
billion won (some 300 million dollars). 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
