<TEXT>
<P>
TOKYO, April 4 (Xinhua) -- The condition of Japanese Prime
Minister Keizo Obuchi, who remains in a coma after suffering a
stroke Sunday, is believed to have worsened Tuesday morning, Kyodo
News reported, quoting political sources.
</P>
<P>
Obuchi's Family members were assembled at the Tokyo hospital
where he is staying.The prime minister's daughter Yuko returned
from her studies in Britain and arrived there in the morning, the
report said.
