<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Clinton Reiterates Call For PNTR With China </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LOS ANGELES, April 3 (Xinhua) -- U.S. President Bill Clinton
Monday reiterated his call for congressional approval of permanent
normal trade relations (PNTR) with China in a speech in the
Silicon Valley, where high-tech executives and moderate Democrats
strongly support free trade with China.
</P>
<P>
"If we do this, 20 years from now, we will wonder why we ever
had a serious debate about it," the president said. "If we don't
do it, 20 years from now, we'll still be kicking ourselves for
being so dumb."
</P>
<P>
Speaking at San Jose's Technology Museum of Innovation in the
center of Silicon Valley, Clinton said the defeat of PNTR with
China would have negative consequences for the U.S. economy and
for Sino-U.S. relations.
</P>
<P>
"The main consequence of this would be to hurt America
economically and to dramatically strain our relationship with
China at a time when we need to maintain a positive ability to
impact their conduct, to reduce strains along the Taiwan Straits,
and to get the leaders in that country to imagine the greatness of
their country in future terms, not yesterday's terms," Clinton
said, emphasizing "This is a big deal."
</P>
<P>
House Minority leader Richard Gephardt, California Gov. Gray
Davis, as well as 150 executives from high-tech companies attended
the event.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, The Clinton administration Monday released two
letters urging Congress to approve PNTR with China, one signed by
40 governors supporting trade with China, and the other by chief
executive officers of 200 high-tech companies, including Microsoft,
IBM and Sun Microsystems, who recently began a major lobbying
campaign in Capitol Hill for PNTR with China.
</P>
<P>
"We consider it the most critical vote you will make in support
of our high-technology industries," the executives wrote in their
letter to Congressmen.
</P>
<P>
U.S. Congress is scheduled to vote on PNTR with China in May.
Some House Democrats and organized labor oppose the trade
agreement.
</P>
<P>
"We tried to get the high-technology community more involved in
the effort around this vote," White House spokesman Jake Siewert
said. "A lot of members on the Hill listen to the high-tech
community. They are the ones creating jobs." 
</P>
</TEXT>
