<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Thai Inflation Low Despite Oil Price Hikes </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BANGKOK, April 4 (Xinhua) -- Thailand's Consumer Price Index (
CPI) in the first quarter of this year rose only 0.9 percent from
the same period last year despite recent oil price hikes, the
Bangkok Post reported Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
World oil prices reached a record high of 30 U.S. dollars a
barrel last month, causing diesel prices in Thailand to mount to
nearly 13 baht (35 U.S. cents) a liter while premium petrol to 16
baht (43 cents).
</P>
<P>
Quoting the Commerce Ministry, the newspaper said the oil price
rises had contributed to an increase in the non-food and beverage
index by 2.5 percent in the first quarter.
</P>
<P>
The transport and communication sector saw the steepest rise at
8.3 percent, followed by tobacco and alcoholic drinks at 1.9
percent.
</P>
<P>
However, the food and beverage index contracted by 1.7 percent
due to declines in farm product prices.
</P>
<P>
The ministry said the figures showed that Thai consumers in
general were not experiencing inflationary pressure.
</P>
<P>
Thailand has projected a 2.2 percent to 2.5 percent inflation
rate in 2000, up from the 0.3 percent rate in 1999. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
