<DOCNO> XIE20000404.0286 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-04 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Automakers Report Mixed Results In Sales </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
March appeared to be another in a string of good months,
industry experts said, adding that the strong economy and price
competition among automakers were pulling buyers into showrooms
despite higher interest rates and gas prices.
</P>
<P>
Ford, the world's No. 2 automaker, said total sales, including
heavy trucks and its upscale Jaguar and Volvo divisions, rose to
441,701 units. That was a record high for any single month at Ford,
and compared with U.S. sales of 399,908 in March 1999. The
previous monthly sales record was 424,091 units, set in June 1978.
</P>
<P>
"U.S. consumers are confirming that this is a great time to buy
a new car or truck," Bob Rewey, Ford's North American sales chief,
said in a statement.
</P>
<P>
General Motors Corp., the world's largest automaker, said U.S.
sales rose 1.1 percent, excluding its Saab unit, to 458,115 units,
thanks mostly to a 16.2 percent rise in sales in light trucks.
Even so, the results fell short of analysts' expectations of a 2
percent to 4 percent gain.
</P>
<P>
GM officials said the results reflected the company's success
in aligning its production with consumer tastes.
</P>
<P>
"We are determined to closely align our vehicle mix with
consumer demand," Bill Lovejoy, GM's North American sales and
marketing chief, said in a statement. "Trucks are a hot commodity.
"
</P>
<P>
Daimler-Chrysler sales were up 4 percent because of a 12
percent rise in car sales. Its mid-sized cars saw the largest
gains, with the Dodge Intrepid up 34 percent and the Chrysler
Concorde up 21 percent.
</P>
<P>
Truck sales were up 1 percent, with demand for mini-vans and
Dodge Dakota four-door pickups outweighing a decline in Dodge and
Jeep SUV sales. Jamie Jameson, Daimler- Chrysler's vice president
for sales and marketing operations, said SUV sales suffered from a
comparison to an even better month last year.
</P>
<P>
U.S. sales for Japan's Toyota Motor Corp. rose 16 percent to a
best-ever March performance of 140,393 units, as strong demand for
its light trucks offset a decline in sales of the top-selling U.S.
car, the Camry mid-sized sedan.
</P>
<P>
"It's March madness," Jim Press, Toyota executive vice
president, said in a statement. "Consumers closed out the first
quarter with a fast-break buying spree, extending the industry's
string of record-breaking months into overtime."
</P>
<P>
Honda Motor Co. said sales jumped 20 percent, largely because
of a boost in Odyssey mini-van sales.
</P>
<P>
Nissan Motor Co. said its sales were up 11 percent, mostly
behind sales of the Xterra and the Frontier pickup.
</P>
<P>
Volkswagen AG said its U.S. sales were up 20 percent.
</P>
<P>
The Mercedes-Benz side of Daimler-Chrysler said its sales were
up 15 percent. Its M-Class SUVs were up 37 percent, while sales of
its luxury cars climbed 10 percent.
</P>
<P>
Sales of South Korea's Hyundai Motor Co. Ltd. surged almost 84
percent last month. Vehicle sales for Japan's Subaru sales rose 4.
7 percent. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
