<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-04 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> U.S. Grants Visa to Cuban Boy's Father </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, April 3 (Xinhua) -- The U.S. State Department
granted a visa Monday night for the father of the Cuban boy, Elian
Gonzalez, to come to the United States and told the boy's
relatives in Florida to hand over the boy to his father.
</P>
<P>
The father, Juan Miguel Gonzalez, will be able to get his visa
as early as on Tuesday. Five others including Elian's kindergarten
teacher in Cuba were also granted visas, State Department
spokesman James Rubin said.
</P>
<P>
"The visas could be issued as early as tomorrow morning," Rubin
added. The visa requests were presented to the U.S. diplomatic
mission in Havana, Cuba last week.
</P>
<P>
Also on Monday night, negotiations between Elian's relatives
and the Immigration and Naturalization Service (INS) over the
custody of the boy adjourned without any result, reports reaching
here from Miami said.
</P>
<P>
An Associated Press report said that the negotiations had
shifted Monday to how to reunite Elian with his father when he
arrives in this country.
</P>
<P>
The Justice Department last week demanded that Elian's
relatives in Florida promise to surrender the six-year-old Cuban
boy if they lose their court fight and said that it would end the
custody of the boy by Tuesday morning.
</P>
<P>
Elian, who is currently under the custody of his great uncle,
Lazaro Gonzalez, in Florida, was rescued on November 25 last year
from a shipwreck after his mother and 11 others died when the boat
capsized in the sea off Florida.
</P>
<P>
The INS ruled earlier this year that the boy belongs to his
father and should be returned to Cuba.
</P>
<P>
However, the decision to return him was delayed after the boy's
great uncle in Florida filed a political asylum for him. U.S.
District Judge K. Michael Moore ruled that only the U.S. attorney
general can grant political asylum to the boy.
</P>
<P>
The boy's father in Cuba, supported by the Cuban government,
insisted that his son should be returned to him while the boy's
great uncle, backed by some anti-Cuba politicians in the U.S.,
asked the boy to stay with him. 
</P>
</TEXT>
