<HEADLINE> Xinhua World Economic News Summary at 0450 GMT, April 4 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON -- Fifty percent of Britons believe Britain will have
joined the European single currency by 2010 whether they like it
or not, according to an opinion poll published on Monday.
</P>
<P>
The Gallop poll for the Daily Telegraph newspaper showed that
46 percent believed Britain would not join the euro by then.
</P>
<P>
Sixty-four percent believed euro membership would be a bad
development for Britain and only 32 percent thought it would be
good. (UK-Euro-Poll)
</P>
<P>
BRUSSELS -- The 11-country euro zone registered a trade deficit
of 3.8 billion euros (some 3.65 billion U.S. dollars) with the
rest of the world in January this year, up 280 percent over a year
ago, the European Union's statistical office, Eurostat, said
Monday.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, the initial estimate of the EU's external trade for
January 2000 was a deficit of 12.3 billion euros (some 11.8
billion dollars). In January 1999, the 15-nation bloc recorded an
external trade deficit of 6.8 billion euros (about 7.9 billion
dollars). (Euro Zone-Trade)
</P>
<P>
TEHRAN -- Iranian Oil Minister Bijan Namdar Zanganeh said here
on Monday that Iran seeks an oil output hike to preserve its share
in the world oil market but will not go for a production rise
which may ruin the market.
</P>
<P>
Iran is seeking a rise in oil production given the market
realities, Zanganeh stressed, adding its policy of not flooding
the market with additional oil does not mean that Iran will not
increase its production. (Iran-Oil)
</P>
<P>
ADDIS ABABA -- Ethiopian economy is facing a big challenge from
ever-increasing shortage of power, a signed article published by
the latest issue of Capital Weekly has warned.
</P>
<P>
The overall situation of the energy sector is not encouraging
and leaves much to be desired, the article said.
</P>
<P>
Power consumers, including citizens of Addis Ababa, currently
face alternate power disruption from 7:00 a.m. to 8:00 p.m. (local
time) cycling every four days. (Ethiopia-Power Shortage)
</P>
<P>
LUANDA -- The Angolan government and the Antwerp's High Council
on Diamonds of Belgium have signed an accord to combat gem
trafficking and to create "transparent control of the diamond
trade", according to an official statement reaching here on Monday.
Angola-Belgium-Accord
</P>
<P>
DAR ES SALAAM -- About 70 percent of the workers of Tanzania's
largest commercial bank will be sacked following the sale of the
bank to a South African company last week, the regional East
African weekly newspaper reported on Monday.
</P>
<P>
Employers of the National Bank of Commerce (NBC) of Tanzania
have been told by the new owners of the former state bank, the
Amalgamated Banks of South Africa (ABSA), that some 733 out of a
total of 1,100 workers must be retrenched, about 350 of them"soon".
Tanzania-Retrenchment
</P>
<P>
WASHINGTON -- A federal judge found Monday that Microsoft Corp.
violated the Sherman Antitrust Act, "maintained its monopoly power
by anticompetitive means" and attempted to monopolize the Web
browser market.
</P>
<P>
U.S. District Court Judge Thomas Penfield Jackson also ruled
that Microsoft violated another section of the law by "unlawfully
tying its Web browser to its operating system" and could be sued
under state anti-competition laws. (US-Judge-Microsoft)
</P>
<P>
CAIRO -- French President Jacques Chirac pledged on Monday that
France will cancel debts of the poorest countries within one or
two years.
</P>
<P>
Chirac made the pledge while addressing the first Africa-Europe
summit opened here earlier in the day. But he neither gave the
figures of the debts that France will write off nor mentioned the
poorest countries. (France-Debt Cancellation)
</P>
<P>
LOS ANGELES -- Houston-based Anadarko Petroleum Corp. agreed to
acquire Fort Worth, Texas-based Union Pacific Resources Group Inc.
for 4.4 billion dollars in stock Monday, continuing the ongoing
consolidation in the worldwide oil exploration and production
industry.
</P>
<P>
Anadarko currently ranks as one of the world's largest
independent oil and natural gas exploration and production
companies, while Union Pacific has ranked as the No. 1 domestic
driller during each of the last seven years.
</P>
<P>
The deal between the two, according to industry analysts,
creates an independent energy powerhouse boasting proved reserves
of nearly 2 billion barrels of oil and 11.7 trillion cubic feet of
natural gas, primarily drawn from U.S.-based assets.  (US-Firm
Merge) 
</P>
</TEXT>
