<HEADLINE> Book on Findings of Ancient Ruins Published in Xinjiang </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
URUMQI, April 4 (Xinhua) -- China has published the second
volume of a book on research findings of a joint Sino-Japanese
exploration to Niya, an ancient city buried in China's largest
desert.
</P>
<P>
The book covers archaeological discoveries made between 1994
and 1997 at the Niya ruins in the Taklimakan Desert in Xinjiang in
northwest China.
</P>
<P>
The first volume of the book was published in 1995, introducing
the discoveries made during their joint exploration from 1988 to
1993.
</P>
<P>
The Niya ruins, known as the Pompeii on the ancient Silk Road,
were the site of the ancient Jingjue Kingdom set up at an oasis by
the Niya River during the Han (206 BC-AD 220) and Jin (265-420 AD)
dynasties
</P>
<P>
According to historical records, the kingdom, located at the
foot of the Kunlun Mountains, had only 480 households with 3,360
persons during the Han Dynasty.
</P>
<P>
It became famous and prosperous on the ancient Silk Road during
the Tang Dynasty (618-907), and was buried in sands later.
</P>
<P>
Chinese and Japanese archaeologists formed a joint exploration
team in 1988 and have made nine explorations to the ruins for the
past 12 years, according to Chinese archaeologists.
</P>
<P>
They have found some 200 sites of relics including tombs of
aristocrats and a variety of burial objects.
</P>
<P>
The newly published book, in both Chinese and Japanese, is a
comprehensive summary of the joint exploration between 1994 and
1997. It will also be translated into English soon, according to
the Urumqi Publishing House. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE20000404.0294 </DOCNO>
