<HEADLINE> Poland's Economy Worsens in First Two Months </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WARSAW, April 3 (Xinhua) -- Poland's economic situation
worsened in the first two months of this year with continuing weak
exports, an increased current account deficit, and a heightened
unemployment rate.
</P>
<P>
The east European country's exports dropped to 2.07 billion U.
S. dollars in February from 2.50 billion dollars in the same
period last year, statistics released by Poland's state bank on
Monday revealed.
</P>
<P>
The current account deficit rose to 2.16 billion dollars by
March from 1.41 billion in the same period last year. The figure
represents 8 percent of the gross domestic product, compared with
the 1999 level of 7.5 percent.
</P>
<P>
The monthly deficit in February reached 949 million dollars,
nearly doubling that of February, 1999.
</P>
<P>
According to official data issued earlier, the number of
jobless people in Poland increased to 2.53 million in February,
bringing the unemployment rate up to 13.9 percent from 13.6
percent in January.
</P>
<P>
Experts here believe that Poland's economic situation failed
to improve because of the weak export.
</P>
<P>
In February, direct foreign investment in Poland was estimated
at about 1.12 billion dollars, up from 608 million in February,
1999.  
</P>
</TEXT>
