<HEADLINE> Obuchi Remains in Coma, Cabinet to Resign En Masse Soon: Acting PM </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TOKYO, April 4 (Xinhua) -- Japanese Prime Minister Keizo
Obuchi remains in a coma but his blood pressure is stable, Acting
Prime Minister Mikio Aoki said Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
Obuchi's condition "remains the same as it was yesterday," Aoki
told a press conference.
</P>
<P>
To avoid a political vacuum in the country, the cabinet will
resign en masse in a day or two, the top government spokesman said.
</P>
<P>
Yoshiro Mori, who holds the No. 2 post of secretary general in
Obuchi's ruling Liberal Democratic Party (LDP), is expected to
succeed Obuchi as party president, which also entails the
premiership.
</P>
<P>
Doctors at Tokyo's Juntendo University Hospital are maintaining
the same type of treatment for Obuchi, putting him on a respirator
and using medication to keep his blood pressure stable at a
sufficient level, Aoki said.
</P>
<P>
Obuchi was taken to the private university hospital around 1 a.
m. Sunday after suffering a stroke at his official residence. He
was moved to the hospital's intensive care unit and put on a
respirator after his condition worsened Sunday night. 
</P>
