<HEADLINE> Australian Scientists Grows Human Nerve Cells </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CANBERRA, April 4 (Xinhua) -- Australian scientists have
succeeded in growing human nerve cells from embryonic stem cells,
the Age daily reported Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
The breakthrough was made by Professor Alan Trounson and Dr
Martin Pera of the Monash Institute of Reproduction and
Development at Monash University, with colleagues from Israel and
Singapore.
</P>
<P>
Creating human nerve cells opened the way for new treatments
for degenerative diseases such as Alzheimer's Parkinson's and
stroke.
</P>
<P>
Embryonic stem cells are cells derived from the early embryo,
which have the potential to become any cell in the body.
</P>
<P>
Professor Trounson was quoted as saying: "We've been able to
get them to form pure nerve cells out of the embryonic stem cell
line -- no one has done that before."
</P>
<P>
"If these nerve cells produce dopamine they could be used to
treat Parkinson's disease, for example, or in any nerve tissue
repair where there has been an injury," he said. "The implications
are just massive. If we can do this then the next thing may be to
grow blood cells to treat blood diseases or muscle cells."
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE20000404.0305 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-04 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Panama Canal Toll Income Increases </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
PANAMA CITY, April 3 (Xinhua) -- Income for Panama Canal tolls
reached 240.2 million U.S. dollars, 3.3 million dollars more than
expected during the period of October 1999 to February 2000.
</P>
<P>
Alberto Aleman Zubieta, administrator with the Panama Canal
Authority (PCA), revealed Monday that the total number of ship's
using the canal reached an average of 33.3 passages per day, or 5,
061 crossings in the first five months of the fiscal year, which
began on October 1,1999, to September 30, this year.
</P>
<P>
Aleman also said the widening project of Corte Culebra, the
canal's narrowest point has been 83 percent completed and is
expected to be finished by December.
</P>
<P>
"Figures show the Canal keeps on being a route of importance
for world sea trading. We continue working on it to increase
capacity and so be able to offer a quicker and safer service to
our users."
</P>
<P>
The 81.3 kilometer-long Canal, continues to play a significant
role in world sea trading as a shortcut between the Pacific and
Atlantic oceans.
</P>
<P>
The Panama government assumed its full responsibility for the
management, operation and maintenance of the canal and the canal
zone on December 31, 1999, ending the Panama Canal Treaty which
was signed with the United States in 1903.  
</P>
</TEXT>
