<HEADLINE> Foreign Investment Hits Record in Czech Republic </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Prague, April 3 (Xinhua) -- The Czech Republic attracted 5.1
billion U.S. dollars of foreign capital in 1999, doubled from
previous year, setting a new historic record, according to the
statistics released by Czech National Bank.
</P>
<P>
From April 1998, the Czech government led by Prime Minister
Milos Zeman adopted a series of measures aiming to draw foreign
investment. The investors, who invested over 10 million dollars in
the country, would be free from income tax for five years. The
land used to establish free tax zones could get interest-free
loans. The new measures led to the rapid increase of foreign
capital to 2.4 billion dollars in 1998, 84.6 percent more than in
1997.
</P>
<P>
The foreign investment attracted by the Czech Republic in 1999
was in the second place among the central easteuropean countries,
following Poland. While the average, 493 dollars per person, was
the highest among the nations.
</P>
<P>
Foreign capital is gaining momentum in the country. Holland's
Philips will invest 640 million Euros here to set up the second
biggest color phenotype company in the world. Some big companies
from Japan, South Korea, as well as American and other European
countries are also planning to build branches in the Czech
Republic. 
</P>
</TEXT>
