single mothers with children, formed long lines Monday in
different banks in Ecuador to cash their solidarity bonus,
economic assistance the government provided for those least
protected.
</P>
<P>
These beneficiaries were surprised when they received --
instead of 75 or 100 sucres -- three and four U.S. dollars. Their
solidarity bonus, also called poverty bonus, had been dollarized,
and for the first time, citizens were receiving their payment in
dollars, a situation that baffled many who were not aware of the
currency change.
</P>
<P>
Ecuador's government started on November 4, 1998, to pay
solidarity bonuses to compensate the eliminating of subsidies for
electricity, domestic gas and diesel for the poorest sectors.
</P>
<P>
This Monday is the first day that solidarity bonus's
beneficiaries received their payment in dollars. Dollarizing began
April 1 in this country. Meanwhile, supermarkets and department
stores are charging buyers in dollars, or sucres.
</P>
<P>
However, in public institutions, charging in dollars hasn't
been standardized yet, which has seen citizens changing their
dollars to sucres for making electricity, drinking water and
telephone payments.
</P>
<P>
The Ecuadorian government announced earlier this year, its
currency, the sucre, would be replaced by the U.S. dollar and will
gradually disappear in the next six months. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
