<HEADLINE> China Is Safe for Foreigners Despite Killing of Germans: Spokesman </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BERLIN, April 3 (Xinhua) -- A German Foreign Ministry spokesman
said Monday that China is "still an extremely safe place" for
tourists despite the killing of a German family in the eastern
city of Nanjing on Sunday.
</P>
<P>
The spokesman told reporters that his government will not issue
any warning against traveling to China.
</P>
<P>
Such a warning is issued only when the security order of the
destination has collapsed and foreigners face unpredictable danger,
he said, adding that China is not the case at all.
</P>
<P>
Also on Monday, a spokeswoman for Daimler-Chrysler said in
Stuttgart that what happened in Nanjing was just an isolate
incident, adding, "China is a safe country."
</P>
<P>
The four members of a German family were stabbed to death when
fighting burglars at their home in the early hours of Sunday in
Nanjing, the capital of east China's Jiangsu Province.
</P>
<P>
The victims were Juergen Pfrang, 51, deputy general manager of
Yaxing-Benz, a Sino-German automotive joint venture in the city of
Yangzhou in Jiangsu Province, his wife, son and daughter. All four
suspects were caught on the spot by the police. 
</P>
</TEXT>
