<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-04 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Canadian Engineer Tests Flapping-Wing Plane </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
OTTAWA, April 3 (Xinhua) -- A Canadian engineer is testing a
flapping-wing plane in the hope that the bird-like ornithopter
will take its historic flight this summer.
</P>
<P>
This is the world's first practice to realize a dream as
ancient as that of Icarus, the Ottawa Citizen daily reported
Monday.
</P>
<P>
The aircraft, spanning 12 meters and weighing 330 kilograms,
derives all of its thrust and lift from flapping its wings.
</P>
<P>
A 93-pound woman will pilot the plane at a "secret" airstrip
outside Toronto if all the kinks are sorted out, the newspaper
said.
</P>
<P>
James DeLaurier, a professor at the University of Toronto
Institute for Aerospace Studies, started building models in 1973.
</P>
<P>
A flapping flying machine is finally close to being viable
because DeLaurier and his team developed a computer program to
analyze complex engineering problems presented by ornithopter
flight.
</P>
<P>
The plane will have a pair of wings constructed strong enough
to withstand extraordinary pressure, while keeping light weight
and flexible enough to twist in the corkscrew motion necessary to
sustain flight.
</P>
<P>
Although humans have made smaller ornithopter models fly,
DeLaurier's structure will be the first full-scale, piloted
flapping flying machine to take off, said the newspaper. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
