<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-04 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China Downsizes Local Government </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HEFEI, April 4 (Xinhua) -- Anhui Province in East China, dubbed
the "cradle of China's rural reforms," has started to
significantly cut its government employees as part of a national
effort to downsize local government departments and staff.
</P>
<P>
Zhang Ping, Anhui's deputy provincial governor, said that
provincial departments in his province will be reduced by 27
percent this year, with the staff being cut by 48.5 percent.
</P>
<P>
Those to be cut off will either be guided to work at
governments at lower levels, enterprises and research institutes,
or be sent to study at universities over the next three years,
Zhang said, adding that they are also encouraged to set up private
businesses.
</P>
<P>
Also in east China, Shandong Province, which ranks third in the
country in terms of gross domestic product, plans to cut its
government employees by 48 percent and reduce the number of
provincial government departments from 67 to 46.
</P>
<P>
China's local government restructuring plan, which aims to
increase government efficiency, has called for halving the staff
of local governments.  
</P>
</TEXT>
