<BODY>
<HEADLINE> N.Z. Industrial Giant on Way to Ending Letter Stocks </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WELLINGTON, April 4 (Xinhua) -- Fletcher Challenge Group (FCL),
a New Zealand industrial giant, has moved closer to dismantling
its letter stocks with the announcement of a five billion NZ
dollar (2.5 billion U.S. dollar) cash-for-shares sale of Fletcher
Paper to Norwegian printing paper giant Norske Skog, the Dominion
reported Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
The announcement was made Monday night in Auckland, the biggest
city in New Zealand. The move paves the way for dismantling
unpopular letter-stocks structure of the four divisions of
Building, Paper, Forests and Energy set up by former FCL Chief
Executive Hugh Fletcher in 1993 under the umbrella of the
corporate Fletcher Challenge Group. Though listed separately,
their performances are still consolidated into one group.
</P>
<P>
Fletcher Paper operates in New Zealand, Australia, Asia, South
America and Canada. The biggest sale in New Zealand's corporate
history signals the end of a business started in 1952.
</P>
<P>
The sale, subject to approval by all FCL shareholders, the vote
of Norske Skog's Corporate Assembly (an independent body to the
board) and to regulatory approvals, is expected to be completed by
early July.
</P>
<P>
The purchase of Fletcher Paper will make Norske Skog the second
largest manufacturer of newsprint in the world, lifting its
ranking from fourth.
</P>
<P>
The Wellington-based newspaper quoted FCL Chairman Roderick
Deane as saying Monday night that he was hopeful the other letter-
stock divisions will be separated into their own entities by the
end of the year.
</P>
<P>
The four Fletcher stocks make up about 6.5 percent of the
benchmark NZSE 40 capital index. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
