<HEADLINE> Paraguay to Negotiate Vehicle-Trading Rules Within Mercosur </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BUENOS AIRES, April 3 (Xinhua) -- Paraguayan Foreign Minister
Juan Esteban Aguirre announced Monday that his country is set to
negotiate concrete points of vehicle-trading rules within the
Southern Common Market (Mercosur).
</P>
<P>
A Paraguayan delegation will bring up at a meeting of Common
Market Group (GMC), Mercosur's executive body, a new defining of
regional tariffs for vehicles, said Esteban.
</P>
<P>
He explained taxing 35 percent for imports from countries
outside the body, collected by Argentina and Brazil on March 23,
has rather a fiscal than a productive impact.
</P>
<P>
The foreign minister hopes that consensus will be reached among
the body's four members concerning the system of vehicle trading.
</P>
<P>
Mercosur is made up of Argentina, Brazil, Paraguay and Uruguay,
with Bolivia and Chile as associate members. 
