<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-04 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Wild Ducks Return to Sino-DPRK Border River </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SHENYANG, April 4 (Xinhua) -- Wild ducks have reappeared on a
border river between China and the Democratic People's Republic of
Korea, after having vanished for many years.
</P>
<P>
There are now tens of thousands of wild ducks and other
waterfowl to be seen on the Yalu River, said Cao Renjiang, an
official with the environmental protection bureau of Dandong City,
located on the river.
</P>
<P>
Flocks of wild ducks appear only in safe places with clean
water and enough food, he said. "This shows that the environment
along the River has been greatly improved," he noted.
</P>
<P>
The number of wild ducks has increased following the
establishment of a nature reserve centered on the outfalls of the
Yalu and Dayang rivers in 1997. 
</P>
</TEXT>
