<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Tel Aviv Considers Biding for 2012 Olympic Games </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JERUSALEM, April 4 (Xinhua) -- Israel's Tel Aviv showed its
intention to make a bid for hosting the 2012 Olympic Games,
sources in the city's municipality revealed Monday night.
</P>
<P>
Tel Aviv Mayor Ron Huldai announced the desire at a news
conference, in which he also unveiled an architectural model for a
potential Olympic project, the sources said.
</P>
<P>
Local International Olympic Committee (IOC) members attended
the conference to endorse Tel Aviv's possible bid.
</P>
<P>
The cost of hosting the Olympics would amount to 9.6 billion U.
S. dollars, with most of it covering massive infrastructure
constructing, such as a new subway system in the city.
</P>
<P>
Some observers pointed out that the Olympics had never been
held in a Middle East country, which increases the hope for Tel
Aviv's success.
</P>
<P>
However, according to these observers, the critical issue would
be the progress of the Middle East peace process. If there will be
peace deals between Israel and its Arab neighbors, the bid would
be possible attractive.
</P>
<P>
If the process was still in stalemate at the time of IOC making
final decision, Tel Aviv's chance would be slim as it would
encounter possible boycott by some Arab countries.
</P>
<P>
The host of 2008 Olympic Games has not been decided by IOC. Ten
contenders, including Beijing, Bangkok, Cairo, Havana, Istanbul,
Kuala Lumpur, Osaka, Paris, Seville, Toronto, had submitted their
applications.
</P>
<P>
The 2000 Olympics would be held in Sydney, Australia this
summer, and Athens had already been confirmed as the host for 2004
Olympic Games. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
