<HEADLINE> Rwandan Genocide Survivors Need Compensation </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NAIROBI, April 3 (Xinhua) -- It is necessary to establish a
compensation fund to assist over 800,000 Rwandan genocide
survivors, Rwanda News Agency quoted officials as saying on
Monday.
</P>
<P>
"There is need for a compensation fund to be in place as soon
as possible," said Jean de Dieu mucyo, minister of Justice and
Institutional Relations.
</P>
<P>
"The genocide survivors have not yet had full justice done,
since none of them has been compensated for the past five years,"
said Frederick Mutagwera, president of the Genocide Survivors
Association.
</P>
<P>
He said, however, the government had tried to assist genocide
survivors by treating genocide survivors with severe injuries,
bringing about 25,000 children to schools and building houses for
survivors.
</P>
<P>
Rwandans began a week-long commemoration last Saturday to mark
the sixth anniversary of the genocide led by Hutu extremists in
April 1994 which claimed over 800,000 lives of Tutsis and moderate
Hutus. 
</P>
</TEXT>
