<DOCNO> XIE20000404.0341 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-04 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Tel Aviv Stock Index Up Against "Microsoft Shock" </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JERUSALEM, April 4 (Xinhua) -- Israel's Tel Aviv Stock Exchange
(TASE) registered moderate gains Tuesday in the shadow of the U.S.
court ruling that Microsoft Corp. violated the antitrust law.
</P>
<P>
After a volatile day of trading, the Tel Aviv 100 index closed
up 1.02 percent to 498.91 points, and the blue-chip Maof index (Tel
Aviv 25) rose by 1.25 percent to 505.81 points.
</P>
<P>
Most TASE analysts breathe a sigh of relief after the close,
comparing the gains with the continuous diving of the Nasdaq
composite index in the U.S. and some other stock markets in other
parts of the world.
</P>
<P>
The technology-dominated Nasdaq plunged below 4,000-point
psychological line on Tuesday, its first time in two months,
because of market shocks of the Microsoft ruling.
</P>
<P>
The ruling issued on Monday decided that the software giant
founded by Bill Gates "maintained its monopoly power by anti-
competitive means," and attempted to monopolize the web browser
market.
</P>
<P>
U.S. District Judge Thomas Penfield Jackson also ruled that a
new round of rulings should be held to determine punishment to
impose on Microsoft, including the question of whether the company
should be broken up.
</P>
<P>
Since then, the Microsoft shares had lost nearly 15 percent of
its value. It led to market panic and dragged down all stock price
indices in the world.
</P>
<P>
TASE, widely regarded as another hi-tech shares center and
having many similarities with Nasdaq, also could not turn a blind
eye to the market reactions.
</P>
<P>
Thus, local analysts warned, Tuesday's gains simply don't mean
the crisis is over as long as the hi-tech shares, especially those
of the Internet start-ups, are still irrationally overvalued.
</P>
<P>
Most Internet companies never earn money and some even posted
large cash losses. Their share prices go up not because of their
economic achievement, but because of a flow of hot money from
amateur investors, according to these analysts.
</P>
<P>
They pointed out the Tel Aviv 100 broke the 500 barrier and is
16 percent below its level of March 5 (586 points). Maof also lost
nearly 9 percent in less than a month while the Teltech index of
technology stocks has fallen a total of 30 percent since the
beginning of March.
</P>
<P>
All the market indicators ominously predicted an even bigger
crash in the near future, an analyst warned. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE20000404.0342 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-04 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Turkey Determined to Continue Fighting Organized Crime </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ANKARA, April 4 (Xinhua) -- Turkey is determined to keep
intensive crackdown on organized crime and drug smuggling, a high-
ranking official said Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
Emin Arslan, chief in charge of fighting organized crime in
Turkey, made the remarks at the conference on the Struggle Against
Smuggling and Organized Crime held in Turkey's southern city of
Antalya, Turkey's Anatolia News Agency reported.
</P>
<P>
A total of 110 police chiefs from 81 provinces of the country
attended the conference. Arslan said that the organized criminal
groups have thrived in areas with authority vacuum.
</P>
<P>
He said that the police forces in Turkey did a good job in
catching criminals, but failed to eradicate the financial sources
of these organizations.
</P>
<P>
"Financial sources feed these organizations and help them grow.
We have to confiscate their financial sources in order to eradicate
them. Unfortunately, we fail to do this in Turkey," Arslan said.
</P>
<P>
The chief said that some imprisoned criminal groups' heads still
run their criminal activities by giving instructions from prisons,
adding that these people must be isolated with the outside world.
</P>
</TEXT>
