<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-04 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> U.S. Ready to Upgrade Jordan's Defense Capabilities: Cohen </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
AMMAN, April 4 (Xinhua) -- Visiting U.S. Defense Secretary
William Cohen told reporters here Tuesday that Washington is
interested in upgrading Jordan's defense capabilities while
contributing to the economic development of the kingdom.
</P>
<P>
Speaking after his meeting with Jordanian Prime Minister Abdel
Rauf Rawabdeh, Cohen said both Jordan and the United States are
working for the improvement of bilateral ties, and Washington is
ready to help Jordan upgrade its 100,000-strong armed forces.
</P>
<P>
Cohen stressed both Jordan and the U.S. believe Jordan's ability
should be upgraded to defend its own security and stability as the
kingdom takes peace and cooperation as its corner stone in its
foreign policies.
</P>
<P>
The United States provided some 300 million U.S. dollars in
various military and economic packages to Jordan in 1999 to reward
its role as a peace broker between Israel and its Arab neighbors.
Jordan signed a peace treaty with Israel in 1994, becoming the
second Arab country after Egypt to strike a peace deal with the
Jewish state.
</P>
<P>
In recent years, the U.S. provided Amman with fighter planes,
tanks, armored vehicles, anti-air missiles, night-vision equipment
and other sophisticated weapons as part of its efforts to help the
modernization drive of the Jordanian armed forces.
</P>
<P>
On his talks with Rawabdeh, Cohen said both sides agreed that
the Middle East countries should work together for a just, durable
and comprehensive peace in the region.
</P>
<P>
Cohen also briefed Jordanian officials on his talks with
Egyptian President Hosni Mubarak and Israeli Prime Minister Ehud
Barak.
</P>
<P>
He discussed with the Jordanian side the peace process
developments on the Syrian track after a summit in Geneva earlier
this month between U.S. President Bill Clinton and Syrian failed to
fix a time to resume the Syrian-Israeli peace talks, which was
derailed in January.
</P>
<P>
Cohen said Jordan and the U.S. are working together for peace
and to lay down the foundations of stability in the region, and
partnership between the U.S. and Jordan has reached an
unprecedented level over the peace process in the region.
</P>
<P>
Cohen arrived in Amman earlier in the day for a two-day visit as
part of his 12-day regional tour, which has taken him to Nigeria,
Egypt, Israel and will take him to six Gulf states over military
cooperation, bilateral ties and the peace process in the Middle
East. 
</P>
</TEXT>
