<HEADLINE> Jordanian King, U.S. Defense Secretary, Review Mideast Peace Process </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
AMMAN, April 4 (Xinhua) -- Jordanian King Abdullah Bin Hussein
on Tuesday met with visiting U.S. Defense Secretary William Cohen
over the latest developments in the Middle East peace process and
the defense needs of the kingdom.
</P>
<P>
The two sides discussed the situation in the region after a
Geneva summit earlier this month between U.S. President Bill
Clinton and Syrian President Hafez Assad failed to agree on the
resumption of the Syrian-Israeli peace talks, which was deadlocked
again in January.
</P>
<P>
During their talks, Abdullah and Cohen stressed the need for a
just, durable and comprehensive peace in the region, Jordan's
official news agency Petra reported.
</P>
<P>
Abdullah, a soldier before his acceding to the throne in
February 1999, also discussed with Cohen the military cooperation
between the two countries, Petra said.
</P>
<P>
In 1999, Washington provided some 300 million U.S. dollars in
various military and economic packages to Jordan to reward the
kingdom's role as a major peace broker in the region between Israel
and its Arab neighbors since it signed a peace treaty with Israel
in 1994.
</P>
<P>
The U.S. has also provided advanced fighter planes, tanks,
armored vehicles, anti-aircraft missiles in recent years to Jordan
to help it modernize its 100,000-strong armed forces.
</P>
<P>
During Tuesday's talks, Abdullah expressed his appreciation for
the U.S. efforts to bring all parties concerned to achieve the
required targets of the peace process under international laws and
relevant U.N. resolutions.
</P>
<P>
The monarch also expressed satisfaction over the current U.S.-
Jordanian relations in all fields.
</P>
<P>
Cohen arrived here earlier in the day for a two-day visit as
part of his 12-day regional tour, which has taken him to Nigeria,
Egypt, Israel and will take him to six Gulf states for talks on
bilateral military cooperation and the Middle East peace process.
</P>
