<HEADLINE> "Old Economy" Lifts Europe's Markets </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, April 4 (Xinhua) -- Europe's largest stocks except
London closed higher Tuesday as investors rediscovered "old
economy" is good and "new techy" is bad.
</P>
<P>
Reversing Monday's gains, London's FTSE 100 index ended 35.1
points or 0.5 percent lower at 6,427, the lowest close in four
weeks.
</P>
<P>
The biggest decliner was hand-held computer maker Psion which
slumped 18.3 percent, while Irish-based Internet security company
Baltimore Technology followed in close pursuit, dropping 16
percent.
</P>
<P>
Telecom companies didn't fare any better. Scotland's Thus fell
14 percent, while Cable &AMP; Wireless dropped 6.6 percent and the UK'
s largest telecom company BT fell 3.4 percent.
</P>
<P>
In Frankfurt, HypoVereinsbank rose 5.8 percent, insurer Allianz
rose 5.3 percent, Deutsche Bank rose 3.6 percent and its merger
partner Dresdner Bank tacked on 4.4 percent.
</P>
<P>
The Xetra Dax 30 index climbed 1.2 percent or 93.58 to 7,522.8
points.
</P>
<P>
The Paris CAC-40 index closed at 6,221.94 points, up 91.67 or 1.
5 percent. Among them, PGLE rose 4.1 percent, while PBNP gained 6.
2 percent. 
</P>
