<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-04 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Britain Cracks Down on Asylum Seekers </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, April 4 (Xinhua) -- Asylum seekers found begging in
Britain will have their claims fast tracked, the Home Office
confirmed Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
When police pick up asylum seekers for begging, immigration
officials will be contacted immediately and they will carry out an
interview as a priority.
</P>
<P>
The Home Office said asylum seekers will be given five days to
make their case before an initial decision. They will then be
given a further four weeks to appeal.
</P>
<P>
Home Secretary Jack Straw said asylum seekers should not get
involved in practices such as aggressive begging.
</P>
<P>
"I agree that we need to treat asylum seekers, founded and
unfounded, in a decent civilized way. We need to be careful about
language," the BBC quoted Straw as saying.
</P>
<P>
"But I also say that asylum seekers themselves do have a
responsibility to recognize that they are coming to a civilized
country and they have duties in terms of their own behavior," he
added.
</P>
<P>
Immigration Minister Barbara Roche revealed freight trains were
the latest route to be exploited by organized gangs of "people
smugglers."
</P>
<P>
But asylum seekers were risking death trying to enter the UK on
freight trains, highlighted by the death of two Romanians who were
electrocuted, she said.
</P>
<P>
Last year more than 800 asylum seekers were detected in railway
wagons. At least two died en route when they tried to break out of
the carriages and were electrocuted by overhead wires.
</P>
<P>
The asylum seekers mainly from Romania are smuggled aboard
trains in northern Italy. Officials said 834 people were
discovered in freight containers last year but it is estimated
that up to 2,500 illegal immigrants used the railways as a route
into the UK. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE20000404.0352 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-04 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Translator's Error Destroyed Italy's Ancient Abbey in WWII, Book Says </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ROME, April 4 (Xinhua) -- The most controversial Allied act in
the Italian campaign in World War II, the destruction of the
ancient Benedictine abbey of Montecassino south of Rome, was a
mistake due to a translator's error, according to a book about to
be published.
</P>
<P>
The book, written by Sir. Rupert Clark, the then-adjutant of
deputy Allied Forces chief General Harold Alexander, claims a
British secret service agent mistranslated an innocuous message
saying "the abbot is with the monks in the monastery."
</P>
<P>
The agent took the German word "abt," meaning abbot, to stand
for "abteilung," meaning unit.
</P>
<P>
He therefore informed his superiors that the Germans had broken
an accord with the Vatican and installed their headquarters in the
abbey, which had commanded the surrounding plain from a high hill
ever since Saint Benedict himself chose the spot in 529.
</P>
<P>
According to former adjutant Sir Rupert Clark, whose book "With
Alex At War" was amply excerpted in today's edition of the British
newspaper Guardian, the decision to send in the bombers was
quickly taken.
</P>
<P>
Clark said he heard of the tragic error from secret service
Colonel David Hunt, who asked to see the intercepted message when
the bombers had already taken off. He realized the mistake but it
was too late.
</P>
<P>
On February 15, 1944, three hours of intensive bombing reduced
one of the glories of Christendom to a pile of rubble, killing 250
people in the process.
</P>
<P>
It was the fourth time the monastery had been destroyed, after
the Lombards, Saracens and an earthquake. But this time more lives
were lost after the event than during the destruction.
</P>
<P>
The rubble afforded a perfect stronghold for the Germans to
defend. Thousands of Allied soldiers lost their lives before the
bloodied hilltop was captured three months later.
</P>
<P>
In the 1950s Montecassino Abbey was rebuilt as it once stood.
Allied governments paid for the project. It is now one of the
biggest tourist attractions between Rome and Naples. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE20000404.0353 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-04 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Germany Warns Against Far Right Violence </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>

<P>
BERLIN, April 4 (Xinhua) -- Although the political influence
of German far right organizations were shrinking, existing far
rightists and neo-nazis were more inclined to violence in the past
year, a report of the German Interior Ministry said Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
In 1999, members of German far right parties and organizations
dropped by 2,200 from the year before to 51,400, but the number of
"skinheads," the most violent and dangerous section of the far-
right extremists, grew by 10 percent to 9,000, the annual report
of the German Constitution Protection Office said.
</P>
<P>
"I have to project that the number of violence-intending far
right extremists will be stable at a high level, in correspondence
with a higher violent tendency of far right extremist scenes,"
said German Interior Minister Otto Schily at a press conference
presenting the report.
</P>
<P>
There were 746 cases of far right violent offenses, a 5.4-
percent increase against 1998, while the total cases of far right
offenses dropped by 9.2 per cent, according to the report.
</P>
<P>
"Yet, they cannot organize any terrorist structure, nor have
they any political concept of an armed war against the state,"
said Schily.
</P>
<P>
"The far right organizations again and again advocated
violence, weapons were again and again found in their scenes, but
many people think this can only lead to more pressure of the state
and make their political work harder -- clearly they have lost the
power to convince."
</P>
<P>
As a proof, far right political parties were losing voters
although they played some media show-offs, and some parties were
splitting, said the minister.
</P>
<P>
The German People Union (DVU), the strongest far right
political party with 17,000 members, is weakening in internal
quarrels after it entered the Brandenburg state parliament last
year.
</P>
<P>
Another extremist party, the Republicans, failed to collect 5
percent of vote to enter a parliament in any local election in
1999.
</P>
<P>
But, both the report and the minister noted that far right
organization were deploying popular media, such as pop bands ,
music CD, and Internet, to attract younger followers.
</P>
<P>
The report said, there were 93 so-called "skinhead bands,"
which played 109 "skinhead concerts" and published "skinhead music
CDs" in 1999, and in Internet, the number of "skinhead music" in
popular MP3 format, was rising.
</P>
<P>
"That makes them (the far right organizations) so dangerous,"
stressed Schily, adding that although the authorities had carried
out "numerous searches and confiscations," these activities
remained at high level.
</P>
<P>
The far right organizations were eager deploying Internet as
their propaganda channel, said the report, quoting there were more
than 330 far right extremist homepages in the World Wide Web (WWW)
while in 1998 the number was only 200.
</P>
<P>
In the wake of stricter German laws, most of these homepages
use north American web sites.
</P>
<P>
The German government has invited other countries to together
take "internationally effective steps against illegal and harmful
contents in Internet," said Shily.
</P>
<P>
Germany and some influential U.S. organizations are pressing U.
S. Internet providers to delete extremist homepages on their site,
he said, adding that "authorities are paying a lot of time to find
out those responsible for the contents."
</P>
<P>
"The far right extremism is a phenomenon for us to fight
against in federal wide, the federal government will further
support states' measures to fight against far right extremism,"
vowed the minister. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE20000404.0354 </DOCNO>
