<HEADLINE> West African Gas Pipeline Officials Stress Environment Protection </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LAGOS, April 4 (Xinhua) -- Officials of the trans-national West
African Gas Pipeline project pledged on Tuesday that they would
take comprehensive environmental considerations when carrying out
the project.
</P>
<P>
Pan African News Agency quoted the officials as saying in
Ghana's capital Accra that it would be one of the worst things
governments would do to render millions of people vulnerable to
known and unknown environmental defects.
</P>
<P>
The project's public affairs manager, Esther Cobbah, of the
Togolese Environmental Protection Agency, said that some
precedents of environmental discrepancies with similar projects
was persuasive enough for the governments to prevent such
disasters.
</P>
<P>
Stressing the importance of the project, she said it was
impossible to achieve energy security if the countries concerned
let natural gas continue to be flared in Nigeria while resorting
to buy expensive fuel from outside the sub-region.
</P>
<P>
"What we need now is for all of us in Ghana, Nigeria, Togo and
Benin to unite to see this project come to pass for our own
benefit and that of our children," she stressed.
</P>
<P>
The project, designed to transmit natural gas from Nigeria to
Benin, Ghana, and Togo, is a key element in the energy common pool
regime in the Economic Community of West African States. 
</P>
</TEXT>
