<HEADLINE> Polenz Nominated German CDU General Secretary </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BERLIN, April 4 (Xinhua) -- A new face emerged in the leading
circle of the German opposite Christian Democratic Union (CDU)
when Ruprecht Polenz was formally nominated as the party's general
secretary Tuesday evening here.
</P>
<P>
Polenz, 53 and a legislator in the German parliament Bundestag,
will be recommended to the CDU federal congress next week to
replace Angela Merkel, who is set to be elected party leader.
</P>
<P>
At a CDU presidium meeting, Merkel chose Polenz to the key
post for party management. Under the CDU party rule, Merkel has
the power to nominate the general secretary.
</P>
<P>
The nomination won "favorable support" from the party
presidium, Merkel told a press conference after the meeting.
</P>
<P>
"He will take the challenge to make the CDU a great middle
party of people," said Merkel. "His previous experiences show that
he understands the modern form of communication."
</P>
<P>
Polenz, who called his new job "hard and full of challenge,"
said he would bring "inner-party democracy" to the conservative
CDU, and would make the party "powerful" before the general
election in 2002.
</P>
<P>
"The CDU must turns its ears to the people," he said.
</P>
<P>
Polenz was born in Saxonia and moved to the western German
city of Muenster with his family. He worked 14 years as a lawyer
with the Muenster Chamber of Commerce and Industry.
</P>
<P>
In 1994 he was elected to the Bundestag as a CDU liberal
winger, and has been responsible for the foreign and security
policy of the CDU parliamentary section.
</P>
<P>
The media and CDU officials depicted Polenz as "hard-working,
serious and talented." His top job is to settle the party finance,
they said.
</P>
<P>
The CDU faces debts of up to 100 million marks, based on old
debts of 25 million marks and adding tens of millions of fines
linked to Kohl's illegal funding scandal. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
