<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Tung Chee Hwa Hails Visit to Canada Success </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Toronto, April 4 (Xinhua) -- Tung Chee Hwa, chief executive of
the Hong Kong Special Administrative Region (HKSAR) of China, said
here Tuesday that he has made "a wonderful visit" to Canada, which
he believes will refocus its attention in Asia.
</P>
<P>
"I must say I had a wonderful visit, a very warm welcome.
Discussion with the prime minister was very useful and productive.
</P>
<P>
"I also had opportunity to see the finance minister and the
foreign minister," Tung told reporters about his first visit to
Canada in the capacity as the chief executive of the HKSAR.
</P>
<P>
"In our discussions, we noticed the prospects of China's
joining WTO" and Hong Kong's economic recovery, he said.
</P>
<P>
The two sides also noticed "that with the recovery of the Asian
economy, it is time Canadian companies should refocus attention in
Asia. There will be great deal opportunities out there," he said
confidently.
</P>
<P>
About 100 Canadian companies have branches or subsidiary
operations in Hong Kong, with another 450 being represented by
distibutors, agents or joint ventures in the region.
</P>
<P>
Hong Kong is the 13th largest export market for Canada, which,
in turn, is Hong Kong's 11th importer.
</P>
<P>
Earlier in the day, Tung told more than 900 guests at a
business luncheon in the Metro Toronto Convention Center that Hong
Kong's Commission for Strategic Development is planning to make
the city with a status comparable to that of Toronto, New York and
London.
</P>
<P>
In doing so, one of the priorities for Hong Kong is to seek
cooperation in developing clean transport, where "Canada looks to
have some of the most promising technology," according to Tung.
</P>
<P>
"I look forward to that developing rapidly," he said.
</P>
<P>
Tung identified a number of other areas he believes Hong Kong
should look to "places like Canada" for ideas and inspiration,
including education for a knowledge-based economy and the sewage
and waste disposal.
</P>
<P>
He reaffirmed that China's "one country, two systems" policy
has been transformed from a concept into an every reality and is
working well in Hong Kong, which has "a very ambitious program
over the next five to 10 years to achieve a standard comparable to
other cities in the world."
</P>
<P>
"If you wish to expand in Asia, please think of Hong Kong," he
told the Canadian Club of Toronto, the Hong Kong-Canada Business
Association and Hong Kong Toronto Development Council, which
jointly hosted the business luncheon.
</P>
<P>
Tung arrived here Saturday to begin a four-day visit to Canada.
He said he would take with him "a very happy memory" of Canada.
</P>
<P>
Tung Chee Hwa is scheduled to leave for the United States
Wednesday to continue his visit. 
</P>
</TEXT>
