<HEADLINE> Nasdaq Regains Ground After Plunging 574 Points </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NEW YORK, April 4 (Xinhua) -- The technology heavy Nasdaq
composite index Tuesday regained ground after plunging 574 points
on rules against Microsoft in an antitrust case.
</P>
<P>
The composite closed down 74.79 at 4,148.89, topping on its
loss of 349.15 points Monday.
</P>
<P>
Broader stock indicators were also lower. The Dow Jones
industrial average fell 57.09 at 11,164.84 and the Standard &AMP; Poor
's 500 index fell 11.24 at 1,494.73.
</P>
<P>
The Nasdaq index plunged as investors became pessimistic about
the future of technology stocks after U.S. District Judge Thomas
Penfield Jackson ruled Monday that Microsoft Corp. has repeatedly
violated antitrust laws. The index lost 574.57 points early in the
session Tuesday before recovering.
</P>
<P>
At its lowest level Tuesday, the Nasdaq was 27 percent below
its record closing high of 5,058.62 set March 10. A drop of 20
percent is defined as a bear market on Wall Street but market
analysts were reluctant to declare that.
</P>
<P>
Investors rushed in the market for bargain-hunting before the
market closed, which rescued the index from a crash. The Nasdaq
recorded a 634 point swing in trading Tuesday, the biggest ever in
its history.
</P>
<P>
The Nasdaq's steep drop also spurred a big selloff in the
broader market. The Dow Index fell as mush as 503 points from an
early 196 point rise and then regained ground. The 700.46-point
swing from high to low was the biggest on record for the Dow.
</P>
<P>
The NYSE index fell 7.36 at 652.30 and the American Stock
Exchange index fell 35.48 at 942.52. The Russell 2000 index of
smaller companies fell 9.90 at 506.12.
</P>
<P>
Declining issues outnumbered advancers by a nearly 2-to-1
margin on the New York Stock Exchange, with 1,065 up, 2,038 down
and 381 unchanged.
</P>
<P>
NYSE volume increased to 1.5 billion shares from 1.02 billion
in the previous session. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE20000404.0360 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-04 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Cardoso Reiterates Support for "One China" Policy </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SAN JOSE, April 4 (Xinhua) -- Visiting Brazilian President
Fernando Henrique Cardoso reiterated Tuesday here his support of
the policy of "only one China" when he was asked on the aspiration
of certain Taiwan sectors to promote this island's independence.
</P>
<P>
Cardoso emphasized Brazil has "a very clear stance. We
recognize China's aspiration to the existence of only one China
and all of our policy goes in line with this concept."
</P>
<P>
Cardoso said this at a press conference here in company of his
Costa Rican counterpart, Miguel Angel Rodriguez, upon ending a
bilateral meeting.
</P>
<P>
"My vision of Brazil's relations with China in the 21st century
is very simple and direct: 'Brazil considers China as a strategic
partner, with which we have best relations,'" said Cardoso.
</P>
<P>
Brazil's President arrived Monday night in Costa Rica to attend
Tuesday a bilateral meeting with President Rodriguez and Wednesday
he'll meet the rest of Central America's presidents and Panama's,
as well as Belize's prime minister and the Dominican Republic's
foreign minister.
</P>
<P>
"Recently I spoke to President Miguel Angel Rodriguez about a
satellite we launched jointly, a Sino-Brazilian satellite.
Actually, there are four satellites, two of which were built in
Brazil and another two in China, but both with technological
exchange," he added.
</P>
<P>
"So we have a very positive vision as regards collaborating
with China, not only in rhetorical terms, but also in very
practical terms," he said.
</P>
<P>
"Likewise, Brazil has been very favorable for the incorporating
of China to the World Trade Organization," he indicated.
</P>
<P>
"We have lots to develop in common," said Brazil's president. "
China has enormous weight, not only in Asia, but also in the rest
of the world. Brazil recognizes this weight, and is very
interested in the rapprochement that already exists and which will
grow."  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
